ont-size: small\">Connected to www.ixdba.net (221.130.192.57).</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Escape character is\'^]\'.</span></span> </div><div> <b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">get</span></span></b> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">&lt;! DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;- / / IETF / / DTD HTML 2.0 / / EN&quot;&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">&lt;html&gt; &lt;head&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">&lt;title&gt; 501 Method Not Implemented &lt;/ title&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">&lt;/ Head&gt; &lt;body&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">&lt;h1&gt; Method Not Implemented &lt;/ h1&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">&lt;p&gt; get to / index.html not supported. &lt;br /&gt;</span></span></div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">&lt;/ P&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">&lt;hr&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">&lt;address&gt; Apache/2.2.4 (Unix) PHP/5.2.3 mod_fastcgi/2.4.2 Resin/3.1.3 Server at www.ixdba.net Port 80 &lt;/ address&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">&lt;/ Body&gt; &lt;/ html&gt;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Connection closed by foreign host.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"># When we entered &quot;telnet www.ixdba.net 80&quot; Then, if &quot;www.ixdba.net&quot; corresponds to port 80 is open ip the case, will give a welcome message similar to &quot;Escape character is\'^]\'&quot;, At this point we entered through the keyboard, &quot;get&quot; command will display the corresponding application port 80 server type, for example, port 80 in this case the corresponding application services for the apache and php and resin combinations.</span></span> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','telnet commandFunction Description: The telnet protocol communications with the remote host or remote host to obtain the information corresponding to the port. Telnet under windows complete with the same function.Using the format: telnet host name or ip address portFor example:1. Log in via telnet...'),(54,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0803/392.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance-traceroute command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenancetraceroute_command','2010-08-03','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' (Editor: South African Ant)...'),(55,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0729/375.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance-scp command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenancescp_command','2010-07-29','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">scp command</span></span></b> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Function: scp is the secure copy, the file or directory from one linux to another linux system copy system. scp to transfer data using the ssh protocol to ensure security of data transmission.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: scp username @ ip address of the remote: the absolute path to the local file system path linux</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">scp remote file path local linux system user name @ ip address: the absolute path name of the remote system file</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Supplement: scp linux using the format first, the remote system copy of a file or directory to the local linux system up, use the format the second is a local copy of a file or directory to a remote linux system a path.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">For example:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">1. Currently we are in the ip as &quot;192.168.60.133&quot; in the linux system, under this system plan / home / ixdba / etc.tar.gz files to the ip is &quot;192.168.60.168&quot; remote linux system root user under The / tmp directory, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # scp <font color=\"#0000ff\">/</font> home / ixdba / etc.tar.gz <font color=\"#0000ff\">root@192.168.60.168:</font> / <font color=\"#0000ff\">tmp</font></span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Command input is completed, will be asked to enter &quot;192.168.60.168&quot; server root password, and then start the remote copy of data.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">If now we are in &quot;192.168.60.168&quot; server, you can also transfer data using the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ OracleDB ~] # scp <font color=\"#0000ff\"><a href=\"mailto:root@192.168.60.133:/home/ixdba/etc.tar.gz\">root@192.168.60.133: / Home / ixdba / etc.tar.gz</a> / tmp</font></span></span> </div><div></div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Command input is completed at this time will be asked to enter &quot;192.168.60.133&quot; server root password, and then start the remote copy of data.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">2. The local / etc directory, copy all the files and subdirectories ip is &quot;192.168.60.135&quot; remote linux system root user under the / opt directory, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # scp-r <font color=\"#0000ff\">/ etc root@192.168.60.135:</font> / <font color=\"#0000ff\">opt</font></span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Here option &quot;r&quot; and the cp command &quot;r&quot; option has the same meaning.</span></span> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','scp commandFunction: scp is the secure copy, the file or directory from one linux to another linux system copy system. scp to transfer data using the ssh protocol to ensure security of data transmission.Using the format: scp username @ ip address of the remote: the absolute path to the local file...'),(56,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0729/374.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance-ifconfig command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenanceifconfig_command','2010-07-29','0000-00-00 00:00:00','script><table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">ifconfig command</span></span></b> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Function: Configure the network or network interface displays the current status. Similar to the ipconfig command under windows, but ifconfig command must be root user to execute.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: ifconfig [options] [interface] [inet | up | down | netmask | addr | broadcast]</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Option Description: See detailed table</span></span> </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"67\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Options</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"501\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Meaning</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"67\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-A</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"501\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Show all network interfaces, including active and inactive.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"67\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-S</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"501\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Show only summary data for each interface is active on the interface, each interface to display a line of information.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"67\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-V</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"501\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">If a network interface error, will return error messages to help find and out of trouble.</span></span> </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">interface: network interface name, linux network interface under the name similar to eth0, eth1, lo, etc., represent the first piece of card, the second card, the loopback interface. This is optional, if you do not add this option, all of the card display system information is displayed if you add this option to specify the card information.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">up: to activate a network interface.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">down: and up the opposite, so that the specified network interface is invalid.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">netmask: To specify a subnet mask of the specified network interface.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">addr: where &quot;addr&quot; is specified for the network interface IP address.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">broadcast: the interface settings for the specified broadcast address.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">For example:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">1. Displays the current system all network interface information, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # ifconfig</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">eth0 Link encap: Ethernet HWaddr 00:13:72:40: C5: F1</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">inet addr: 192.168.60.13 Bcast: 192.168.60.255 Mask: 255.255.255.0</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">inet6 addr: fe80:: 213:72 ff: fe40: c5f1/64 Scope: Link</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">UP BROADCAST RUNNING MULTICAST MTU: 1500 Metric: 1</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">RX packets: 154657999 errors: 0 dropped: 0 overruns: 0 frame: 0</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">TX packets: 194872221 errors: 0 dropped: 0 overruns: 0 carrier: 0</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">collisions: 0 txqueuelen: 1000</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">RX bytes: 1700497213 (1.5 GiB) TX bytes: 1917599211 (1.7 GiB)</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Interrupt: 201</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">lo Link encap: Local Loopback</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">inet addr: 127.0.0.1 Mask: 255.0.0.0</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">inet6 addr::: 1 / 128 Scope: Host</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">UP LOOPBACK RUNNING MTU: 16436 Metric: 1</span></span> </div><div><span style=\"font-size: small\">y:</span> Arial &quot;&gt; <span style=\"font-size: small\">RX packets:</span> 336372975 <span style=\"font-size: small\">errors: 0 dropped: 0 overruns: 0 frame: 0</span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">TX packets: 336372975 errors: 0 dropped: 0 overruns: 0 carrier: 0</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">collisions: 0 txqueuelen: 0</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">RX bytes: 2956943107 (2.7 GiB) TX bytes: 2956943107 (2.7 GiB)</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">From the above we see that:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">First line: display connection type is Ethernet (Ethernet), HWaddr that the hardware MAC address.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Second row: turn display network card ip address, broadcast address, subnet mask.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">The third line: ipv6 address configuration information, because we do not use ipv6 address, so there is no ip address shown.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Fourth line: &quot;UP&quot; on behalf of card turned on, &quot;RUNNING&quot; card on behalf of the network cable is connected, &quot;MULTICAST&quot; on behalf of support for multicast, &quot;MTU: 1500&quot; that the maximum transmission unit of 1500 bytes.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">The fifth, sixth line: show the card to receive and send data packet statistics.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Eighth row: shows the card to receive and send data bytes in statistics.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">2. Configure the network card eth0 the two ip addresses were 192.168.60.136,192.168.66.138 a subnet mask of 255.255.255.254, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # ifconfig eth0 192.168.60.136 netmask 255.255.255.254</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # ifconfig eth0: 0 192.168.66.138 netmask 255.255.255.254</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># At this point with the ifconfig command, you can see two network card information, and are &quot;eth0&quot; and &quot;eth0: 0&quot; If you want this time to add the eth0 ip address, then the card name followed by &quot;eth0 : 1, eth0: 2 ... ... &quot;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">3. NIC\'s MAC address changes for the new MAC address, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # ifconfig eth0 hw ether xx: xx: xx: xx: xx: xx</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Where &quot;xx: xx: xx: xx: xx: xx&quot; for the new MAC address, then use ifconfig eth0 view information, MAC address has been changed.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">4. Disable and then enable the network card eth0, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # ifconfig eth0 down</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ oracledb ~] # ifconfig eth0 up</span></span> </div><p> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Special attention, with the ifconfig command to configure the network card information, the network card restart or reboot your machine, all configuration is effective, and if the network card configuration to make a permanent effect, you need to modify the network card configuration file.</span></span> </p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','ifconfig commandFunction: Configure the network or network interface displays the current status. Similar to the ipconfig command under windows, but ifconfig command must be root user to execute.Using the format: ifconfig [options] [interface] [inet | up | down | netmask | addr | broadcast]Option...'),(57,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0729/373.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance -mount/umount command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenance_mountumount_command','2010-07-29','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">mount / umount command</span></span></b> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Function: mount and unload the specified file system. In the third chapter we have described over mount / umount command, where more in-depth about the mount / umount of use.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: mount [options] [-L &lt;label&gt;] [-o &lt;option&gt;] [-t &lt;the file system type&gt;] [device name] [mount point]</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">umount [mount point]</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Option meaning: the meaning of more options see the table below</span></span> </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Options</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Meaning</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-A</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Load the file / etc / fstab to specify all the equipment.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-N</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Not to load the information recorded in the / etc / mtab file</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-R</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Read-only load the equipment.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-W</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Read-write mode loading device, is mount the default settings.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-F or-v</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Not loaded equipment, mount the mount only view state.</span></span> </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-L &lt;label&gt;: the disk partition ID tag is actually an alias, the label can be easily named, it is easy to remember, in the linux partition under the name of the device more difficult to remember, the use of labels instead of device name, easy to remember.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-O &lt;option&gt;: Specify the option to load the file system, these options include:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">async: asynchronous manner to perform file input and output actions.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">atime: access is updated every inode access time, the default settings, cancel the option noatime.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">auto: must be in / etc / fstab file to specify this option. Implementation-a option, set to auto load the equipment, de-select the noauto.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">dev: readable characters on the file system or block device, cancel the option to nodev.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">exec: executable binary files, cancel the option noexec. <br /> noatime: do not update when the inode access time access time. <br /> noauto: adding this option, you can not use the-a option to load. <br /> nodev: do not read the characters on the file system or block device. <br /> noexec: can not execute binary file. <br /> nosuid: close the set-user-identifier (set user ID) and set-group-identifer (set group ID) bit set. <br /> nouser: the user can not perform the load operation, the default settings.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">iocharset = XXX mount partition using the specified character set.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">codepage = XXX mount partition using the specified code page. <br /> remount: re-loading equipment. Usually used to change the device settings state. <br /> ro: read-only mode loading. <br /> rw: read-write mode loading. <br /> suid: start set-user-identifier (set user ID) and set-group-identifer (set group ID) bit, to cancel options nosuid. <br /> sync: synchronous manner to the file system input and output actions. <br /> user: general users can load equipment.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">defaults: use the default option. The default option is rw, suid, dev, exec, anto nouser and async.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-T &lt;file system type&gt;: Specify the device file system type, commonly used options are:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">ext3/ext2: Linux file system now commonly used. <br /> msdos: MS-DOS\'s FAT. <br /> vfat: Win85/98 of VFAT. <br /> nfs: Network File System. <br /> iso9660: CD-ROM CD-ROM file system standard. <br /> ntfs: Windows NT file system.</span></span> </div><div><span style=\"font-size: small\">Device Name: linux partition on the hard disk device identification, similar to / dev/sda1, / dev/hda2 and so on.</span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Mount point: linux system to a specified directory.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">For example:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">1. CD-ROM image file to mount the linux system:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ localhost /] # mount-o loop-t iso9660 / iso/RHEL4-U4-i386-AS-disc1.iso / ixdba</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># In the windows need to access the virtual CD-ROM ISO image file such third-party software, and in the linux system disc image file can be achieved by mounting the read.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Here, &quot;loop&quot; option that the hard disk partition as an image file attached to the system, &quot;-t&quot; specifies the type of image file to iso9660, that is, the standard CD-ROM file system. &quot;/ Iso/RHEL4-U4-i386-AS-disc1.iso&quot; said the image file path, &quot;/ ixdba&quot; said the mount point, after the success can be mounted / ixdba directory to access the content of the image file.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">2. windows + linux dual system of co-existence environment, the D drive under windows to linux mount under / mnt / d directory, and supports Chinese, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ localhost /] # mount-t vfat-o codepage = 936, iocharset = cp936 / dev/hda3 / mnt / d</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># The above display, &quot;-t vfat&quot; option that is needed to mount the D drive fat file system format, &quot;- o&quot; option specifies the partition behind the mount support for the Chinese after the show, &quot;/ dev/hda3&quot; is under the D drive in windows under linux hardware ID, &quot;/ mnt / d&quot; is the linux system on the specified mount point, mount success can access under linux / mnt / d to access the windows directory under the D drive content.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">3. Linux system on a way to read-only linux system to mount another partition on the shared out, that is our future to in-depth about the network filesystem (NFS) file system, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div align=\"left\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ localhost /] # mount-t nfs-o ro 192.168.60.133: / home / ixdba / mnt / nfs</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># The above command, &quot;-t nfs&quot; mount the specified file system type is nfs, &quot;-o ro&quot; means read-only mount specified, &quot;192.168.60.133: / home / ixdba&quot; said the ip address of &quot;192.168 .60.133 &quot;one another linux system, / home / ixdba directory shared out,&quot; / mnt / nfs &quot;is specified in the local mount point on linux system.</span></span> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','mount / umount commandFunction: mount and unload the specified file system. In the third chapter we have described over mount / umount command, where more in-depth about the mount / umount of use.Using the format: mount [options] [-L <label>] [-o <option>] [-t <the file system type>] [device name]...'),(58,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0728/372.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Sometimes, in fact, Linux is really very fragile','Sometimes_in_fact_Linux_is_really_very_fragile','2010-07-28','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> linux system in their design, great flexibility, the simple and the kernel will be able to interact with a command to complete the commissioning work. </p><p> Here are some commands can be used in special environment, but do not practice in the production server, here to share your reference! </p><p></p><p> # Restart your computer <br /> echo &quot;b&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Turn off the computer immediately <br /> echo &quot;o&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Export the <span class=\"t_tag\" href=\"tag.php?name=%C4%DA%B4%E6\" onclick=\"tagshow(event)\">memory</span> allocation information (can use / var / log / message view) <br /> echo &quot;m&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Export the current CPU registers and flag bits of information <br /> echo &quot;p&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Export the thread state information <br /> echo &quot;t&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Deliberately <span class=\"t_tag\" href=\"tag.php?name=%CF%B5%CD%B3\" onclick=\"tagshow(event)\">crash</span> <br /> echo &quot;c&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Immediately re-mount all <span class=\"t_tag\" href=\"tag.php?name=%CE%C4%BC%FE\" onclick=\"tagshow(event)\">file</span> systems <br /> echo &quot;s&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger <br /> # Immediately re-mount all the file system is read-only <br /> echo &quot;u&quot;&gt; / proc / sysrq-trigger </p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' linux system in their design, great flexibility, the simple and the kernel will be able to interact with a command to complete the commissioning work.  Here are some commands can be used in special environment, but do not practice in the production server, here to share your reference!  # Restart...'),(59,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0727/371.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance of the-fsck command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenance_of_thefsck_command','2010-07-27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"><b>Ã‚Â </b> <b>fsck command</b></span></span> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Function: Check the file system and try to fix errors.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: fsck [options] [-t &lt;the file system type&gt;] [device name]</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Option Description: See detailed table</span></span> </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Options</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Meaning</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-A</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Automatically fix file system without any prompts.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-R</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Take interactive repair mode, for questioning in the implementation of repair, allowing users to identify and determine treatment.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-A</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">According to / etc / fstab configuration file contents, check all the documents listed in the file system.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-T</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Perform fsck command does not display the header information.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-V</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Fsck command displays the execution process.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"91\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-N</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"477\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Not executing instructions, list only the practical implementation of the action will be conducted.</span></span> </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-T &lt;file system type&gt;: Specify the file system type to check.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Note: Before performing fsck command to repair a file system, this corresponds to the file system disk partition must be in the unloaded state, the disk partition mounted under repair is extremely unsafe, the data may have been damaged, there may be damaged disk.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">For example:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Check and try to fix the problem of the disk partition / dev/sda10, when asked in the implementation of repair, allowing users to identify and determine treatment, showing in detail the repair process, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ localhost /] # fsck-rV-t ext3 / dev/sda10</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">fsck 1.39 (29-May-2006)</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[/ Sbin/fsck.ext3 (1) - / dev/sda10] fsck.ext3-r / dev/sda10</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">e2fsck 1.39 (29-May-2006)</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Opt contains a file system with errors, check forced.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Pass 1: Checking inodes, blocks, and sizes</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Pass 2: Checking directory structure</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Pass 3: Checking directory connectivity</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Pass 4: Checking reference counts</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Inode 6121 ref count is 2, should be 1. Fix &lt;y&gt;? Yes</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Unattached inode 6122</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Connect to / lost + found &lt;y&gt;?</span></span>yes </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Inode 6122 ref count is 2, should be 1. Fix &lt;y&gt;? Yes</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Pass 5: Checking group summary information</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Block bitmap differences: - (519 - 529) -9273</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Fix &lt;y&gt;? Yes</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">... ... ... ...</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Opt: ***** FILE SYSTEM WAS MODIFIED *****</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Opt: 19/128520 files (15.8% non-contiguous), 46034/514048 blocks</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># It can be seen from above, fsck to repair the file system is called the time / sbin/fsck.ext3 command, fsck repair through a five step inspection, repair center if found necessary, will prompt the user whether to fix, according to &quot;y&quot; key to repair, press any other key to skip the repair.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">When the fsck command is executed, fsck if we find there is no file system dependent file or directory, will prompt the user whether they get it back, because no file system dependent file or directory is invisible to users, and also can not be used by the file system is generally a result of internal structural damage, if you agree to retrieve, but also the input even if it says &quot;y&quot; key, fsck command will these orphaned files or directories into the lost + found directory and use these files corresponds to their own i-node number to name for users to find their own lost files, lost + found literal meaning is lost back.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">So when the user in the use of fsck command to repair the disk partitions, if found to partition a file is missing, can go to the corresponding lost + found directory to find, because this time has been unable to tell by the file name file, we can use the file command file system type, and then determine which documents we need.</span></span> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','Ã‚Â  fsck commandFunction: Check the file system and try to fix errors.Using the format: fsck [options] [-t <the file system type>] [device name]Option Description: See detailed tableOptionsMeaning-AAutomatically fix file system without any prompts.-RTake interactive repair mode, for questioning in...'),(60,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0727/370.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance-df command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenancedf_command','2010-07-27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">df command</span></span></b> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Function: used to check the linux system disk space occupancy.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: df [options]</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Option Description: See the following table details</span></span> </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Options</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Meaning</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-H</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Easy to understand format to the output file system partition occupancy, such as 32k, 120M, 60G.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-K</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">K units of output to the size of the file system partition occupancy.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-M</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">M units of output to the size of the file system partition occupancy.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-A</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Lists all file system partition that contains the file system partition 0 size.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-I</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Inodes file system partition list information.</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"79\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-T</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"489\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Display disk partition file system type.</span></span> </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">For example:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">1. View the current system partition, and to display the file system type, user-friendly output, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ web1 ~] # df-hT</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Filesystem Type Size Used Avail Use% Mounted on</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sda2 ext3 15G 603M 14G 5% /</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sda1 ext3 99M 14M 81M 14% / boot</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sda7 ext3 96G 19G 72G 21% / cicro</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">none tmpfs 2.0G 0 2.0G 0% / dev / shm</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sda3 ext3 9.7G 3.3G 5.9G 36% / usr</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sda6 ext3 7.7G 243M 7.1G 4% / var</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sdf6 ocfs2 951G 77G 875G 9% / webdata</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">The output can be seen from the above, each of the total size of the file system partition, have been used size, remaining size, the percentage of occupancy, etc., can also be seen, the above system uses the ext3, tmpfs, ocfs2 three types of file system .</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">On the concept of file system, we have described in detail later chapters.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">2. Inodes file system information output, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ web1 ~] # df-ihT</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Filesystem Type Inodes IUsed IFree IUse% Mounted on</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">/ Dev/sda2 ext3 1.9M 8.8K 1.9M 1% /</span></span> </span&gt; </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">/ Dev/sda1 ext3 26K 38 26K 1% / boot</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">/ Dev/sda7 ext3 13M 41K 13M 1% / cicro</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">none tmpfs 496K 1 496K 1% / dev / shm</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">/ Dev/sda3 ext3 1.3M 156K 1.1M 13% / usr</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">/ Dev/sda6 ext3 1003K 3.3K 999K 1% / var</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">/ Dev/sdf6 ocfs2 30M 2.4M 28M 9% / webdata</span></span> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','df commandFunction: used to check the linux system disk space occupancy.Using the format: df [options]Option Description: See the following table detailsOptionsMeaning-HEasy to understand format to the output file system partition occupancy, such as 32k, 120M, 60G.-KK units of output to the size of...'),(61,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0727/369.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance-cpio command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenancecpio_command','2010-07-27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Function: cpio command is the way by redirecting the package file backup, restore, recovery tool, which can extract to &quot;. Cpio&quot; or &quot;. Tar&quot; at the end of the file.</span></span> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: cpio [Options]&gt; the file name or device name</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">cpio [options] &lt;file name or device name</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Option Description: Detailed description of options see the table below</span></span> </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"55\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Options</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"513\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Meaning</span></span> </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"55\"><div align=\"center\"> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-O</span></span> </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"513\"><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Copy files packaged into the 