ace=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Oracle 10g + Redhat5, all the normal installation, install the user oracle. <br /><br /><br /><br /> Sqlplus oracle user to start today with the normal <br /> [Abc @ rhel4 admin] $ sqlplus / as sysdba <br /> SQL * Plus: Release 10.2.0.1.0 - Production on Thu Apr 23 12:11:25 2009 <br /> Copyright (c) 1982, 2005, Oracle. All rights reserved. <br /><br /> Connected to: <br /> Oracle Database 10g Enterprise Edition Release 10.2.0.1.0 - Production <br /> With the Partitioning, OLAP and Data Mining options <br /> SQL&gt; <br /><br /> However, the listener starts when the error was: <br /> [Abc @ rhel4 admin] $ lsnrctl <br /> LSNRCTL for Linux: Version 10.2.0.1.0 - Production on 23-APR-2009 12:13:06 <br /> Copyright (c) 1991, 2005, Oracle. All rights reserved. <br /> Welcome to LSNRCTL, type &quot;help&quot; for information. <br /><br /> <strong><font color=\"#ff0000\">LSNRCTL&gt; start</font></strong> <br /> Starting / u01/app/oracle/product/10.2.0/bin/tnslsnr: please wait ... <br /><br /> TNSLSNR for Linux: Version 10.2.0.1.0 - Production <br /> System parameter file is / u01/app/oracle/product/10.2.0/network/admin/listener.ora <br /> Log messages written to / u01/app/oracle/product/10.2.0/network/log/listener.log <br /> Listening on: (DESCRIPTION = (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = tcp) (HOST = localhost.localdomain) (PORT = 1521))) <br /> Error listening on: (DESCRIPTION = (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = IPC) (KEY = EXTPROC1))) <br /> <strong><font color=\"#ff0000\">TNS-12555: TNS: permission denied <br /> TNS-12560: TNS: protocol adapter error <br /> TNS-00525: Insufficient privilege for operation <br /> Linux Error: 1: Operation not permitted</font></strong> <br /><br /><br /><br /> Through the log <u><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net/a/mz/\">the error</a></u> message shows, it should be related with the permissions, and finally found a hidden message <br /><br /> <font color=\"#ff6600\"><strong>/ Var / tmp / .oracle this directory is rather special, if the oracle no authority to operate this directory, then, oracle user can not access / var / tmp / .oracle folder.</strong></font> <br /><br /> Is simple, do: chmod 777 / var / tmp / .oracle <br /><br /> After ok.</font> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','Oracle 10g + Redhat5, all the normal installation, install the user oracle.  Sqlplus oracle user to start today with the normal  [Abc @ rhel4 admin] $ sqlplus / as sysdba  SQL * Plus: Release 10.2.0.1.0 - Production on Thu Apr 23 12:11:25 2009  Copyright (c) 1982, 2005, Oracle. All rights reserved. ...'),(112,'Oracle','Database','en','/a/db/oracle/2010/0422/20.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Used to solve data dblink oracle snapshot','Used_to_solve_data_dblink_oracle_snapshot','2010-04-22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> This example has been fully tested, one-way, two-way synchronization can be used. </p><p> - Terms Description: Source - are synchronized <u><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net/a/db/\">database</a></u> <br /> Objective - To synchronize to the database </p><p> Step 6 must be performed before, 6 after some auxiliary information. </p><p> - 1, the destination database, create a dblink <br /> drop public database link dblink_orc92_182; <br /> Create public DATABASE LINK dblink_orc92_182 CONNECT TO bst114 IDENTIFIED BY password USING\'\'orc92_192.168.254.111\'\'; <br /> - Dblink_orc92_182 is dblink_name <br /> - Bst114 is the username <br /> - Password is the password <br /> -\'\'Orc92_192.168.254.111\'\'is the name of the remote database </p><p><br /> - 2, in the source and destination to be synchronized to create a database table (preferably with a primary key constraint, the snapshot can quickly refresh) <br /> drop table test_user; <br /> create table test_user (id number (10) primary key, name varchar2 (12), age number (3)); </p><p> - 3, in the destination database, test dblink <br /> Select * from <a href=\"mailto:test_user@dblink_orc92_182\">test_user @ dblink_orc92_182</a> ; / / query the source database table <br /> select * from test_user; </p><p> - 4, in the source database, create a snapshot log table to be synchronized <br /> Create snapshot log on test_user; </p><p> - 5 to create a snapshot, the snapshot is created on the destination database <br /> Create as Select * from Snapshot sn_test_user <a href=\"mailto:test_user@dblink_orc92_182\">test_user @ dblink_orc92_182</a> ; </p><p> - 6, set the refresh time snapshot (can choose only one way to refresh, fast refresh is recommended, so that it can trigger two-way synchronization) <br /> Fast refresh <br /> Alter snapshot sn_test_user refresh fast Start with sysdate next sysdate with primary key; <br /> - Oracle automatic fast refresh immediately, after constantly refreshed, only in test use. Real project to properly weigh the refresh time. </p><p> Complete refresh <br /> Alter snapshot sn_test_user refresh complete Start with sysdate +30 / 24 * 60 * 60 next sysdate +30 / 24 * 60 * 60; <br /> - Oracle automatically in 30 seconds after the first complete refresh, after a full refresh every 30 seconds </p><p> - 7, manually refresh the snapshot, in the case does not automatically refresh, you can manually refresh the snapshot. <br /> Manual refresh mode 1 <br /> begin <br /> dbms_refresh.refresh (\'\'sn_test_user\'\'); <br /> end; </p><p> Manual refresh mode 2 <br /> EXEC DBMS_SNAPSHOT.REFRESH (\'\'sn_test_user\'\',\'\' F\'\'); / / The first parameter is the snapshot name, the second parameter is a fast refresh F C is completely refreshed. </p><p> - 8. To modify the session time format <br /> ALTER SESSION SET NLS_DATE_FORMAT =\'\'YYYY-MM-DD HH24: MI: SS\'\'; </p><p> - 9. See the last refresh time snapshot <br /> SELECT NAME, LAST_REFRESH FROM ALL_SNAPSHOT_REFRESH_TIMES; </p><p> - 10. See a snapshot of the next execution time <br /> select last_date, next_date, what from user_jobs order by next_date; </p><p> - 11. Print debugging information <br /> dbms_output.put_line (\'\'use\'\'||\'\' plsql\'\'); </p><p> - 12. If you want one-way synchronization, then the destination database, create the following trigger (when the source database table changes, the purpose of the database table along with change, but the purpose of the database table changes, the source database table does not change). <br /> create or replace trigger TRI_test_user_AFR <br /> after insert or update or delete on sn_test_user <br /> for each row <br /> begin <br /> if deleting then <br /> delete from test_user where id =: old.id; <br /> end if; <br /> if inserting then <br /> insert into test_user (id, name) <br /> values (: new.id,: new.name); <br /> end if; <br /> if updating then <br /> update test_user set name =: new.name where id =: old.id; <br /> end if; <br /> end TRI_test_user_AFR; </p><p> - 13. If you want two-way synchronization, the implementation in the source database before step 6, and both create the following trigger (when the source database table changes, the purpose of the database table changes with the purpose of the database table changes, the source database Table has changed) <br /> CREATE OR REPLACE TRIGGER BST114.TRI_TEST_USER_AFR <br /> AFTER DELETE OR INSERT OR UPDATE <br /> ON BST114.SN_TEST_USER <br /> REFERENCING NEW AS NEW OLD AS OLD <br /> FOR EACH ROW <br /> declare <br /> tmp_id number (10): =- 1; <br /> begin </p><p> dbms_output.put_line (\'\'begin\'\'); <br /> if inserting then <br /> - Select id into tmp_id from test_user where id =: new.id; <br /> for p in (select id from test_user where id =: new.id) <br /> loop <br /> tmp_id: = p.id; <br /> end loop; <br /><br /> dbms_output.put_line (tmp_id ||\'\'===------------\'\'); <br /> if (tmp_id =- 1) then <br /> insert into test_user (id, name, age) <br /> values (: new.id,: new.name,: new.age); <br /> end if; <br /> end if; <br /><br /> if updating then <br /> dbms_output.put_line (\'\'updated\'\'); <br /> for p in (select name, age from test_user where id =: old.id) <br /> loop <br /> if (p.name! =: new.name) or (p.age! =: new.age) then <br /> update test_user set name =: new.name, age =: new.age where id =: old.id; <br /> end if; <br /> end loop; <br /> end if; <br /><br /> if deleting then <br /> dbms_output.put_line (\'\'deleted\'\'); <br /> delete from test_user where id =: old.id; <br /> end if; <br /> dbms_output.put_line (\'\'end\'\'); <br /> end TRI_test_user_AFR; <br /> - To prevent two-way synchronization trigger an infinite loop, so to increase the number of judgments in the trigger to stop the endless loop. </p><p> - The above synchronization principle <br /> 1. First create a dblink, can access the remote database <br /> 2. To create a snapshot of local, remote data mapping table, when the remote table has changed, it will respond to the snapshot. <br /> 3. As a snapshot view of the table is similar, so create a local trigger for the snapshot, the snapshot when there are changes, it will trigger the corresponding event. <br /> 4. To write a trigger to synchronize data in the code. </p><p> - Attachment: Snapshot refresh time parameter that day, the number of seconds = 24 hours * 60 minutes * 60 note so in order to refresh after 30 seconds, the parameter should be written like sysdate +30 / (24 * 60 * 60) <br /> 1 minute == sysdate +60 / (24 * 60 * 60) </p><p> The number of minutes a day = 24 hours * 60 minutes <br/&gt; A minute can also write sysdate +1 / (24 * 60) <br /> 30 minutes == sysdate +30 / (24 * 60) <br /> 60 minutes == sysdate +60 / (24 * 60) </p><p> So <br /> 1 hour == sysdate +1 / 24 == sysdate +60 / (24 * 60) <br /> 1 day == sysdate +1 <br /> Month == sysdate +30 </p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' This example has been fully tested, one-way, two-way synchronization can be used.  - Terms Description: Source - are synchronized database Objective - To synchronize to the database  Step 6 must be performed before, 6 after some auxiliary information.  - 1, the destination database, create a dblink...'),(113,'Mysql','Database','en','/a/db/mysql/2010/0422/49.html','http://www.ixdba.net','How to set MySQL Sync (mysql dual hot','How_to_set_MySQL_Sync_mysql_dual_hot','2010-04-22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> MySQL provides <u><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net/a/db/\">database</a></u> synchronization features, which we implemented <u><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net/a/db/\">the database</a></u> of redundant disaster, backup, restore, load balancing, etc. are of great help. This paper describes a common method of synchronization settings. </p><p> Synchronization in two forms: </p><p> &quot;Master - slave&quot;, and &quot;Lord - Lord.&quot; </p><p> A: &quot;Lord - from the&quot; way </p><p> 1, for the server </p><p> Between the different versions of MySQL (the binary log) binlog format may be different, so the best combinations is the Master of the MySQL version and the version of the same or lower Slave, Master\'s version will definitely not be higher than Slave version. </p><p> In this paper, we assume that the primary server (hereinafter referred to as Master) and from the server (hereinafter referred to as the Slave) version is 4.1.24, the operating system is Redhat Linux AS4.0 </p><p> Suppose </p><p> Sync Master is the host ip: 192.168.60.219, Slave host ip is: 192.168.60.132,2 a MySQL the basedir directory is / usr / local / mysql, datadir is: / usr / local / mysql / data (is the mysql database default data directory). </p><p> 2, set the synchronization server </p><p> (1), set the Sync Master </p><p> Each synchronization server must be set to a unique number, or can not properly run simultaneously. Then sync profile configuration database, mysql database, the default configuration file called my.cnf, start the database when the data directory from the default my.cnf read the information, if not the next data file, you can create a, my . cnf Default template generally mysql / support-files directory, this directory has a variety of situations cnf files, such as my-huge.cnf, my-large.cnf, my-medium.cnf, my-small . cnf, etc., under the circumstances, to choose my-medium.cnf can then copy it to data, the renamed my.cnf. began to modify the my.cnf, add the following lines: </p><p> log-bin </p><p> server-id = 1 (identified as the master database) </p><p> sql-bin-update-same </p><p> binlog-ignore-db = mysql </p><p> set-variable = binlog-ignore-db = mysql # specify the database log </p><p> Then add an account in the Master devoted to synchronization, as follows: </p><p> MySQL&gt; GRANT REPLICATION SLAVE ON *.* TO <a href=\"mailto:backup@192.168.60.132\">backup@192.168.60.132</a> IDENTIFIED BY \'1234 \'; </p><p> If you want to have permission to do Slave &quot;LOAD TABLE FROM MASTER&quot; or &quot;LOAD DATA FROM MASTER&quot; statement, it must grant the global FILE and SELECT permissions: </p><p> MySQL&gt; GRANT FILE, SELECT, REPLICATION SLAVE ON *.* TO <a href=\"mailto:backup@192.168.60.132\">backup@192.168.60.132</a> IDENTIFIED BY \'1234 \'; </p><p> Above the fourth line in the my.cnf file that does not record the mysql database update log, which avoids the permissions settings on the Master are synchronized to the Slave, if there is no restriction in this regard, can not set this parameter. </p><p> The last set to complete my.cnf, setting is completed, first check the mysql / data directory if mysql start off at values similar to *. info, localhost *, ib * and the like on the value of information. If you have deleted, then the master server, start the mysql. You can view the data files under the localhost.localdomain.err, test the connectivity of the master in the Slave. At the same time with the show slave status to see synchronous configuration. </p><p> Then back up the data on the Master, the first execute the following SQL statement: </p><p> mysql&gt; FLUSH TABLES WITH READ LOCK; </p><p> Do not exit the terminal, otherwise the lock is not in force; and then export the data, compressed data files can be packaged directly, or you can use the mysqldump tool to do, recommend the former approach, so much more quick and easy. </p><p> root $ cd / usr / local / mysql </p><p> root $ tar zcf data.tar.gz. / data (where it may be &quot;var&quot;, and other practical storage of data files, according to the truth may be) </p><p> Then copy the data to the Slave server, unlock, set the correct permissions and owner, etc., start the Slave database, then &quot;UNLOCK TABLES&quot; statement to release the lock. Then close the database. </p><p> (2), set the Slave </p><p> As with the primary database to find the my.cnf template, repair to as my.cnf, add the following lines: </p><p> server-id = 2 (Slave server ID) </p><p> master-host = 192.168.60.219 # master server name </p><p> master-user = backup # sync account name, the default is to test </p><p> master-password = 1234 # sync account password, default is empty </p><p> master-port = 3306 # master server TCP / IP port number, default is 3306 </p><p> set-variable = replicate-ignore-db = mysql # skip the synchronization of the database name, if there are multiple, set times </p><p> set-variable = replicate-do-db = cicro # want to synchronize the database name, if you have more than one, set many times. </p><p> master-connect-retry = 10 default retry interval of 60 seconds </p><p> After setting, first check the mysql / data directory if mysql start off at values similar to *. info, localhost *, ib * and the like on the value of information. If you have deleted, then the Slave server, start mysql, then test it on the Slave whether connected to the Master on the right, and have the appropriate permissions. </p><p> You can view the data under the localhost.localdomain.err file, test the connectivity of Slave and master. </p><p> root $ mysql-h192.168.60.219-ubackup-p 1234 </p><p> mysql&gt; SHOW GRANTS; </p><p> +------------------------------------------------- -------------------------------------------------- -----------------------------------+ </p><p> | Grants for <a href=\"mailto:backup@192.168.60.132\">backup@192.168.60.132</a> | </p><p> +------------------------------------------------- -------------------------------------------------- -----------------------------------+ </p><p> | GRANT SELECT, FILE, REPLICATION SLAVE ON *.* TO <a href=\"mailto:&apos;backup&apos;@&apos;192.168.60.132&apos;\">\'Backup\' @ \'192 .168.60.132 \'</a> IDENTIFIED BY PASSWORD \'* 9FF2C222F44C7BBA5CC7E3BE8573AA4E1776278C\' | </p><p> +------------------------------------------------- -------------------------------------------------- -----------------------------------+ </p><p> Now, restart the Slave. After the successful launch, log Slave, check synchronization status: </p><p> mysql-hlocalhost-uroot </p><p> mysql&gt; SHOW SLAVE STATUS \\ G </p><p> *************************** 1. Row ******************** ******* </p><p> Slave_IO_State: Waiting for master to send event </p><p> Master_Host: 192.168.60.132 </p><p> Master_User: backup </p><p> Master_Port: 3306 </p><p> Connect_Retry: 10 </p><p> Master_Log_File: localhost-bin.000002 </p><p> Read_Master_Log_Pos: 1556 </p><p> Relay_Log_File: localhost-relay-bin.000004 </p><p> Relay_Log_Pos: 51 </p><p> Relay_Master_Log_File: localhost-bin.000002 </p><p> Slave_IO_Running: Yes </p><p> Slave_SQL_Running: Yes </p><p> Replicate_Do_DB: cicro, cicro </p><p> Replicate_Ignore_DB: </p><p> Replicate_Do_Table: </p><p> Replicate_Ignore_Table: </p><p> Replicate_Wild_Do_Table: </p><p> Replicate_Wild_Ignore_Table: </p><p> Last_Errno: 0 </p><p> Last_Error: </p><p> Skip_Counter: 0 </p><p> Exec_Master_Log_Pos: 1556 </p><p> Relay_Log_Space: 51 </p><p> Until_Condition: None </p><p> Until_Log_File: </p><p> Until_Log_Pos: 0 </p><p> Master_SSL_Allowed: No </p><p> Master_SSL_CA_File: </p><p> Master_SSL_CA_Path: </p><p> Master_SSL_Cert: </p><p> Master_SSL_Cipher: </p><p> Master_SSL_Key: </p><p> Seconds_Behind_Master: 0 </p><p> 1 row in set (0.00 sec) </p><p> You can see, Slave_IO_Running and Slave_SQL_Running two values are for the &quot;Yes&quot;, indicating that the Slave I / O and SQL threads are running. </p><p> So far, the main - from the synchronization settings successfully. </p><p> Second: &quot;Lord - the Lord&quot; means: </p><p> If you add in the master slave settings, add the Slave master set, became the &quot;main - the main&quot; synchronization mode. </p><p> 1: Configuring master server </p><p> Then the above configuration, the master\'s my.cnf add the configuration information: </p><p> master-host = 192.168.60.132 </p><p> master-user = backup </p><p> master-password = 1234 </p><p> replicate-do-db = cicro </p><p> master-connect-retry = 10 default retry interval of 60 seconds </p><p> 2: Configure slave server: </p><p> First, add an account in the slave devoted to synchronization, as follows: </p><p> MySQL&gt; GRANT FILE, SELECT, REPLICATION SLAVE ON *.* TO <a href=\"mailto:backup@192.168.60.219\">backup@192.168.60.219</a> IDENTIFIED BY \'1234 \'; </p><p> My.cnf in the slave\'s configuration file, add the following information: </p><p> binlog-do-db = cicro </p><p> Note: When there is an error check the data directory slave *. err log file. Thread synchronization time out, when the synchronization mechanism to correct errors to make work, run the slave start. </p><p> Similarly, first remove the two servers log information under the data, followed by start slave, master. Implement Dual Active. </p><p> Test: </p><p> Large data to the slave scale bulk insert AA (1872000) Ordinance, master database can update the 2500 data per second. <br /></p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' MySQL provides database synchronization features, which we implemented the database of redundant disaster, backup, restore, load balancing, etc. are of great help. This paper describes a common method of synchronization settings.  Synchronization in two forms:  \"Master - slave\", and \"Lord - Lord.\" ...'),(114,'Oracle','Database','en','/a/db/oracle/2010/0423/63.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle database to write TO_DATE format','Oracle_database_to_write_TO_DATE_format','2010-04-23','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> TO_DATE format (time :2007 -11-02 13:45:25 example) <br /><br /> Year: <br /> yy two digits show the value of two years: 07 <br /> yyy three digits show the value of three years: 007 <br /> yyyy four digits show the value of four years: 2007 <br /><br /> Month: <br /> mm number two on display: 11 <br /> mon abbreviated character set display: 11 months, if the English version, showing nov <br /> month spelled out character set display: 11 months, if the English version, show november <br /><br /> Day: <br /> dd number the first few days show the value of the month: 02 <br /> ddd number then display the first few days: 02 <br /> dy abbreviated days of the week the first short display: Friday, if the English version, show fri <br /> day spelled out the first days of the week in full display: Friday, if the English version, show friday <br /> ddspth spelled out, ordinal twelfth <br /><br /> Hour: <br /> hh two digits 12 Ã¥Â°ÂÃ¦Â—Â¶ hex display: 01 <br /> hh24 two digits 24 Ã¥Â°ÂÃ¦Â—Â¶ hexadecimal display: 13 <br /><br /> Minute: <br /> mi two digits 60 hexadecimal display: 45 <br /><br /> Second: <br /> ss two digits 60 hexadecimal display: 25 <br /><br /> Other Q digit quarter showed the value: 4 <br /> WW digit year display the first few weeks: 44 <br /> W digit month of the first few weeks, the displayed value: 1 <br /><br /> 24-hour format time range: 0:00:00 - 23:59:59 .... <br /> 12-hour format time range: 1:00:00 - 12:59:59 .... <br /><br /> 1. Date and character conversion function usage (to_date, to_char) <br /><br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\') as nowTime from dual; / / date into a string <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy\') as nowYear from dual; / / get the time of <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'mm\') as nowMonth from dual; / / get the monthly time <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'dd\') as nowDay from dual; / / Get the daily time <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'hh24\') as nowHour from dual; / / obtain the time when <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'mi\') as nowMinute from dual; / / Get the sub-time <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'ss\') as nowSecond from dual; / / Get time in seconds <br /> select to_date (\'2004-05-07 13:23:44 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\') from dual / / </p><p> 2. <br /> select to_char (to_date (222, \'J\'), \'Jsp\') from dual <br /><br /> Display Two Hundred Twenty-Two </p><p> 3. Seeking one day of the week <br /> select to_char (to_date (\'2002-08-26 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \'),\' day \') from dual; <br /> Monday <br /> select to_char (to_date (\'2002-08-26 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \'),\' day \',\' NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE = American \') from dual; <br /> monday <br /> Set the date language <br /> ALTER SESSION SET NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE = \'AMERICAN\'; <br /> The same can be <br /> TO_DATE (\'2002-08-26 \',\' YYYY-mm-dd \',\' NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE = American \') </p><p> 4. The number of days between two dates <br /> select floor (sysdate - to_date (\'20020405 \',\' yyyymmdd \')) from dual; </p><p> 5. Time for the use of null <br /> select id, active_date from table1 <br /> UNION <br /> select 1, TO_DATE (null) from dual; <br /><br /> Note that to use TO_DATE (null) </p><p> 6. Months difference <br /> a_date between to_date (\'20011201 \',\' yyyymmdd \') and to_date (\'20011231\', \'yyyymmdd\') <br /> So at 12:00 on December 31 and December 1 after a 12-point is not included in the prior within this range. <br /> So, when the time requires precise, I felt to_char still necessary <br /> 7. Date format conflict <br /> Enter the format depends on your character set installed on the type of ORACLE, such as: US7ASCII, date format, type is: \'01-Jan-01 \' <br /> alter system set NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE = American <br /> alter session set NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE = American <br /> Or write in to_date <br /> select to_char (to_date (\'2002-08-26 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \'),\' day \',\' NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE = American \') from dual; <br /> Note me to cite only NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE, of course, there are many, <br /> To see <br /> select * from nls_session_parameters <br /> select * from V $ NLS_PARAMETERS </p><p> 8. <br /> select count (*) <br /> from (select rownum-1 rnum <br /> from all_objects <br /> where rownum &lt;= to_date (\'2002-02-28 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \') - to_date (\'2002- <br /> 02-01 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \') +1 <br /> ) <br /> where to_char (to_date (\'2002-02-01 \';, \'Yyyy-mm-dd\') + rnum-1, \'D\') <br /> not in (\'1 \', \'7\') <br /><br /> 2002-02-28 to 2002-02-01 Find and seven except Monday between the number of days <br /> In the before and after the call DBMS_UTILITY.GET_TIME, so that after subtracting the results (get is 1 / 100 seconds, not milliseconds). </p><p> 9. Find the month <br /> select months_between (to_date (\'01-31-1999 \',\' MM-DD-YYYY \'), to_date (\'12-31-1998\', \'MM-DD-YYYY\')) &quot;MONTHS&quot; FROM DUAL; <br /> 1 <br /> select months_between (to_date (\'02-01-1999 \',\' MM-DD-YYYY \'), to_date (\'12-31-1998\', \'MM-DD-YYYY\')) &quot;MONTHS&quot; FROM DUAL; <br /> 1.03225806451613 <br /><br /> 10. Next_day usage <br /> Next_day (date, day) <br /><br /> Monday-Sunday, for format code DAY <br /> Mon-Sun, for format code DY <br /> 1-7, for format code D </p><p> 11 <br /> select to_char (sysdate, \'hh: mi: ss\') TIME from all_objects <br /> Note: The first record of the TIME and the last line is the same <br /> Can create a function to deal with this problem <br /> create or replace function sys_date return date is <br /> begin <br /> return sysdate; <br /> end; <br /><br /> select to_char (sys_date, \'hh: mi: ss\') from all_objects; <br /><br /> 12. To obtain the number of hours <br /> extract () to find a date or interval value of the field values SELECT EXTRACT (HOUR FROM TIMESTAMP \'2001-02-16 2:38:40 \') from offer <br /> SQL&gt; select sysdate, to_char (sysdate, \'hh\') from dual; <br /><br /> SYSDATE TO_CHAR (SYSDATE, \'HH\') <br /> -------------------- --------------------- <br /> 2003-10-13 19:35:21 07 <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select sysdate, to_char (sysdate, \'hh24\') from dual; <br /><br /> SYSDATE TO_CHAR (SYSDATE, \'HH24\') <br /> -------------------- ----------------------- <br /> 2003-10-13 19:35:21 19 </p><p><br /> 13. Years at treatment <br /> select older_date, <br /> newer_date, <br /> years, <br /> months, <br /> abs ( <br /> trunc ( <br /> newer_date- <br /> add_months (older_date, years * 12 + months) <br /> ) <br /> ) Days <br /><br /> from (select <br /> trunc (months_between (newer_date, older_date) / 12) YEARS, <br /> mod (trunc (months_between (newer_date, older_date)), 12) MONTHS, <br /> newer_date, <br /> older_date <br /> from ( <br /> select hiredate older_date, add_months (hiredate, rownum) + rownum newer_date <br /> from emp <br /> ) <br /> ) </p><p> 14. Dealing with uncertain number of days in the month approaches <br /> select to_char (add_months (last_day (sysdate) +1, -2), \'yyyymmdd\'), last_day (sysdate) from dual </p><p> 16. To find out the number of days this year <br /> select add_months (trunc (sysdate, \'year\'), 12) - trunc (sysdate, \'year\') from dual </p><p> Treatment of leap year <br /> to_char (last_day (to_date (\'02 \'| |: year,\' mmyyyy \')),\' dd \') <br /> If it is not a leap year 28 </p><p> 17.yyyy the difference with the rrrr <br /> \'YYYY99 TO_C <br /> ------- ---- <br /> yyyy 99 0099 <br /> rrrr 99 1999 <br /> yyyy 01 0001 <br /> rrrr 01 2001 </p><p> 18. Do not deal with time zones <br /> select to_char (NEW_TIME (sysdate, \'GMT\', \'EST\'), \'dd / mm / yyyy hh: mi: ss\'), sysdate <br /> from dual; </p><p> An interval of 19.5 seconds <br /> Select TO_DATE (FLOOR (TO_CHAR (sysdate, \'SSSSS\') / 300) * 300, \'SSSSS\'), TO_CHAR (sysdate, \'SSSSS\') <br /> from dual </p><p> 2002-11-1 9:55:00 35786 <br /> SSSSS that 5 seconds </p><p> 20. The first few days a year <br /> select TO_CHAR (SYSDATE, \'DDD\'), sysdate from dual <br /><br /> 3102002-11-6 10:03:51 </p><p> 21. Calculate hours, minutes, seconds, milliseconds <br /> select <br /> Days, <br /> A, <br /> TRUNC (A * 24) Hours, <br /> TRUNC (A * 24 * 60 - 60 * TRUNC (A * 24)) Minutes, <br /> TRUNC (A * 24 * 60 * 60 - 60 * TRUNC (A * 24 * 60)) Seconds, <br /> TRUNC (A * 24 * 60 * 60 * 100 - 100 * TRUNC (A * 24 * 60 * 60)) mSeconds <br /> from <br /> ( <br /> select <br /> trunc (sysdate) Days, <br /> sysdate - trunc (sysdate) A <br /> from dual <br /> ) </p><p><br /> select * from tabname <br /> order by decode (mode, \'FIFO\', 1, -1) * to_char (rq, \'yyyymmddhh24miss\'); <br /><br /> / / <br /> floor ((date2-date1) / 365) as in <br /> floor ((date2-date1, 365) / 30) as the month <br /> d (mod (date2-date1, 365), 30) as a day. </p><p> 23.next_day function returns a date next week, day or Sunday for the 1-7 - Saturday, 1 Sunday next_day (sysdate, 6) is from the current start of the next Friday. Behind the numbers begin to run from Sunday. <br /> 1234567 <br /> Day one hundred twenty-three thousand four hundred fifty-six <br /><br /> --------------------------------------------------------------- <br /><br /> select (sysdate-to_date (\'2003-12-03 12:55:45 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\')) * 24 * 60 * 60 from ddual <br /> Date of return to the days and then converted to ss <br /><br /> 24, round [rounded to the nearest date] (day: rounding to the nearest Sunday) <br /> select sysdate S1, <br /> round (sysdate) S2, <br /> round (sysdate, \'year\') YEAR, <br /> round (sysdate, \'month\') MONTH, <br /> round (sysdate, \'day\') DAY from dual </p><p> 25, trunc [truncated to the nearest date, in days], returns a date type select sysdate S1, <br /> trunc (sysdate) S2, / / returns the current date, not when every second trunc (sysdate, \'year\') YEAR, / / returns the current year on January 1, no, hour, trunc (sysdate, \'month\') MONTH, / / Returns the current month 1, minutes and seconds when no trunc (sysdate, \'day\') DAY / / Return the current week Sunday, when the minutes and seconds from dual non- </p><p> 26, the latest date of return to date list of select greatest (\'01-1 Ã¦ÂœÂˆ -04 \', \'04-January -04\', \'10-February -04 \') from dual </p><p> 27. Calculate the time difference Note: oracle time difference is the number of days as a unit, so the conversion into years, Japan <br /> select floor (to_number (sysdate-to_date (\'2007-11-02 15:55:03 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\')) / 365) as spanYears from dual / / time difference - in select ceil (moths_between (sysdate-to_date (\'2007-11-02 15:55:03 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'))) as spanMonths from dual / / time difference - on select floor (to_number (sysdate -to_date (\'2007-11-02 15:55:03 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss \'))) as spanDays from dual / / time difference - days select floor (to_number (sysdate-to_date (\' 2007-11-02 15:55:03 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\')) * 24) as spanHours from dual / / time difference - when the select floor (to_number (sysdate-to_date (\'2007- 11-02 15:55:03 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\')) * 24 * 60) as spanMinutes from dual / / time difference - sub-select floor (to_number (sysdate-to_date (\'2007- 11-02 15:55:03 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\')) * 24 * 60 * 60) as spanSeconds from dual / / time difference - seconds </p><p> 28. Updated Note: oracle time of addition and subtraction is the number of days as a unit, change the amount set n, so the conversion into years, at select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'), to_char (sysdate + n * 365, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\') as newTime from dual / / change the time - on select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'), add_months (sysdate , n) as newTime from dual / / change the time - on select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'), to_char (sysdate + n, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\' ) as newTime from dual / / change the time - at select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'), to_char (sysdate + n/24, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\' ) as newTime from dual / / change the time - when the select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'), to_char (sysdate + n/24/60,\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss \') as newTime from dual / / change time - sub-select to_char (sysdate,\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss \'), to_char (sysdate + n/24/60/60,\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\') as newTime from dual / / change the time - seconds </p><p> 29. Find the first day of the month, last day of the SELECT Trunc (Trunc (SYSDATE, \'MONTH\') - 1, \'MONTH\') First_Day_Last_Month, <br /> Trunc (SYSDATE, \'MONTH\') - 1 / 86400 Last_Day_Last_Month, <br /> Trunc (SYSDATE, \'MONTH\') First_Day_Cur_Month, <br /> LAST_DAY (Trunc (SYSDATE, \'MONTH\')) + 1 - 1 / 86400 Last_Day_Cur_Month <br /> FROM dual; <br /></p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' TO_DATE format (time :2007 -11-02 13:45:25 example)  Year:  yy two digits show the value of two years: 07  yyy three digits show the value of three years: 007  yyyy four digits show the value of four years: 2007  Month:  mm number two on display: 11  mon abbreviated character set display: 11...'),(115,'Oracle','Database','en','/a/db/oracle/2010/0422/17.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle DB Link get two steps using two','Oracle_DB_Link_get_two_steps_using_two','2010-04-22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> 1, the target to create Oracle DB Link: <br /> A, in the network / admin / tnsname.ora file to add the source database connection information, such as: <br /> AAA = <br /> (DESCRIPTION = <br /> (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = TCP) (HOST = 10.5.1.3) (PORT = 1521)) <br /> (CONNECT_DATA = <br /> (SERVER = DEDICATED) <br /> (SERVICE_NAME = AAA) <br /> ) <br /> ) <br /> B, the target machine using sqlplus user / pwd login. <br /> C, with the following command to create DB Link: <br /> create public database link AAA_LINK connect to user identified by pwd using \'AAA\'; <br /> Command Description: <br /> CREATE PUBLIC DATABASE LINK <u><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net/a/db/\">database</a></u> link name CONNECT TO username IDENTIFIED BY password USING \'local configuration data instance name\'; <br /> If successfully established, it will prompt: Database link created. </p><p> 2, use the following script, you can synchronize data table: <br /> #! / Bin / sh <br /> # To sync table A to BBB database from AAA database <br /> sqlplus <a href=\"mailto:user/pwd@BBB\">User / pwd @ BBB</a> &lt;&lt;EOF # Here is the BBB\'s database instance name and password there, follow the practical situation <br /> truncate table A; <br /> insert into A <br /> Select * from <a href=\"mailto:b_schema.A@AAA_LINK\">b_schema.A @ AAA_LINK</a> ; # This is the point source to synchronize the table, the table name must be &lt;table owner&gt;. &lt;table name&gt; @ &lt;dblink name&gt; <br /> commit; </p><p> PS: need DB support for Advanced replication capabilities, whether to support, available as SQL view: <br /> select * from v $ option where PARAMETER = \'Advanced replication\'; returns True if it is to support. </p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' 1, the target to create Oracle DB Link:  A, in the network / admin / tnsname.ora file to add the source database connection information, such as:  AAA =  (DESCRIPTION =  (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = TCP) (HOST = 10.5.1.3) (PORT = 1521))  (CONNECT_DATA =  (SERVER = DEDICATED)  (SERVICE_NAME = AAA)  )  ) ...'),(116,'Oracle','Database','en','/a/db/oracle/2010/0422/18.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle of some basic knowledge but easily confused','oracle_of_some_basic_knowledge_but_easily_confused','2010-04-22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> 1. A table space belongs to only one database. </p><p> 2. Each database at least one control file (recommendation 3, on separate disk). </p><p> 3. Each database at least one tablespace (SYSTEM tablespace). </p><p> 4. To establish the purpose of SYSTEM table space is the same as the destination table stored together in order to improve efficiency, only the data dictionary should be kept. </p><p> 5. Each database at least two online log groups, each with at least one online log file. </p><p> 6. A data file can only belong to a table space. </p><p> 7. Once a data file is added to a table space, you can not remove from the table space, could no longer be added to other table space. </p><p> 8. To create a new table space needs to create a new data file. </p><p> 9. Data files are formatted as ORACLE ORACLE block, Oracle9i previous versions, ORACLE block size is in the first set when creating a database. </p><p> 10. And can not be changed later, to change, can only rebuild the database. </p><p> 11. A segment belongs to only one section of the table space, but can belong to multiple data files. </p><p> 12. A zone data file belongs to only one extent, the range (extent) can not span data files. </p><p> 13.PCTFREE and PCTUSED sum not greater than or equal 100. </p><p> 14. A single transaction can span multiple rollback segments. </p><p> 15. Index table without ROWID value. </p><p> 16. Rollback segments with different sizes without any benefit. </p><p> 17.COMMIT, the data do not immediately write disk (data files). </p><p> 18. Even if a transaction is not submitted, will be written to the redo log. </p><p> 19.Oracle 8.0.4, in the initial installation of the default created when the database instance named ORCL. </p><p> 20. A block of the maximum length of 16KB (with 2K, 4K, 8K, 16K). </p><p> Maximum number of files per database (by block size) </p><p> 20000 block of 2K files </p><p> 4K block of 40,000 files </p><p> 8K or more blocks of 65,536 files </p><p> 21.oracle server can start multiple databases. </p><p> 22. A set of operating system you can install multiple versions of the ORACLE database system (UNIX can, NT can not.) </p><p> 23. An ORACLE database system can have multiple ORACLE database and its corresponding instance. </p><p> 24. Every ORACLE database has a database instance (INSTANCE) (OPS excluded). </p><p> 25. Therefore, an operating system at the same time can have multiple oracle database instance start. </p> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>',' 1. A table space belongs to only one database.  2. Each database at least one control file (recommendation 3, on separate disk).  3. Each database at least one tablespace (SYSTEM tablespace).  4. To establish the purpose of SYSTEM table space is the same as the destination table stored together in...'),(117,'Oracle','Database','en','/a/db/oracle/2010/0422/19.html','http://www.ixdba.net',' This article discusses the...','_This_article_discusses_the','2010-04-22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> This article discusses the parameters involved are: <br /> log_archive_dest <br /> log_archive_dest_n <br /> log_archive_start <br /> db_recovery_file_dest <br /> Oracle version: <br /> SQL&gt; select * from v $ version; </p><p> BANNER </p><p> -------------------------------------------------- ------------------------------ </p><p> Oracle Database 10g Enterprise Edition Release 10.2.0.2.0 - Prod <br /> PL / SQL Release 10.2.0.2.0 - Production <br /> CORE 10.2.0.2.0 Production <br /> TNS for Solaris: Version 10.2.0.2.0 - Production <br /> NLSRTL Version 10.2.0.2.0 - Production </p><p> Oracle 10g Enterprise Edition to </p><p> SQL&gt; show parameter spfile <br /> NAME TYPE VALUE <br /> ----------------------------------- --------------- ------- ------------------------------ </p><p> spfile string / export / home / oracledb / oracle / p roduct/10.2.0/dbs/spfileorcl.ora </p><p> Using a spfile parameters. </p><p><br /> SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_dest_1 = \'location = / export / home / arch\'; </p><p> System altered. </p><p></p><p> SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_dest_1 =\'\'; # set to empty, no location message. </p><p> System altered. </p><p></p><p> SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_dest = \'/ export / home / arch\'; </p><p> alter system set log_archive_dest = \'