 0pt\">=</span> dedicated or</span> server <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">=</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">shared. <br /><br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">Details, see:</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"><br /> <span style=\"COLOR: black; TEXT-DECORATION: none; text-underline: none\">http://download-west.oracle.com/ ... nproc.htm # sthref630</span></span> </p>',' Difference between the concept and  -------------------------------------------------- -------------  Sharing model for a similar connection pool concept, but the practical application of the effect is not very good, did not know there is no improvement in 10g ...'),(215,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/a6/1990.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle DBA, UNIX Pocket Reference manual document management','Oracle_DBA_UNIX_Pocket_Reference_manual_document_management','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1. Lists the most recent move over (touched) files as a DBA, you often need to view the file as a recent passive. When the Oracle files are read or write when he is too passive. ls command to see which file is the last passive before. Note that using the output to limit the number of head, only recently moving off the output file (default 10) <br /> $ Ls-alt | head <br /> total 29837 <br /> -Rw ------- 1 afis system 592 Oct 10 10:12. Sh_history <br /> -Rw-r - r - 1 afis system 75 Oct 10 10:08 errlog.txt <br /> -Rwxr-xr-x 1 afis system 1467 Oct 9 09:48. Profile <br /> drwxr-x - x 11 afis system 8192 Oct 8 13:21. <br /> drwxr-xr-x 2 afis system 8192 Sep 26 13:21 unixsvr20060925 <br /> drwxr-xr-x 2 afis system 8192 Sep 25 16:59 unixsvr20060921 <br /> -Rw-r - r - 1 afis system 15 Sep 22 16:52 logfile.txt <br /> -Rw ------- 1 afis system 15 Sep 22 15:15 nohup.out <br /> -Rw-r - r - 1 afis system 506 Sep 22 11:32. Dxhanziim780.tmp <br /> -L option displays details of the file, including the modification time,-t option to make the results sorted according to the passive-off date, but the time is still displayed in the modification time. -T will follow a passive sort down over time, hence the head. -A option displays all the files in your directory. <br /> 2. Show recently modified files <br /> $ Ls-alc | tail <br /> total 3 <br /> -Rw-r - r - 1 afis system 2 Oct 10 10:34 1.txt <br /> -Rw-r - r - 1 afis system 2 Oct 10 10:35 2.txt <br /> -Rw-r - r - 1 afis system 2 Oct 10 10:35 3.txt <br /> 3. Delete the file unmodified, for example, to delete more than 5 days unmodified archive: <br /> / Usr / bin / find $ DBA / $ ORACLE_SID / arch / arch_prod *. arc-ctime +5-exec rm {} \\ <br /> Note that when testing the above command should be careful. We would also check whether the path does exist. <br /> 4. Displays the file size (512 byte blocks) <br /> Sometimes we need to quickly find a larger trace or core dump files. By using the du command to display the file size, the unit is 512 bytes. If you want to kb to show, you can use the-k parameter <br /> # Du-s * | sort-n | tail <br /> 31288 archlog269.arc.Z <br /> 34000 archlog253.arc.Z <br /> 34480 archlog256.arc.Z <br /> 35464 archlog252.arc.Z <br /> 36696 archlog255.arc.Z <br /> 37400 archlog258.arc.Z <br /> 37456 archlog263.arc.Z <br /> 38576 archlog270.arc.Z</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">39248 archlog267.arc.Z <br /> 102408 archlog272.arc.Z <br /> If we want to see the total size of a directory, you can use du-sk command. For example, <br /> # Du-sk / home / oracle <br /> 2353 <br /> 5. Locate the file that contains a specific string by using find and grep commands to find files containing specific strings in the file. For example, suppose you want to check the script file containing the v $ session. You can execute the following command, Unix will be in your current directory and all subdirectories in the file extension is the sql to find: <br /> HBZW&gt; find.-Name &quot;*. sql&quot;-print | xargs grep-iv \\ $ session <br /> . / Script / test.sql: select * from v $ session; <br /> The following is the interpretation of this command: <br /> find. <br /> In the current directory and all subdirectories to find <br /> -Name &quot;*. sql&quot; <br /> Find the file extension is sql <br /> -Print <br /> The actual display file list. Output is piped to xargs <br /> xargs <br /> The contents of each file passed to the command after <br /> grep-iv \\ $ session <br /> Contents of the file filter to show only the line containing v $ sessoin,-i option means it is not case sensitive. <br /> 6. Find the file most recently created the following command to find files created within 1 day. <br /> HBZW&gt; find.-Mtime -1-print <br /> . / Script <br /> . / Script / test.sql <br /> . / Script / watch.sql <br /> . / Script / haha.txt <br /> Learn by analogy, if you want to check more than 1 day files created to use the +1 option <br /> 7. Find large files in the system the following command to find files larger than 10,000 bytes: <br /> # Find.-Size +10000 c-print <br /> If not c, then check the file is larger than 10000 blocks (512 bytes) file. Some Unix, you can add k, unit is kb. <br /> 8. Find the size of the files in a range: <br /> For example, find the size of 100 to 120 bytes of the file <br /> # Find.-Size +100 c-size-120c-print <br /> If you want to find exactly how much the file size, it can be: <br /> # Find.-Size 100c-print <br /> The above command to find the right size is 100 bytes.</font> </p>','1. Lists the most recent move over (touched) files as a DBA, you often need to view the file as a recent passive. When the Oracle files are read or write when he is too passive. ls command to see which file is the last passive before. Note that using the output to limit the number of head, only...'),(216,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/de/1988.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle DBA, UNIX Pocket Reference Manual of memory and cpu','Oracle_DBA_UNIX_Pocket_Reference_Manual_of_memory_and_cpu','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1. Display memory information under TRU64: <br /> $ / Bin / vmstat-P | grep &quot;Total Physical Memory&quot; <br /> Total Physical Memory = 1024.00 M <br /> Total Physical Memory Use: 130730 / 1021.33M <br /> 2. Display memory under HP-UX information: <br /> grep MemTotal / proc / meminfo <br /> 3. Solaris memory size is displayed: <br /> / Usr / sbin / prtconf | grep &quot;Memory size&quot; <br /> 4. Aix memory size is displayed: <br /> / Usr / sbin / lsattr-E-l sys0-a realmem <br /> 5. Aix\'s svmon tool use <br /> IBM AIX provides a tool called svmon. This tool displays the server usage of all memory, including paging and memory use. For example: <br /> # Svmon <br /> size inuse free pin virtual <br /> memory 1048576 961861 86715 115058 165229 <br /> pg space 131072 315 <br /> work pers clnt lpage <br /> pin 115058 0 0 0 <br /> in use 165244 14559 782058 0 <br /> size: real memory of the frame (frame) size. In Unix, an equal one. Page size is generally under Unix <br /> 4k. <br /> inuse: Use the frame number <br /> free: the number of available frame <br /> pin: peg (pin) of the frame number <br /> virtual: the total amount of virtual memory available <br /> svmon command can also be used to view the memory of a specific process information such as: <br /> # Svmon-P 17322 <br /> -------------------------------------------------- ----------------------------- <br /> Pid Command Inuse Pin Pgsp Virtual 64-bit Mthrd LPage <br /> 17322 unixsvr 17604 2423 0 14099 N Y N</font> </p>','1. Display memory information under TRU64:  $ / Bin / vmstat-P | grep \"Total Physical Memory\"  Total Physical Memory = 1024.00 M  Total Physical Memory Use: 130730 / 1021.33M  2. Display memory under HP-UX information:  grep MemTotal / proc / meminfo  3. Solaris memory size is displayed:  / Usr /...'),(217,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/42/1987.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle DBA, UNIX Pocket Reference manual server configuration parameters','Oracle_DBA_UNIX_Pocket_Reference_manual_server_configuration_parameters','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">There are many Unix system configuration parameters, such as the core parameters, such as some configuration value is about memory, disk and other information. Unix operating system kernel parameters on the impact of very large, there are some parameters to install Oracle in Unix is very useful. <br /> 1. Show HP-UX to the service by using the lsdev command device information, you can connect to the server shows all the device information. Including disk drives, <br /> Memory, CPU, bus and so on. The following command, lsdev lists all the mount to the server device.</font> </p><div align=\"left\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt 55.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 15.3pt\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black\">$</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: blue\">Lsdev</span></font> </div><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Character Block Driver Class <br /><br /> 0 -1 cn pseudo <br /> 3 -1 mm pseudo <br /> 16 -1 ptym ptym <br /> 17 -1 ptys ptys <br /> 27 -1 dmem pseudo <br /> 28 -1 diag0 diag <br /> 46 -1 netdiag1 unknown <br /> 52 -1 lan2 lan <br /><br /> 2. Aix display device information in the server can also be used in the AIX lsdev command to check the hardware device information. <br /> $ Lsdev-C <br /> sys0 ... System Object <br /> sysplanar0 ... System Planar <br /> pci0 ... PCI Bus <br /> pci1 ... PCI Bus <br /> isa0 ... ISA Bus <br /> sa0 ... Standard I / O Serial Port <br /> sa1 ... Standard I / O Serial Port <br /> scsi0 ... Wide SCSI I / O Controller <br /> hdisk0 ... 16 Bit SCSI Disk Drive <br /> hdisk1 ... 16 Bit SCSI Disk Drive <br /> ... <br /> 3. Show HP-UX kernel parameters in the system we can kmtune command to display the HP-UX Version 11 after all the core values of parameters of wear. Some key parameters, such as maxusers semmni and so on, Oracle will run correctly is extremely important. <br /> $ Kmtune <br /> Parameter Value <br /> NSTREVENT 50 <br /> NSTRPUSH 16 <br /> NSTRSCHED 0 <br /> STRCTLSZ 1024 <br /> STRMSGSZ 65535 <br /> acctresume 4 <br /> acctsuspend 2 <br /> semmni 200 <br /> semmns 800 <br /> semmnu 30 <br /> semume 10 <br /> semvmx 32767 <br /> ... ... <br /><br /> Of course, we can use grep to output filter, get some of our concern. For example: <br /> $ Kmtune | grep-i shm <br /> shmem 1 <br /> shmmax 1073741824 <br /> shmmni 500 <br /> shmseg 300 <br /> 4. View the system in the AIX kernel parameters that we need to use the lsattr command. For example: <br /> $ Lsattr-El sys0 <br /> maxbuf 20 Maximum number of pages in block ... <br /> maxmbuf 0 Maximum Kbytes of real memory al ... <br /> maxuproc 200 Maximum number of PROCESSES allo ... <br /> iostat true Continuously maintain DISK I / O h. .. <br /> realmem 3137536 Amount of usable physical mem ... <br /> modelname IBM ,9076-WCN Machine name ... <br /> systemid IBM, 010013864 Hardware system ide ... <br /> ... <br /> This command shows us the beginning of the parameter max is useful, such as maxbuf, maxuproc and so on. <br /> 5. The core parameters is displayed in TRU64 <br /> TRU64 core parameter file is under / etc / sysconfigtab, can be used as a vi to edit files. We can use the sysconfig command to see the core parameters, such as: <br /> # Sysconfig-q ipc <br /> ipc: <br /> msg_max = 8192 <br /> msg_mnb = 16384 <br /> msg_mni = 64 <br /> msg_tql = 40 <br /> shm_max = 4278190080 <br /> shm_min = 256 <br /> shm_mni = 1024 <br /> shm_seg = 1024 <br /> sem_mni = 16 <br /> sem_msl = 2600 <br /> sem_opm = 10 <br /> sem_ume = 10 <br /> sem_vmx = 32767 <br /> sem_aem = 16384 <br /> sem_broadcast_wakeup = 1 <br /> max_kernel_ports = 93728 <br /> ssm_threshold = 8388608 <br /> ssm_enable_core_dump = 1 <br /> shm_allocate_striped = 1 <br /> shm_enable_core_dump = 1 <br /> 6. Solaris kernel parameters shown under <br /> Solaris kernel parameters are under / etc / system, we can use cat to display, you can use vi to edit. Cases</font> </p>','There are many Unix system configuration parameters, such as the core parameters, such as some configuration value is about memory, disk and other information. Unix operating system kernel parameters on the impact of very large, there are some parameters to install Oracle in Unix is very useful.  1....'),(218,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/7c/1986.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle DBA, UNIX Pocket Reference manual process management','Oracle_DBA_UNIX_Pocket_Reference_manual_process_management','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">This section describes how to manage the environment in the Unix oracle process. We know, Oracle instance composed by a set of processes, <br /> Such as PMON, SMON, DBWR, LGWn and so on. There is also need attention and management process, if used <br /> deticated listener, the listener will also generate this process. <br /> 1. Shows the process of Oracle\'s Unix <br /> $ Ps-ef | grep &quot;ora_&quot; | grep-v grep <br /> UID PID PPID C STIME TTY TIME CMD <br /> oracle 898 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:02.20 ora_pmon_gaxz <br /> oracle 900 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:06.11 ora_dbw0_gaxz <br /> oracle 902 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:06.90 ora_lgwr_gaxz <br /> oracle 904 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 1:01.29 ora_ckpt_gaxz <br /> oracle 906 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:12.56 ora_smon_gaxz <br /> oracle 908 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:00.17 ora_reco_gaxz <br /> oracle 910 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:28.05 ora_cjq0_gaxz <br /> oracle 912 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 5:28.37 ora_qmn0_gaxz <br /> oracle 914 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:00.16 ora_s000_gaxz <br /> oracle 916 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:00.07 ora_d000_gaxz <br /> UID: behalf of the user <br /> PID: Representative process <br /> PPID: Parent process. If the parent process is 1, the representative of the process is invoked by the init process. <br /> STIME: start-up time <br /> CMD: Unix command to be executed <br /> 2. View the longest CPU consuming process: <br /> $ Ps-ef | grep oracle | sort +6 | tail <br /> oracle 914 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:00.19 ora_s000_gaxz <br /> oracle 908 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:00.20 ora_reco_gaxz <br /> oracle 898 1 0.0 Sep 22?? 0:02.94 ora_pmon_gaxz</font> </p>','This section describes how to manage the environment in the Unix oracle process. We know, Oracle instance composed by a set of processes,  Such as PMON, SMON, DBWR, LGWn and so on. There is also need attention and management process, if used  deticated listener, the listener will also generate this...'),(219,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/55/1984.html','http://www.ixdba.net','The UNIX Oracle DBA Pocket Construction of Unix commands reference manual','The_UNIX_Oracle_DBA_Pocket_Construction_of_Unix_commands_reference_manual','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<div class=\"Section1\"><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt 37.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 14.65pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-line-height-rule: exactly; mso-layout-grid-align: none\"> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt; mso-ascii-font-family: simsun; mso-hansi-font-family: simsun; mso-bidi-font-family: simsun\">Sometimes</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: simsun; mso-font-kerning: 0pt; mso-bidi-font-family: simsun\"> </span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; ms