),(220,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/89/1976.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle locking mechanism for protecting shared resources Enqueue','oracle_locking_mechanism_for_protecting_shared_resources_Enqueue','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<html><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">enqueue is a protected shared <a class=\"kw\" href=\"/article/2f/673.html\">resources</a> of the locking mechanism. The locking mechanisms to protect shared <a class=\"kw\" href=\"/article/2f/673.html\">resources</a> , such as logging data, in order to avoid two people updating the same data at the same time. enqueue <br /> Includes a queuing mechanism, that is FIFO (FIFO) queuing mechanism.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Enqueue waits are common ST, HW, TX, TM, etc.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">ST enqueue, for space management and dictionary managed tablespaces (DMT) in the range of distribution is typical in the DMT for the uet $ and fet $ data dictionary table contention. To support the version of LMT, we should make use of locally managed tablespaces. Or consider pre-allocated a certain number of hand-district (Extent), reduce the dynamic expansion of the queue when the serious competition.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">We look at an example:</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"left style25\"><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><div align=\"left\" class=\"left style25\"><table bgcolor=\"#999999\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"style6\" valign=\"top\" width=\"736\"><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â \r\nDB Name DB Id Instance Inst Num Release OPS Host\r\n------------ ----------- ------------ -------- ------- ---- --- ------------------\r\nDB 40757346 aaa 1 8.1.7.4.0 NO server\r\n\r\n                Snap Id Snap Time Sessions\r\n                ------- ------------------ --------\r\n Begin Snap: 2845 31-10 02:10:16 46 May -03\r\n   End Snap: 2848 31-10 03:40:05 46 May -03\r\n    Elapsed: 89.82 (mins)\r\n\r\n\r\n<strong>For a Statspack the report, the sampling time is very important dimension, leaving time for reference, any wait is not enough to describe the problem.</strong>\r\n\r\nCache Sizes\r\n~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n           db_block_buffers: 51200 log_buffer: 2097152\r\n              db_block_size: 16384 shared_pool_size: 209715200\r\n... ... ... ..\r\nTop 5 Wait Events\r\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ Wait% Total\r\nEvent Waits Time (cs) Wt Time\r\n-------------------------------------------- ------ ------ ------------ -------\r\nenqueue 53,793 16,192,686 67.86\r\nrdbms ipc message 19,999 5,927,350 24.84\r\npmon timer 1,754 538,797 2.26\r\nsmon timer 17 522,281 2.19\r\nSQL * Net message from client 94,525 520,104 2.18\r\n          -------------------------------------------------- -----------\r\n\r\n</font> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong>In the Statspack analysis, Top 5 wait event is part of our main concerns.\r\nThis system, in addition to enqueue wait event, the other four belong to the Idle wait events, without concern. Let\'s look at enqueue wait events in the 89.82 (mins) sampling interval, the cumulative enqueue wait up to 16,192,686 cs, or 45 hours. The wait is too significant, in fact, is precisely because the system encountered great difficulties, observe the queue to wait then we should pay attention to what is waiting for the queue waiting for <a class=\"kw\" href=\"/article/2f/673.html\">resources</a> . Quick jump to other parts of Statspack, we see the following details:</strong>\r\n\r\nEnqueue activity for DB: DB Instance: aaa Snaps: 2716 -2718\r\n-&gt; Ordered by waits desc, gets desc\r\n\r\nEnqueue Gets Waits\r\n---------- ------------ ----------\r\nST 1,554 1,554\r\n          -------------------------------------------------- -----------\r\n\r\n<strong>We see the main queue waiting to lock in the ST waiting for DMT, we say that the wait with the FET $, UET $\'s contention closely related. We go back to study the capture of the SQL statement:\r\n</strong>\r\n-&gt; End Buffer Gets Threshold: 10000\r\n-&gt; Note that resources reported for PL / SQL includes the resources used by\r\n   all SQL statements called within the PL / SQL code. As individual SQL\r\n   statements are also reported, it is possible and valid for the summed\r\n   total% to exceed 100\r\n\r\n  Buffer Gets Executions Gets per Exec% Total Hash Value\r\n--------------- ------------ -------------- ------- - ----------\r\n      4,800,073 1,026.8 51.0 2,913,840,444 467.5\r\nselect length from fet $ where file # =: 1 and block # =: 2 and ts # =: 3\r\n\r\n        803,187 10,223 78.6 8.5 528 349 613\r\ndelete from uet $ where ts # =: 1 and segfile # =: 2 and segblock # =: 3 a\r\nnd ext # =: 4\r\n\r\n        454,444 10,300 44.1 4.8 1839874543\r\nselect file #, block #, length from uet $ where ts # =: 1 and segfile # =:\r\n2 and segblock # =: 3 and ext # =: 4\r\n\r\n         23,110 10,230 2.3 0.2 3230982141\r\ninsert into fet $ (file #, block #, ts #, length) values (: 1,: 2,: 3,: 4)\r\n\r\n         21,201 347 61.1 0.2 1705880752\r\nselect file # from file $ where ts # =: 1\r\n....\r\n          9,505 12 792.1 0.1 1714733582\r\nselect f.file #, f.block #, f.ts #, f.length from fet $ f, ts $ t whe\r\nre t.ts # = f.ts # and t.dflextpct! = 0 and t.bitmapped = 0\r\n\r\n          6,426 235 27.3 0.1 1877781575\r\ndelete from fet $ where file # =: 1 and block # =: 2 and ts # =: 3\r\n\r\n<strong>We see frequent database operations UET $, FET $ system table has become a major bottleneck in the system.\r\nSo far, we have the system can accurately locate the problem, the corresponding solution is also very easy to determine, in 8.1.7, the use of LMT instead of DMT,\r\nThis is the fundamental way to solve the problem, of course, but also to implement a comprehensive consideration, the reality is much more complex.\r\n</strong>\r\n       </font></font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></div><br /><br /><center> <b><font color=\"red\">Read more:</font></b>* &quot;&gt; <b>1</b> * <a href=\"/article/89/1976$2.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">2</a> * <a href=\"/article/89/1976$2.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">Next&gt;&gt;</a> </center><br />','enqueue is a protected shared resources of the locking mechanism. The locking mechanisms to protect shared resources , such as logging data, in order to avoid two people updating the same data at the same time. enqueue  Includes a queuing mechanism, that is FIFO (FIFO) queuing...'),(221,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/1c/1975.html','http://www.ixdba.net','&quot;Log file sync&quot; wait event','quotLog_file_syncquot_wait_event','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">When a user submits (commits) or rollback (rollback), session\'s redo information needs to write to the redo logfile. <br /> LGWR process will notify users perform write operations, LGWR to complete the task after the user process will be notified. <br /> This means a user process to wait for the event is waiting for LGWR write is complete.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">For rollback, the rollback event logging command issued from the user to rollback to complete.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If the wait too, may indicate that LGWR to write inefficient, or the system to submit too often. <br /> To solve the problem, you can concern: <br /> log file parallel write wait event <br /> user commits, user rollback and other statistical information can be used to commit or roll back the number of observations</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Solution: <br /> 1. LGWR performance to improve to make use of fast disks, not to redo log file stored in a raid 5 disk <br /> 2. Using bulk submission <br /> 3. The proper use of NOLOGGING / UNRECOVERABLE other options</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Can be calculated by the following average redo write size:</font> </p><div align=\"left\" class=\"left style25\"><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">avg.redo write size = (Redo block written / redo writes) * 512 bytes</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If the system generates redo a lot, and each written in less general description of the LGWR is activated too frequently. <br /> May lead to excessive competition redo associated latch, and the effective use of Oracle may not piggyback function.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">We extract from a statspack some data to study this problem.</font> </p><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1. The main information</font></strong> </p><table border=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#999999\" width=\"729\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">DB Name DB Id Instance Inst Num Release OPS Host\r\n------------ ----------- ------------ -------- ------- ---- --- ------------\r\nDB 1222010599 oracle 1 8.1.7.4.5 NO sun\r\n                Snap Id Snap Time Sessions\r\n                ------- ------------------ --------\r\n Begin Snap: 3473 13-Oct-04 13:43:00 540\r\n   End Snap: 3475 13-Oct-04 14:07:28 540\r\n    Elapsed: 24.47 (mins)\r\n\r\nCache Sizes\r\n~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n           db_block_buffers: 102400 log_buffer: 20971520\r\n              db_block_size: 8192 shared_pool_size: 600M\r\n\r\nLoad Profile\r\n~~~~~~~~~~~~ Per Second Per Transaction\r\n                                   --------------- ---------------\r\n                  Redo size: 28,458.11 2,852.03\r\n                  ......\r\n                          </font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">2. Wait for the event</font></strong> </p><table bgcolor=\"#999999\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"style6\" valign=\"top\" width=\"736\"><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Event Waits Timeouts Time (cs) (ms) / txn\r\n---------------------------- ------------ ---------- ----------- ------ ------\r\n<em>log file sync 14,466 2 4,150 3 1.0</em>\r\ndb file sequential read 17,202 0 2,869 2 1.2\r\nlatch free 24,841 13,489 2,072 1 1.7 \r\ndirect path write 121 0 1,455 120 0.0\r\ndb file parallel write 1,314 0 1,383 11 0.1\r\n</font> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><em>log file sequential read 1,540 0 63 0 0.1\r\n....\r\nlog file switch completion 1 0 3 30 0.0</em>\r\nrefresh controlfile command 23 0 1 0 0.0\r\nLGWR wait for redo copy 46 0 0 0 0.0\r\n....\r\n<em>log file single write 4 0 0 0 0.0</em>\r\n       </font></font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table><p> <font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\"><strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">IXDBA.NET Technical Community</font></strong></a></font> <br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">We see here log file sync and db file parallel write wait to come together.</font> </p></div><br /><br /><center> <b><font color=\"red\">Read more:</font> <font color=\"red\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">1</font></b> <a href=\"/article/1c/1975$2.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">2</a> * <a href=\"/article/1c/1975$3.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">3</a> * <a href=\"/article/1c/1975$2.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">Next&gt;&gt;</a> </center><br />','When a user submits (commits) or rollback (rollback), session\'s redo information needs to write to the redo logfile.  LGWR process will notify users perform write operations, LGWR to complete the task after the user process will be notified.  This means a user process to wait for the event is...'),(222,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/74/1973.html','http://www.ixdba.net','db file scattered read-DB file scattered read','db_file_scattered_readDB_file_scattered_read','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">This usually related to display and wait a full table scan. <br /> When the database when a full table scan, based on performance considerations, data distributed (scattered) read Buffer Cache. If this wait event more significant, <br /> May account for some full-table scan the table, did not create the index or not to create an appropriate index, we may need to check to determine whether these data sheets for the correct settings.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">However, this wait event does not necessarily mean poor performance, under certain conditions, Oracle will take the initiative to replace the use of full table scan to improve the performance of index scan, this amount of data and access relevant, under the Oracle CBO will be conducted in a more intelligent choice , under the RBO more inclined to use Oracle indexes.</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Because a full table scan is placed LRU (Least Recently Used, Least Recently applicable) a list of the cold end (cold end), for frequently accessed small tables, you can choose them in the Cache memory to avoid repeated reading .</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">When the wait for more significant events, you can combine the dynamic performance view v $ session_longops to be diagnosed, the view recorded in a long time (more than 6 seconds to run) to run things, a full table scan may be a lot of operations (In any case, This part of the information is worthy of our attention.)</font> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"style25\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">We passed through a case study to familiarize yourself with the wait for the event:</font> <br /></p><div align=\"left\" class=\"left style25\"><p></p><table border=\"0\" style=\"WIDTH: 571px; HEIGHT: 1551px\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#999999\" width=\"734\"><pre> DB Name DB Id Instance Inst Num Release OPS Host         \r\n---------- ----------- ---------- -------- ---------- - --- ----------   \r\nK2 1999167370 k2 1 8.1.5.0.0 NO k2       \r\n\r\n\r\n<strong>This is a 8.1.5 database system, enhanced by the script, we can use the database in 8.1.5 statspack for a database diagnosis.</strong>\r\n\r\n                                                             Snap Length   \r\nStart Id End Id Start Time End Time (Minutes)    \r\n-------- -------- -------------------- -------------- ------ -----------   \r\n     170 176 25-Feb-03 10:00:11 25-Feb-03 15:00:05 299.90   \r\n\r\nCache Sizes                                                                   \r\n~~~~~~~~~~~                                                                   \r\n           db_block_buffers: 64000                                      \r\n              db_block_size: 8192                                      \r\n                 log_buffer: 8388608                                      \r\n           shared_pool_size: 157286400                                      \r\n                                                                              \r\n... ... ... ... ... ...                    \r\n                                                                              \r\nTop 5 Wait Events                                                             \r\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ Wait% Total\r\nEvent Waits Time (cs) Wt Time\r\n-------------------------------------------- ------ ------ ----------------------- -------\r\ndb file scattered read 16,842,920 3,490,719 43.32\r\nlatch free 844,272 3,270,073 40.58\r\nbuffer busy waits 114,421 933,136 11.58\r\ndb file sequential read 2,067,910 117,750 1.46\r\nenqueue 464 110,840 1.38\r\n         -------------------------------------------------- -----------        \r\n\r\n<strong>This is a typical poor performance of the system, waiting for several important events occurred in Top 5, in which the first 3 to wait for a very significant need to be adjusted accordingly.\r\n5-hour sampling interval, which db file scattered read about 10 hours total of waiting time, has become the main reason affecting system performance.\r\nAfter understanding these we can further look to see whether there can be related to SQL\'s SQL statement.\r\n</strong>\r\nSQL ordered by Gets for DB: K2 Instance: k2 Snaps: 170 - 176   \r\n                                                                              \r\n                                Gets% of                               \r\n   Buffer Gets Executes per Exec Total Hash Value                  \r\n-------------- ------------ ------------ ------ ------ ------                  \r\nSQL statement                                                                 \r\n-------------------------------------------------- ----------------------------\r\n     6,480,163 12 540,013.6 2.4 3791855498                  \r\n  SELECT &quot;PROCESS_REQ&quot;. &quot;WORK_ID&quot;, &quot;PROCESS_REQ&quot;. &quot;STOCK_NO&quot;, &quot;PROCESS_R\r\n                                                                              \r\n     3,784,566 16 236,535.4 1.4 2932917818                  \r\nSELECT * FROM FIND_LATER_WO ORDER BY NOTE, ORDER_NO                            \r\n                                                                                \r\n     1,200,976 3 .4 4,122,791,109 400,325.3                  \r\n  SELECT &quot;ITEM_STOCK&quot;. &quot;ITEM_NO&quot;, &quot;ITEM&quot;. &quot;NOTE&quot;, &quot;ITEM&quot;\r\n                                                                               \r\n       923,944 9 102,660.4 .3 2200071737                  \r\n  SELECT &quot;ITEM_STOCK&quot;. &quot;ITEM_NO&quot;, &quot;ITEM_STOCK&quot;. &quot;STOCK_NO&quot;,921,301 3 307,100.3 .3 2218843294 SELECT &quot;ITEM_STOCK&quot;. &quot;ITEM_NO&quot;, &quot;ITEM&quot;. &quot;NOTE&quot;, &quot;ITEM&quot; 911,285 3 303,761.7 .3 1769130587 SELECT &quot;LISTS&quot;. &quot;ITEM_NO&quot;, &quot;LISTS&quot;. &quot;SUB_ITEM&quot;, &quot; LISTS &quot;831,439 2 415,719.5 .3 1349577999 SELECT&quot; GROUP_OPER &quot;.&quot; ITEM_NO &quot;,&quot; GROUP_OPER &quot;.&quot; PROCESS_ID &quot;, 802,918 1 802,918.0 .3 3613809507 SELECT&quot; LISTS &quot;.&quot; ITEM_NO &quot;,&quot; LISTS &quot;.&quot; SUB_ITEM &quot;,&quot; ITEM &quot;. 800,548 2 400,274.0 .3 2643788247 SELECT&quot; ITEM_STOCK &quot;.&quot; ITEM_NO &quot;,&quot; ITEM &quot;.&quot; NOTE &quot;,&quot; ITEM &quot;666,085 2 333,042.5 .2 3391363608 SELECT&quot; ITEM_STOCK &quot;.&quot; ITEM_NO &quot;,&quot; ITEM_STOCK &quot;.&quot; STOCK_NO &quot; , ... ... ... .. <strong>note of the above query result Buffer Gets a lot of very large, we have reason to suspect that the index is a problem, or even the lack of necessary indexes. SQL record is more than a fragment, by Hash Value in combination with v $ sql_text we can get the complete SQL statement. In this diagnosis, I immediately went to check the v $ session_longops data table, a grouping query results are as follows:</strong> TARGET COUNT (*) ------------------- --------------------------------------------- ----- ----- SA.PPBT_GRAPHOBJTABLE 418 SA.PPBT_PPBTOBJRELATTABLE 53 <strong>we find these problems SQL full table scan (with v $ session_longops view OPNAME) mainly in PPBT_GRAPHOBJTABLE and PPBT_PPBTOBJRELATTABLE two data tables. Further research found that the two tables does not have any index, and a considerable amount of data:</strong> SQL&gt; select count (*) from SA.PPBT_PPBTOBJRELATTABLE; COUNT (*) ---------- 1209017 SQL&gt; select count (*) from SA.PPBT_GRAPHOBJTABLE; COUNT (*) ---------- 2445 <strong>to create the appropriate index, system performance is greatly improved!</strong> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></div>','This usually related to display and wait a full table scan.  When the database when a full table scan, based on performance considerations, data distributed (scattered) read Buffer Cache. If this wait event more significant,  May account for some full-table scan the table, did not create the index...'),(223,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/7e/1940.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Solve the ORA-600 [qmxiUnpPacked2] error','Solve_the_ORA600_qmxiUnpPacked2_error','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Test a Oracle 9.2.0.8 database encountered an ORA-600 [qmxiUnpPacked2] error.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Drop user error is triggered when: <br /></font> </p><blockquote> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; drop user eygle; <br /> drop user eygle <br /> * <br /> ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-01001: invalid cursor <br /> ORA-00600: internal error code, arguments: [qmxiUnpPacked2], [121], [], [], [],[], [], []</font> </blockquote><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">According to</font> <font color=\"#0082ff\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Metalink</font> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Note: 339070.1, this error of a <a class=\"kw\" href=\"/article/57/751.html\">trigger</a> condition is not fully upgraded, you need to run catpatch.sql script. <br /> The following steps to resolve the issue: <br /></font> </p><blockquote> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; shutdown immediate <br /> SQL&gt; startup migrate <br /> SQL&gt; spool patch.log <br /> SQL&gt; @? / Rdbms / admin / catpatch <br /> SQL&gt; spool off</font> </blockquote><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Record of this to remember!</font> </p>','Test a Oracle 9.2.0.8 database encountered an ORA-600 [qmxiUnpPacked2]...'),(224,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/10/1000.html','http://www.ixdba.net','In Oracle10g RAC ASM disk under the new','In_Oracle10g_RAC_ASM_disk_under_the_new','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In Oracle10g RAC environment, the changes to the ASM disk group should be extremely cautious. If set incorrectly can easily lead to other nodes down.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Before creating the ASM disk group, you need to authorize the device file, this step must be a different node in the RAC for. <br /> Second, the different nodes of the same device file is best.</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">bash-2.05 # chown oracle: dba / dev/rdsk/c2t0d3 * <br /> bash-2.05 # chmod 660 / dev/rdsk/c2t0d3 *</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Then under the Oracle user, modify the disk scan path can be found the new disk has been identified:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; select path from v $ asm_disk;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">PATH <br /> -------------------------------------------------- ------------------------------ <br /> / Dev/vx/rdsk/10gracdg/asmdata</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; show parameter string</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">NAME TYPE VALUE <br /> ------------------------------------ ----------- --- --------------------------- <br /> asm_diskstring string / dev/vx/rdsk/10gracdg/asmdata <br /> SQL&gt; alter system set asm_diskstring = \'/ dev/vx/rdsk/10gracdg/asmdata\', \'/ dev / rdsk / *\';</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">System altered.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; show parameter string</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">NAME TYPE VALUE <br /> ------------------------------------ ----------- --- --------------------------- <br /> asm_diskstring string / dev/vx/rdsk/10gracdg/asmdata, <br /> / Dev / rdsk / * <br /> SQL&gt; select path from v $ asm_disk;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">PATH <br /> -------------------------------------------------- ------------------------------ <br /> / Dev/rdsk/c2t0d3s1 <br /> / Dev/rdsk/c2t0d3s6 <br /> / Dev/vx/rdsk/10gracdg/asmdata</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">To confirm that the different nodes, the disk can be properly identified, then you can create ASM disk group:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; create diskgroup testdg external redundancy disk \'/ dev/rdsk/c2t0d3s6\';</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Diskgroup created.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; select group_number, name, state, total_mb from v $ asm_diskgroup;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GROUP_NUMBER NAME STATE TOTAL_MB <br /> ------------ ------------------------------ -------- --- ---------- <br /> 1 ORADG MOUNTED 16384 <br /> 2 TESTDG MOUNTED 927 <br /></font> </p><p> <strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\">www.ixdba.net</a></font></strong> </p><br /><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">You can then manually mount the nodes in another new disk group:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; select group_number, name, state, total_mb from v $ asm_diskgroup;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GROUP_NUMBER NAME STATE TOTAL_MB <br /> ------------ ------------------------------ -------- --- ---------- <br /> 1 ORADG MOUNTED 16384 <br /> 0 TESTDG DISMOUNTED 0</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; alter diskgroup testdg mount;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Diskgroup altered.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; select group_number, name, state, total_mb from v $ asm_diskgroup;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GROUP_NUMBER NAME STATE TOTAL_MB <br /> ------------ ------------------------------ -------- --- ---------- <br /> 1 ORADG MOUNTED 16384 <br /> 2 TESTDG MOUNTED 927</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Solaris platform from the above operations, the steps may be different on different platforms, operation risk, action to be cautious.</font> </p>','In Oracle10g RAC environment, the changes to the ASM disk group should be extremely cautious. If set incorrectly can easily lead to other nodes...'),(225,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/b4/293.html','http://www.ixdba.net','ORACLE SQL Performance Optimization Series (a)','ORACLE_SQL_Performance_Optimization_Series_a','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><br /> 1.</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">The types of</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">ORACLE</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">optimizer</span> </p><p> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">ORACLE</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">optimizer There are</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">3 <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">kinds:</span> <br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">Ã£Â€Â€Ã£Â€Â€</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">Ã£Â€Â€Ã£Â€Â€</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">a.</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: \'Times New Roman\'\">Ã£Â€Â€</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FON