tyle=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">The first group of two</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">SQL</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">statements are the same <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">(can share),</span> while the second group the two statements are different <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">(even</span> at <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">runtime,</span> assigns a different bind variables the same <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">value)</span></span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">Ã£Â€Â€Ã£Â€Â€</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">Ã£Â€Â€Ã£Â€Â€</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">a. <br /></span>SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana &quot;&gt; <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><br /></span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">Ã£Â€Â€Ã£Â€Â€</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">select pin, name from people where pin =: blk1.pin;</span> </p>',' 1. The types of ORACLE...'),(226,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/13/1707.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle performance tuning: Management oracle log','oracle_performance_tuning_Management_oracle_log','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Understanding of Oracle\'s logging mechanisms</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Ã¢Â€Â¢ Oracle\'s log is used to record the user changes the database, so that when there is server hardware failure or user error and missing data, you can redo logs to recover the committed transactions, Oracle log mechanism consists of the following components: <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ the log part of SGA cache for the cache server process the log, including DML and DDL; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ LGWR process is responsible for the background process writes the log data in the cache-line log files, each instance has only one; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ checkpoint checkpoint database is used to synchronize data files and log files, a checkpoint to complete the event, representing in this case occurred before the start of changes to all data files are actual records to the data file, the database is at this point in time consistent, in the instance recovery time, and only after the last checkpoint only need to redo log; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ on-line log files from the log cache used to store log data written for each database requires at least two log files, the current log file to fill after the log switch occurred before it can continue to write a log file; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ LGWR archive log filled online log files of all groups after the first group will be back to write the log file, in non archive mode, the log file to be reused in the log will be discarded, in archive mode, the log file before being reused will be ARC0 process log files copied to the archive; <br /> Ã¢Â€Â¢ Some optional log mechanisms, such as archiving and Standby, because the additional I / O will reduce system performance, while providing a reliable disaster recovery capabilities, the performance is not recommended because of the decline of these closed production system archiving. <br /></font> </p><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Adjust the log cache</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Ã¢Â€Â¢ Log buffer management mechanism can be understood as similar to a funnel, log data continuously added from the funnel at the top, and then occasionally switch to open the bottom of the funnel the data will be added empty, this switch is the LGWR process, in order to keep the log cache has space to accommodate the increase incoming log data, LGWR listed below will be executed under any of the log buffer write operation: <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ Commit command is issued the application; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ three seconds to the time interval has; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ one-third of the log buffer is full; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ When the log buffer to 1M; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ database checkpoint occurs; <br /> Ã¢Â€Â¢ Measuring the performance of the log cache server process by placing logs to the log buffer section when the number of times and the time to wait to measure; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ Select Name, Value <br /> From V $ sysstat <br /> Where Name In (\'redo entries\', \'redo buffer allocation retries\', <br /> \'Redo log space requests\'); <br /> redo entries into the log cache server process logs the total number of articles; <br /> redo buffer allocation retries the server must be placed on the log and then wait for the number of retries; <br /> redo log space requests LGWR process waiting to write the log buffer when the number of log switches;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Select Retries.Value / Entries.Value &quot;Redo log Buffer Retry Ratio&quot; <br /> From V $ sysstat Entries, V $ sysstat Retries <br /> Where Entries.Name = \'redo entries\' <br /> And Retries.Name = \'redo buffer allocation retries\' <br /> This query used to calculate the rate of the log cache and try again, this ratio should be less than one percent; <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ Select s.Username, Sw.Wait_Time, Sw.Seconds_In_Wait, Sw.State <br /> From V $ session_Wait Sw, V $ session s <br /> Where Sw.Sid = s.Sid And Sw.Event Like \'% log buffer space%\'; <br /> This query is used to show which way to write session LGWR wait; <br /> State has four values: WAITING (the session is waiting), WAITED UNKNOWN TIME (wait time is unknown), WAITED SHORT TIME (waiting time less than hundredths of a second), WAITED KNOWN TIME (waiting time is known, is wait_time column bit below the time); <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ Statspack there are two places in the cache and logs performance-related data: <br /> Example hit rate (Instance Efficiency Percentages) in the Redo NoWait%, the value of the log cache and retry rate is equal to 1; <br /> Instance activity statistics (Instance Activity Stats) in the redo entries, redo buffer allocation retries, redo log space requests;</font> </p><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã¢Â€Â¢ Improved performance of the log cache</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Improve the performance of the log cache is to reduce or eliminate the cache server process reads the log and place the logs to the log buffer section when the wait can be from the following two aspects: <br /> ÃƒÂ˜ increase the log buffer</font> </p>','Understanding of Oracle\'s logging...'),(227,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/0b/1001.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle RAC environment, adjust the system clock','oracle_RAC_environment_adjust_the_system_clock','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In the RAC environment, Cluster of the need to maintain time synchronization between nodes, so pay attention during the installation process synchronous clock.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">We can date-s to change the system time</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # date <br /> Sat Dec 29 09:25:25 CST 2007 <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # date-s &quot;Sat Dec 29 09:37:50 CST 2007&quot; <br /> Sat Dec 29 09:37:50 CST 2007</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Note, however, this system\'s hardware clock may be different:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ smsdbrac2 ~] # date <br /> Sat Dec 29 09:38:39 CST 2007 <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac2 ~] # clock - show <br /> Sat 29 Dec 2007 09:27:43 AM CST -0.021796 seconds</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Note If the system clock and hardware clock is inconsistent, then restart the process, the system clock from the received time information. <br /> So need to synchronize the hardware clock:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # hwclock - show <br /> Sat 29 Dec 2007 09:32:41 AM CST -0.019265 seconds <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # date <br /> Sat Dec 29 09:44:13 CST 2007 <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # hwclock - systohc <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # date <br /> Sat Dec 29 09:44:25 CST 2007 <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac1 root] # hwclock - show <br /> Sat 29 Dec 2007 09:44:29 AM CST -0.015972 seconds</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Command hwclock - systohc specified time synchronization between the system hardware clock.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Always synchronized, RAC between nodes should be synchronized from the ntp server, time, or to a node as the master node, other nodes according to their time synchronization. <br /> The simplest is to create a crontab task:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ smsdbrac2 ~] # crontab-l <br /> 0 1,4,8,13,17,20 * * * / etc / rsyncdate.sh <br /> [Root @ smsdbrac2 ~] # cat / etc / rsyncdate.sh <br /> rdate-s 192.168.200.11</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If there is a firewall, you need to open between the nodes 37 need rdate port:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">-A RH-Firewall-1-INPUT-m state - state NEW-m udp-p udp - dport 37-j ACCEPT <br /> -A RH-Firewall-1-INPUT-m state - state NEW-m tcp-p tcp - dport 37-j ACCEPT <br /></font> </p>','In the RAC environment, Cluster of the need to maintain time synchronization between nodes, so pay attention during the installation process synchronous...'),(228,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/3d/1005.html','http://www.ixdba.net','How to Start DataGuard standby database','How_to_Start_DataGuard_standby_database','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Came to the company early in the morning, open the mailbox and found a bunch of alarm messages received, a Down Standby database out.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Check the main library visit, warning the log records the error message:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">*** 2006-10-30 07:32:10.614 <br /> kcrrfail: dest: 2 err: 12560 force: 0 <br /> ORA-12560: TNS: protocol adapter error <br /> *** 2006-10-30 07:34:10.615 <br /> Error 12541 connecting to destination LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_2 standby host \'bmarksb\' <br /> Error 12541 attaching to destination LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_2 standby host \'bmarksb\' <br /> Heartbeat failed to connect to standby \'bmarksb\'. Error is 12541. <br /> *** 2006-10-30 07:34:10.615 <br /> kcrrfail: dest: 2 err: 12541 force: 0 <br /> ORA-12541: TNS: no listener <br /> *** 2006-10-30 07:36:10.615 <br /> Error 12541 connecting to destination LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_2 standby host \'bmarksb\' <br /> Error 12541 attaching to destination LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_2 standby host \'bmarksb\' <br /> Heartbeat failed to connect to standby \'bmarksb\'. Error is 12541.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Sign In from the library host, start the standby database manually:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Oracle @ wapcom2 bdump] $ sqlplus &quot;/ as sysdba&quot;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL * Plus: Release 9.2.0.6.0 - Production on Mon Oct 30 08:17:24 2006</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Copyright (c) 1982, 2002, Oracle Corporation. All rights reserved.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Connected to an idle instance.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; startup nomount; <br /> ORACLE instance started.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Total System Global Area 470881780 bytes <br /> Fixed Size 452084 bytes <br /> Variable Size 167772160 bytes <br /> Database Buffers 301989888 bytes <br /> Redo Buffers 667648 bytes <br /> SQL&gt; alter database mount standby database;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Database altered.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; alter database recover managed standby database disconnect from session;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Database altered.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; exit <br /> Disconnected from Oracle9i Enterprise Edition Release 9.2.0.6.0 - Production <br /> With the Partitioning, OLAP and Oracle Data Mining options <br /> JServer Release 9.2.0.6.0 - Production <br /> [Oracle @ wapcom2 bdump] $ lsnrctl start</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Observed log information from the library and found the archive can be automatically applied:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Oracle @ wapcom2 bdump] $ tail-f alert_bmark.log <br /> Standby Database mounted. <br /> Completed: alter database mount standby database <br /> Mon Oct 30 08:19:23 2006 <br /> alter database recover managed standby database disconnect from session <br /> Attempt to start background Managed Standby Recovery process <br /> MRP0 started with pid = 12 <br /> MRP0: Background Managed Standby Recovery process started <br /> Media Recovery Waiting for thread 1 seq # 5151 <br /> Mon Oct 30 08:19:29 2006 <br /> Completed: alter database recover managed standby database di <br /> Mon Oct 30 08:22:58 2006 <br /> Media Recovery Log / opt/oracle/oradata/bmark/stdarch/1_5151.arc <br /> Media Recovery Log / opt/oracle/oradata/bmark/stdarch/1_5152.arc <br /> Media Recovery Log / opt/oracle/oradata/bmark/stdarch/1_5153.arc <br /> Media Recovery Log / opt/oracle/oradata/bmark/stdarch/1_5154.arc <br /> Media Recovery Log / opt/oracle/oradata/bmark/stdarch/1_5155.arc <br /> Media Recovery Waiting for thread 1 seq # 5156</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">And then check the reason and found that the problem is the host, constantly re-starting the night:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">-Bash-2.05b $ last | grep reboot <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 08:10 (02:14) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 07:51 (02:32) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 07:38 (02:45) <br /> <strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\">IXDBA.NET Technical Community</a></font></strong> <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 07:35 (02:48) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 07:21 (03:02) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 07:18 (03:05) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 06:39 (03:44) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 06:37 (03:46) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 06:32 (03:51) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 06:03 (04:21) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 01:48 (08:36) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 01:23 (09:01) <br /> reboot system boot 2.4.21-15.ELsmp Mon Oct 30 00:39 (09:44)</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Prima facie there is a hardware failure, hardware failure is very frequent recently, at the end also to the accident-prone period. <br /> To remind everyone a lot of attention.</font> </p><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></p>','Came to the company early in the morning, open the mailbox and found a bunch of alarm messages received, a Down Standby database...'),(229,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/8e/1006.html','http://www.ixdba.net','System tablespace IO data corruption error handling','System_tablespace_IO_data_corruption_error_handling','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Colleagues have recently encountered a database problem, that there is a system tablespaces bad blocks, warning log file continuously following error:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Oracle @ gdmstest bdump] $ tail -20 alert_mydb.log <br /> Linux Error: 4: Interrupted system call <br /> Additional information: 23710 <br /> Wed Oct 25 16:47:44 2006 <br /> Errors in file / opt/oracle/admin/mydb/bdump/mydb_smon_19646.trc: <br /> ORA-00604: error occurred at recursive SQL level 1 <br /> ORA-01115: IO error reading block from file 1 (block # 23712) <br /> ORA-01110: data file 1: \'/ opt/oracle/oradata/mydb/system01.dbf\' <br /> ORA-27091: skgfqio: unable to queue I / O <br /> ORA-27072: skgfdisp: I / O error <br /> Linux Error: 4: Interrupted system call <br /> Additional information: 23710 <br /> Wed Oct 25 16:47:59 2006 <br /> Errors in file / opt/oracle/admin/mydb/bdump/mydb_smon_19646.trc: <br /> ORA-00604: error occurred at recursive SQL level 1 <br /> ORA-01115: IO error reading block from file 1 (block # 23712) <br /> ORA-01110: data file 1: \'/ opt/oracle/oradata/mydb/system01.dbf\' <br /> ORA-27091: skgfqio: unable to queue I / O <br /> ORA-27072: skgfdisp: I / O error <br /> Linux Error: 4: Interrupted system call <br /> Additional information: 23710</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Check through dbv damage and no reported data block:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Oracle @ gdmstest mydb] $ dbv file = system01.dbf blocksize = 8192</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">DBVERIFY: Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production on Thu Oct 26 11:36:42 2006</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Copyright (c) 1982, 2002, Oracle Corporation. All rights reserved.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">DBVERIFY - Verification starting: FILE = system01.dbf</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">DBVERIFY - Verification complete</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Total Pages Examined: 23709 <br /> Total Pages Processed (Data): 13000 <br /> Total Pages Failing (Data): 0 <br /> Total Pages Processed (Index): 2090 <br /> Total Pages Failing (Index): 0 <br /> Total Pages Processed (Other): 1377 <br /> Total Pages Processed (Seg): 0 <br /> Total Pages Failing (Seg): 0 <br /> Total Pages Empty: 7242 <br /> Total Pages Marked Corrupt: 0 <br /> Total Pages Influx: 0</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">We take a look at this issue, first of all from the error log, in fact, this is not a corrupted data block problem: <br /> ORA-01115: IO error reading block from file 1 (block # 23712)</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">This is a IO error, the data block can not read.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Tips for the DBV said only examined 23,709 data blocks, the data block is no problem, but we really are 23,712 pieces of data error data block number, that check to the block near the DBV, can not continue to read, and then exit.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">The system table space is much larger than 23709 * 8k / 1024 = 185M.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">At this point check the system log, dmesg log a large number of addressing errors, that is hardware failure occurred:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Maintain @ gdmstest bdump] $ dmesg <br /> : Error = 0x40 {UncorrectableError}, LBAsect = 58847319, high = 3, low = 8515671, sector = 14266880 <br /> end_request: I / O error, dev 03:06 (hda), sector 14266880 <br /> hda: dma_intr: status = 0x51 {DriveReady SeekComplete Error} <br /> hda: dma_intr: error = 0x40 {UncorrectableError}, LBAsect = 58847319, high = 3, low = 8515671, sector = 14266880 <br /> end_request: I / O error, dev 03:06 (hda), sector 14266880 <br /> hda: dma_intr: status = 0x51 {DriveReady SeekComplete Error} <br /> hda: dma_intr: error = 0x40 {UncorrectableError}, LBAsect = 58847319, high = 3, low = 8515671, sector = 14266880 <br /> end_request: I / O error, dev 03:06 (hda), sector 14266880 <br /> hda: dma_intr: status = 0x51 {DriveReady SeekComplete Error}</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">To this problem is positioning.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If we try to cp the file system table space, it will also receive a hardware error message:</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Oracle @ gdmstest mydb] $ cp system01.dbf system01.dbf.bk <br /></font> </p><p> <strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\">www.ixdba.net</a></font></strong> </p><br /> cp: reading into the \'system01.dbf\': Input / output error <br /> [Oracle @ gdmstest mydb] $ ll <br /> The total amount of 2,173,060 <br /> .... <br /> -Rw-r ----- 1 oracle dba 524296192 10 Ã¦ÂœÂˆ 25 16:49 system01.dbf <br /> -Rw-r ----- 1 oracle dba 194236416 10 Ã¦ÂœÂˆ 25 17:00 system01.dbf.bk <br /> ............... <p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Can only copy 194236416 Bytes, which is 194,236,416 / 8192 = 23710.5, also read about 23709 data blocks, the hardware will damage the system means to solve the other. <br /></font> </p>','Colleagues have recently encountered a database problem, that there is a system tablespaces bad blocks, warning log file continuously following...'),(230,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/d4/1169.html','http://www.ixdba.net','The midst of sadness: encountered ORA-00600 [','The_midst_of_sadness_encountered_ORA00600_','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Today, a RAC cluster customer problems, a node is restarted, ASM disk groups can not mount, report the following errors:</font> </p><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">ORA-00600: internal error code, arguments: [kfgFinalize_2], [], [], [], [], [], [], []</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Check the trac file as follows: <br /> Errors in file / u01/app/oracle/admin / + ASM / udump / + asm2_ora_11560.trc: <br /> ORA-00600: internal error code, arguments: [kfgFinalize_2], [], [], [], [], [], [], [] <br /><br /> ksedmp: internal or fatal error <br /> ORA-00600: internal error code, arguments: [kfgFinalize_2], [], [], [], [], [], [], [] <br /> Current SQL statement for this session: <br /> ALTER DISKGROUP ALL MOUNT</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> The back is a bunch of binary code, it appears that the disk group mount time is a problem.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Find information on all aspects, that is an oracle bug. <br /></font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">There are three solutions: <br /></font> </p><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1, the upgrade to 10.2.0.3 <br /> 2, hit a patch up <br /> 3, the live nodes that PMON to kill off, and then restart the instance of the node alive, making the force to recover the database</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Evaluate,</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Option 1 moves too much, but this version did not test used.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Option 2 of the readme file clearly says the patch may cause data loss, to the support of the oracle support to do, I do not support,</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Option III seems more feasible, the problem is at least one node is alive, if forced to kill pmon process, the Node 2 also get up, it all comes to an end, and only ready to cut the program before the dataguard.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">At this point in the oracle forum to see that not kill pmon, as long as the two nodes are dang down, and then start to ok.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Then reboot both nodes, and saw SUCCESS: diskgroup DATA was mounted tips out, relieved.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Database all together, the business returned to normal!</font> </p>','Today, a RAC cluster customer problems, a node is restarted, ASM disk groups can not mount, report the following...'),(231,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/25/1180.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Advanced Copy with ORACLE internal and external networks to achieve','Advanced_Copy_with_ORACLE_internal_and_external_networks_to_achieve','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">This paper introduces the advanced copy functions ORACLE, and through a practical project, the discussion inside and outside the network level in how to use advanced replication DB to achieve unity of internal and external network data, given the configuration script for your reference. <br /><br /> 1, the basic concept <br /><br /> ORACLE <br /> ORACLE is a Senior Structured Query Language (SQL) relational database based on large-scale, More simply it is easy to manipulate the language of logic management of a large number of regular data collection. Is a client / server (CLIENT / SERVER) architecture databases. <br /><br /> What is a senior copy copy? Simply copy is in the form of two or more database systems in a distributed database environment, the process of copying data. <br /> Advanced Replication, is composed of a distributed database system in multiple databases and maintaining database objects in the replication process. Oracle Advanced Replication allows applications to update any copies of the database, and these changes are automatically passed to other databases, while ensuring global transaction consistency and data integrity.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Replication, replication of data at any time in any consistent replication nodes. If the replication environment, a copy of any data node update operation occurred, this change will be instantly reflected to all other replication nodes. The technology for real-time requirements are higher for commercial applications.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Asynchronous replication, all replicated data nodes in a certain period of time is not synchronized. If the replication environment, one node in the replication of data updates occurred, this change will be in different dissemination and application services to all other replication nodes. Between these different services can be spaced a few seconds, a few minutes, hours, or a few days. Temporary copy of data between nodes is not synchronized, but will eventually spread to ensure that all copy data between nodes consistent. <br /><br /> 2, the project situation <br /> This is a demand within and outside the network describes the structure of the examination and approval system. <br /> External network has a WEB (+ APPSERVER), a DB (ORACLE9.2, double NIC), responsible for receiving approval to declare the results and feedback. <br /> Within the network have a WEB (+ APPSERVER), a DB (ORACLE9.2, double NIC), responsible for receiving approval of reporting and feedback results, and treatment through the approval process for approval from outside of the declaration. <br /> From the foregoing, the network features include the external network functions, but need CA certificate to declare the external network, the network does not. <br /> According to the relevant provisions of confidentiality, within and outside the government system must be physically isolated network, so the declaration is received outside the network and not immediately respond to the internal network, the same token, the results within the network can not be quickly fed back to the external network. <br /><br /> Technology choice ` <br /> We chose ORACLE asynchronous hand-copy, copy the main end the following functions: <br /> 1. The external network data is copied to a new report within the network; <br /> 2. To the network on the results reported back to the external network. <br /><br /> Operation to achieve because the normal working hours, both inside and outside the network can not stop the inside and outside the network can not physically connected. Then set each night from 18:00 to 18:15 (or other period) maintenance period, all the time inside and outside the network to stop operations by the system administrator to DB with internal and external networks are connected to disconnect all network cables, with a straight line of the two DB connections networking, user interface provided by ORACLE, the outer end manually refresh the network records. <br /><br /><br /> 3, the specific implementation steps <br /><br /> The following are the technical parameters used in the script, the same table structure inside and outside the network, and has a primary key. <br /><br /> Intranet Extranet <br /> IP 192.168.0.50 192.168.0.100 <br /> SID ORANEI ORAWAI <br /> Table LAWTABLE <br /> REGISTER <br /> USERINFO <br /> ... ... <br /> A total of 68 tables LAWTABLE <br /> REGISTER <br /> 2 tables login / password HOLEN / HOLEN HOLEN / HOLEN <br /><br /> The following is to the customer to install the SQL scripts used <br /><br /> Step One: Configure the network, ie end MASTER <br /> - Version: 2.0 <br /> - Revised by: Chen</font> </p> <font color=\"#003366\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"mailto:holen@263.net\">holen@263.net</a></font> <br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">- Time :2003-6-8 15:30 <br /> - Within the network as a MASTER <br /> - Create the network users HOLEN <br /><br /> CONN SYSTEM / PASSWORD @ ORANEI <br /><br /> CREATE USER &quot;HOLEN&quot; PROFILE &quot;DEFAULT&quot; IDENTIFIED BY &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> GRANT &quot;CONNECT&quot; TO &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> GRANT &quot;DBA&quot; TO &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> GRANT &quot;RESOURCE&quot; TO &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> - Into the network database backup into the dos down to complete (Table LAWTABLE, REGISTER, and other tables) <br /><br /> Step Two: Configure the network, which MASTER-side (continued) <br /> - Need to copy (sync) on the table for the user under HOLEN LAWTABLE, REGISTER <br /><br /> - Create a replication environment repadmin user management <br /> <strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://bbs.ixdba.net\">IXDBA.NET Community Forums</a></font></strong> <br /> CREATE USER REPADMIN IDENTIFIED BY REPADMIN; <br /> ALTER USER REPADMIN DEFAULT TABLESPACE USERS; <br /> ALTER USER REPADMIN TEMPORARY TABLESPACE TEMP; <br /> GRANT connect, resource TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Repadmin user rights granted to the current site can manage any of the main group <br /> EXECUTE dbms_repcat_admin.grant_admin_any_schema (\'\'\'\' REPADMIN\'\'\'\'); <br /><br /> - Repadmin user privileges can be granted to any table to create snapshot logs <br /> GRANT comment any table TO REPADMIN; <br /> GRANT lock any table TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Specify the repadmin user propagator, and grant permission to perform any procedure <br /> EXECUTE dbms_defer_sys.register_propagator (\'\'\'\' REPADMIN\'\'\'\'); <br /> GRANT execute any procedure TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Distribution of proxy snapshot administration permissions to repadmin, list_of_gnames is null, means the group can manage all the objects <br /> BEGIN <br /> dbms_repcat_admin.register_user_repgroup ( <br /> username =&gt;\'\'\'\'repadmin\'\'\'\', <br /> privilege_type =&gt;\'\'\'\'proxy_snapadmin\'\'\'\', <br /> list_of_gnames =&gt; NULL); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - Allocation\'\'\'\'receiver\'\'\'\'rights to repadmin <br /> BEGIN <br /> dbms_repcat_admin.register_user_repgroup ( <br /> username =&gt;\'\'\'\'repadmin\'\'\'\', <br /> privilege_type =&gt;\'\'\'\'receiver\'\'\'\', <br /> list_of_gnames =&gt; NULL); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> GRANT select any table TO repadmin; <br /><br /> - The establishment of the ORANEI the main group, the main group called HOLEN_MASTER, and the main group to add a table <br /> - To establish a replication of the main group <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.CREATE_MASTER_REPGROUP ( <br /> gname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN_MASTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> qualifier =&gt;\'\'\'\'\'\'\'\', <br /> group_comment =&gt;\'\'\'\'\'\'\'\'); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> CONNECT REPADMIN / REPADMIN; <br /><br /><br /> - Add tables to the replication group object LAWTABLE <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.CREATE_MASTER_REPOBJECT ( <br /> gname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN_MASTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> type =&gt;\'\'\'\'TABLE\'\'\'\', <br /> oname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; LAWTABLE &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> sname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> copy_rows =&gt; TRUE, <br /> use_existing_object =&gt;</font>TRUE); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - Create a snapshot of the corresponding log <br /> CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG <br /> ON &quot;HOLEN&quot;. &quot;LAWTABLE&quot; <br /> TABLESPACE &quot;SYSTEM&quot; <br /> WITH PRIMARY KEY <br /> EXCLUDING NEW VALUES; <br /><br /> - Generate Replication Support <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.GENERATE_REPLICATION_SUPPORT ( <br /> sname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> oname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; LAWTABLE &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> type =&gt;\'\'\'\'TABLE\'\'\'\', <br /> min_communication =&gt; TRUE, <br /> generate_80_compatible =&gt; FALSE); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - Add tables to the replication group object REGISTER <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.CREATE_MASTER_REPOBJECT ( <br /> gname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN_MASTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> type =&gt;\'\'\'\'TABLE\'\'\'\', <br /> oname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; REGISTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> sname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> copy_rows =&gt; TRUE, <br /> use_existing_object =&gt; TRUE); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> CREATE SNAPSHOT LOG <br /> ON &quot;HOLEN&quot;. &quot;REGISTER&quot; <br /> TABLESPACE &quot;SYSTEM&quot; <br /> WITH PRIMARY KEY <br /> EXCLUDING NEW VALUES; <br /><br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.GENERATE_REPLICATION_SUPPORT ( <br /> sname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> oname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; REGISTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> type =&gt;\'\'\'\'TABLE\'\'\'\', <br /> min_communication =&gt; TRUE, <br /> generate_80_compatible =&gt; FALSE); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - MASTER-side configuration is completed <br /><br /> Step Three: Configure the external network, that is, end SNAPSHOT <br /> - Outside the network as SNAPSHOT <br /> - Create the external network users HOLEN <br /><br /> CONN SYSTEM / PASSWORD @ ORAWAI <br /><br /> - Create a regular user <br /> CREATE USER &quot;HOLEN&quot; PROFILE &quot;DEFAULT&quot; IDENTIFIED BY &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> GRANT &quot;CONNECT&quot; TO &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> GRANT &quot;DBA&quot; TO &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /> GRANT &quot;RESOURCE&quot; TO &quot;HOLEN&quot;; <br /><br /> - Create a snapshot of end user management repadmin replication environment <br /> CREATE USER REPADMIN IDENTIFIED BY REPADMIN; <br /> ALTER USER REPADMIN DEFAULT TABLESPACE USERS; <br /> ALTER USER REPADMIN TEMPORARY TABLESPACE TEMP; <br /> GRANT connect, resource TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Repadmin user rights granted to the current site can manage any of the main group <br /> EXECUTE dbms_repcat_admin.grant_admin_any_schema (\'\'\'\' REPADMIN\'\'\'\'); <br /><br /> - Repadmin user privileges can be granted to any table to create snapshot logs <br /> GRANT comment any table TO REPADMIN; <br /> GRANT lock any table TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Specify the repadmin user propagator, and grant permission to perform any procedure <br /> EXECUTE dbms_defer_sys.register_propagator (\'\'\'\' REPADMIN\'\'\'\'); <br /> GRANT execute any procedure TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Grant repadmin user can create a snapshot <br /> GRANT create any snapshot TO REPADMIN; <br /> GRANT alter any snapshot TO REPADMIN; <br /><br /> - Outside the network to establish links within the network <br /> - Outside the network side need to add to the tree ORANEI <br /> CREATE PUBLIC DATABASE LINK ORANEI CONNECT TO REPADMIN IDENTIFIED BY REPADMIN USING\'\'\'\'ORANEI\'\'\'\'; <br /><br /> - Refresh Group HOLEN_REFRESH networks have been established outside <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REFRESH.MAKE ( <br /> name =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;.&quot; HOLEN_REFRESH &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> list =&gt;\'\'\'\'\'\'\'\', <br /> next_date =&gt; SYSDATE, <br /> interval =&gt;\'\'\'\'/* 1: Mins * / sysdate + 1 / (60 * 24 )\'\'\'\', <br /> implicit_destroy =&gt; FALSE, <br /> lax =&gt; FALSE, <br /> job =&gt; 0, <br /> rollback_seg =&gt; NULL, <br /> push_deferred_rpc =&gt; TRUE, <br /> refresh_after_errors =&gt; TRUE, <br /> purge_option =&gt; NULL, <br /> parallelism =&gt; NULL, <br /> heap_size =&gt; NULL); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - Outside the network to establish a snapshot group <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.CREATE_SNAPSHOT_REPGROUP ( <br /> gname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN_MASTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> master =&gt;\'\'\'\'ORANEI.US.ORACLE.COM\'\'\'\', <br /> propagation_mode =&gt;\'\'\'\'ASYNCHRONOUS\'\'\'\'); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - Create a snapshot, the snapshot belongs to the user in the table established under, in this case the user must first login with HOLEN <br /> CONNECT HOLEN / HOLEN; <br /><br /> - Create a snapshot LAWTABLE <br /> CREATE SNAPSHOT &quot;HOLEN&quot;. &quot;LAWTABLE&quot; <br /> REFRESH FAST FOR UPDATE <br /> AS SELECT * FROM &quot;HOLEN&quot;. &quot;LAWTABLE&quot; @ ORANEI.US.ORACLE.COM C <br /> / <br /><br /> - Adding the snapshot refresh group <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REFRESH.ADD ( <br /> name =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;.&quot; HOLEN_REFRESH &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> list =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN &quot;.&quot; LAWTABLE &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> lax =&gt; TRUE); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - A snapshot of the snapshot group joined <br /> BEGIN <br /> DBMS_REPCAT.CREATE_SNAPSHOT_REPOBJECT ( <br /> gname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; HOLEN_MASTER &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> sname =&gt; \'&amp; #39;\'\'&quot;HOLEN &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> oname =&gt;\'\'\'\'&quot; LAWTABLE &quot;\'\'\'\', <br /> type =&gt;\'\'\'\'SNAPSHOT\'\'\'\', <br /> min_communication =&gt; FALSE); <br /> END; <br /> / <br /><br /> - Create a snapshot REGISTER <br /> CREATE SNAPSHOT &quot;HOLEN&quot;. &quot;REGISTER&quot; <br /> REFRESH FAST FOR UPDATE <br /> AS SELECT * FROM &quot;HOLEN&quot;. &quot;REGISTER&quot; @ ORANEI.US.ORACLE.COM C','This paper introduces the advanced copy functions ORACLE, and through a practical project, the discussion inside and outside the network level in how to use advanced replication DB to achieve unity of internal and external network data, given the configuration script for your reference.  1, the...'),(232,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/c7/2128.html','http://www.ixdba.net','See also ORA-19809, oracle flashback features garbage','See_also_ORA19809_oracle_flashback_features_garbage','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Today View the database manager error log oradim.log found the following warning message: <br /> ORA-16038: log 3 sequence # 472 cannot be archived <br /> ORA-19809: limit exceeded for recovery files <br /> ORA-00312: online log 3 thread 1: \'C: \\ ORACLE \\ PRODUCT \\ 10.2.0 \\ ORADATA \\ CHEP \\ REDO03.LOG\'</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Checked and error messages <br /> ORA-19809: limit exceeded for recovery files <br /> Cause: The limit for recovery files specified by the DB_RECOVERY_FILE_DEST_SIZE was exceeded. <br /> Action: The error is accompanied by 19804. See message 19804 for further details.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">ORA-19804: cannot reclaim string bytes disk space from string limit <br /> Cause: Oracle cannot reclaim disk space of specified bytes from the DB_RECOVERY_FILE_DEST_SIZE limit. <br /> Action: There are five possible solutions: <br /> Take frequent backup of recovery area using RMAN. <br /> Consider changing RMAN retention policy. <br /> Consider changing RMAN archivelog deletion policy. <br /> 4) Add disk space and increase DB_RECOVERY_FILE_DEST_SIZE. <br /> 5) Delete files from recovery area using RMAN.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">oracle10g default, archived logs are stored in the flash recovery area, when building a database if you use the default settings, <br /> Flash recovery area should be 2G, space is filled it can not be filed later, you can use the following command to see its size and storage location <br /> SQL&gt; show parameter db_recovery_file_dest;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">NAME TYPE VALUE <br /> ------------------------------------ ----------- --- --------------------------- <br /> db_recovery_file_dest string / opt/oracle/product/10.2.0/flash_recovery_area <br /> db_recovery_file_dest_size big integer 2G</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Solution: <br /> 1. Increase Flash Recovery Area <br /> ALTER SYSTEM SET db_recovery_file_dest_size = 4g scope = both;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">2. Modify the file settings:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">The default path is occupied db_recovery_file_dest log_archive_dest_10, and log_archive_dest_n and log_archive_dest can not be used, so there needs to be done the following:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Method One:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">(1) blank DB_RECOVERY_FILE_DEST</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; alter system set db_recovery_file_dest =\'\';</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">(2) re-run log_archive_dest set</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_dest = \'/ export / home / arch\';</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">System altered.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Method Two:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Set the archive to another directory: <br /> SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_dest_1 = \'location = / export / home / arch\'; <br /> System altered.</font> </p><p><br /> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">Finally, you can see through the show parameter log_archive_dest</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Tahoma\" size=\"2\">3. Transfer or delete the flash recovery area in the archive logs.</font> </p>','Today View the database manager error log oradim.log found the following warning message:  ORA-16038: log 3 sequence # 472 cannot be archived  ORA-19809: limit exceeded for recovery files  ORA-00312: online log 3 thread 1: \'C: \\ ORACLE \\ PRODUCT \\ 10.2.0 \\ ORADATA \\ CHEP \\...'),(233,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/31/2095.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle10g in the conversion between SCN and TimeStamp','Oracle10g_in_the_conversion_between_SCN_and_TimeStamp','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font color=\"#ff6600\">First, the system can be obtained by dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number current SCN values:</font> <br /></p><p> SQL&gt; col scn for 9999999999999 <br /> SQL&gt; select dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number scn from dual; <br /> SCN <br /> -------------- <br /> 8908390522972 <br /></p><p> <font color=\"#ff6600\">SCN through scn_to_timestamp function can be converted to a timestamp:</font> <br /></p><p> SQL&gt; select scn_to_timestamp (8908390522972) scn from dual; <br /> SCN <br /> -------------------------------------------------- ------------------------- <br /> 05-JAN-07 10.56.30.000000000 AM <br /> Then by the timestamp can be converted timestamp_to_scn SCN: <br /> SQL&gt; select timestamp_to_scn (scn_to_timestamp (8908390522972)) scn from dual; <br /> SCN <br /> -------------- <br /> 8908390522972 </p><p><br /> With these two functions, the final time, Oracle will be the relationship between SCN and established, before the Oracle10g, there is no way to get through the function of converting the corresponding relationship between SCN and time, the general analysis of the log can be obtained by logmnr. </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#ff6600\">But this function is converted to rely on internal data in the database records, for the ancient SCN can not convert</font> </p><p> Consider the following example: <br /></p><p> SQL&gt; select min (FIRST_CHANGE #) scn, max (FIRST_CHANGE #) scn from v $ archived_log; <br /> SCN SCN <br /> ------------------ ------------------ <br /> 8907349093953 8908393582271 <br /> SQL&gt; select scn_to_timestamp (8907349093953) scn from dual; <br /> select scn_to_timestamp (8907349093953) scn from dual <br /> * <br /> <font color=\"#ff0000\">ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-08181: specified number is not a valid system change number <br /> ORA-06512: at &quot;SYS.SCN_TO_TIMESTAMP&quot;, line 1 <br /> ORA-06512: at line 1</font> <br /></p><p> SQL&gt; select scn_to_timestamp (8908393582271) scn from dual; <br /> SCN <br /> -------------------------------------------------- ------------------------- <br /> 05-JAN-07 11.45.50.000000000 AM </p>','First, the system can be obtained by dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number current SCN...'),(234,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/b6/2045.html','http://www.ixdba.net','ORACLE SQL syntax and common data objects - data definition (DDL) part of the','ORACLE_SQL_syntax_and_common_data_objects__data_definition_DDL_part_of_the','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<html><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 20.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; mso-char-indent-count: 2.0\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Tahoma\">1.CREATE</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Tahoma; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Tahoma\">(create tables, indexes, views, synonyms, procedures, functions,</s