\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">flashback</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">mode can not use</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">DML</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">statements, but can only view the data, using the usual methods can not recover the data, we use the following method to restore data:</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"></span></p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 22pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-char-indent-count: 2.0\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">insert into exitgogo</span> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 22pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-char-indent-count: 2.0\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">select * from exitgogo as of timestamp to_timestamp (\'2005-01-21 14:48:0 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\');</span> </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 22pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; mso-char-indent-count: 2.0\"> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Ã‹ÂŽÃŒÂ¥_GB2312\">Sentence statement means that the table</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\">exitgogo 2005-01-21 14:48:0</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Ã‹ÂŽÃŒÂ¥_GB2312\">in the records of this time point inserted into the current time</span>exitgogo <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Ã‹ÂŽÃŒÂ¥_GB2312\">table.</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 11pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"></span></p>','empty\n'),(263,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/44/1884.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle SMON_SCN_TIME','oracle_SMON_SCN_TIME','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <strong>SMON_SCN_TIME</strong> is the Oracle database system tables, for the conduct of secondary recovery and other functions. <br /> In Oracle9iR2 in, SMON_SCN_TIME be updated every 5 minutes. </p><p><table><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#999999\" width=\"500\"><pre> [Oracle @ jumper oracle] $ sqlplus &quot;/ as sysdba&quot; </pre><pre> SQL * Plus: Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production on Mon Dec 19 18:19:27 2005 </pre><pre> Copyright (c) 1982, 2002, Oracle Corporation. All rights reserved. </pre><pre><br /> Connected to: <br /> Oracle9i Enterprise Edition Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production <br /> With the Partitioning option <br /> JServer Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production </pre><pre> SQL&gt; alter session set nls_date_format = \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\'; </pre><pre> Session altered. </pre><pre> SQL&gt; select * from smon_scn_time where rownum &lt;10; </pre><pre> THREAD TIME_MP TIME_DP SCN_WRP SCN_BAS <br /> ---------- ---------- ------------------- ---------- - --------- <br /> 2005-12-18 22:37:15 2565931 11134916635 <br /> 2005-12-18 22:37:28 2565979 11134916648 <br /> <strong>2005-12-18 22:43:49</strong> 2566224 11134917029 <br /> <strong>2005-12-18 22:48:57</strong> 2566325 11134917336 <br /> 2005-12-18 22:54:04 2566426 11134917643 <br /> 2005-12-18 22:59:11 2566527 11134917950 <br /> 2005-12-18 23:04:18 2566628 11134918257 <br /> 2005-12-18 23:09:25 2566733 11134918564 <br /> 2005-12-18 23:14:33 2566836 11134918871 </pre><pre> 9 rows selected. </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> SMON_SCN_TIME 5 days of data records, which is 1440 ((5d x 24h x 12m = 1440) records. <br /> So Oracle9iR2, the table attribute modification time and the flashback time difference should be at least 5 minutes. Otherwise there will be ORA-01466 error. </p><p><table><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#999999\" width=\"500\"><pre> [Oracle @ jumper oracle] $ sqlplus eygle / eygle </pre><pre> SQL * Plus: Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production on Mon Dec 19 19:34:53 2005 </pre><pre> Copyright (c) 1982, 2002, Oracle Corporation. All rights reserved. </pre><pre><br /> Connected to: <br /> Oracle9i Enterprise Edition Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production <br /> With the Partitioning option <br /> JServer Release 9.2.0.4.0 - Production </pre><pre> 19:34:58 SQL&gt; col myscn for 9999999999999999 <br /> 19:34:58 SQL&gt; variable myscn number; <br /> 19:34:58 SQL&gt; create table eygle (c1 number); </pre><pre> Table created. </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; exec: myscn: = dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number (); </pre><pre> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; print myscn; </pre><pre> MYSCN <br /> <font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://bbs.ixdba.net\"><strong>IXDBA.NET Community Forums</strong></a></font> <br /> ----------------- <br /> 107374274756 </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; insert into eygle values (1); </pre><pre> 1 row created. </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; commit; </pre><pre> Commit complete. </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; exec: myscn: = dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number (); </pre><pre> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; print myscn; </pre><pre> MYSCN <br /> ----------------- <br /> 107374274777 </pre><pre> 19:35:00 SQL&gt; select * from eygle as of scn (: myscn); <br /> select * from eygle as of scn (: myscn) <br /> * <br /> ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-01466: unable to read data - table definition has changed </pre><pre> 19:41:10 SQL&gt; select * from eygle as of scn (: myscn); <br /> select * from eygle as of scn (: myscn) <br /> * <br /> ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-01466: unable to read data - table definition has changed </pre><pre> 19:43:03 SQL&gt; select dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number myscn from dual; </pre><pre> MYSCN <br /> ----------------- <br /> 107374274944 </pre><pre> 19:43:15 SQL&gt; select * from eygle as of scn 107374274944; </pre><pre> C1 <br /> ---------- <br /> 1 </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p>','SMON_SCN_TIME is the Oracle database system tables, for the conduct of secondary recovery and other functions.  In Oracle9iR2 in, SMON_SCN_TIME be updated every 5 minutes....'),(264,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/74/1883.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle9i in flashback some of the problems','oracle9i_in_flashback_some_of_the_problems','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In 9i, if you use the undo tablespace oracle automatically manage rollback segments, by setting undo_retention retained in the undo tablespace data for so long, so to avoid snapshot too old error, but also through flashback and get a point in time previous data, but to emphasize a few points here: <br /></font> <font color=\"#ff0000\"><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1: flashback feature does not support the DDL statement, if you have not truncate the data to find out back <br /> 2: It looks like this <br /> oracle generated every 5 minutes will be recorded SCN that corresponds to a TIME usually only records the SCN, but will be recorded every 5 minutes SCN and TIME <br /> When using the time to do flashback when the bias is likely to <br /><br /> Requests for experimental 4! ! ! !</font></font> <br /><br /><br /><br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Experiment 1: Using flashback features <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number from dual; <br /><br /> GET_SYSTEM_CHANGE_NUMBER <br /> ------------------------ <br /> 36,501,397 <br /><br /> SQL&gt; insert into tf values (3); <br /><br /> 1 row created. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; commit; <br /><br /> Commit complete. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.enable_at_system_change_number (36501397); <br /><br /> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select * from tf; <br /><br /> A <br /> ---------- <br /> 1 <br /> 2 <br /><br /><br /> Experiment 2: flashback does not support DDL <br /><br /> Then the above steps <br /> SQL&gt; truncate table tf; <br /><br /> Table truncated. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.enable_at_system_change_number (36501397); <br /><br /> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select * from tf; <br /> select * from tf <br /> * <br /> ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-01466: unable to read data - table definition has changed <br /><br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.disable; <br /><br /><br /> Experiment 3: We create a table, to immediately see the effect, all processes in 5 minutes, it is time to complete the section, we will be unable to query the data! <br /><br /> SQL&gt; drop table tf; <br /><br /> Table dropped. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number from dual; <br /><br /> GET_SYSTEM_CHANGE_NUMBER <br /> ------------------------ <br /> 36,509,390 <br /><br /> SQL&gt; create table tf (a number); <br /><br /> Table created. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; insert into tf values (1); <br /><br /> 1 row created. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; commit; <br /><br /> Commit complete. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select dbms_flashback.get_system_change_number from dual; <br /><br /> GET_SYSTEM_CHANGE_NUMBER <br /> ------------------------ <br /> 36,509,490 <br /><br /> SQL&gt; insert into tf values (2); <br /><br /> 1 row created. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; commit; <br /><br /> Commit complete. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.enable_at_system_change_number (36509390); <br /><br /> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select * from tf; <br /> select * from tf <br /> * <br /> ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-01466: unable to read data - table definition has changed <br /><br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.disable; <br /><br /> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.enable_at_system_change_number (36509490); <br /><br /> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select * from tf; <br /> select * from tf <br /> * <br /> ERROR at line 1: <br /> ORA-01466: unable to read data - table definition has changed <br /><br /><br /> SQL&gt; exec dbms_flashback.disable; <br /><br /> PL / SQL procedure successfully completed. <br /><br /><br /> Experiment IV: The time to do, we carefully look at the following relationship between time and data! <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\') from dual; <br /><br /> TO_CHAR (SYSDATE, \'YY <br /> ------------------- <br /> 2003-04-26 17:09:04 <font color=\"#ff0000\">create table before the time time1</font> <br /><br /> SQL&gt; create table test1 (a number); <br /><br /> Table created. <br /><br /> SQL&gt; select to_char (sysdate, \'yyyy-mm-dd hh24: mi: ss\') from dual; <br /></font> </p><p> <strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\">www.ixdba.net</a></font></strong> </p><br /><br /> TO_CHAR (SYSDATE, \'YY <br /> ------------------- <br /> 2003-04-26 17:09:20','In 9i, if you use the undo tablespace oracle automatically manage rollback segments, by setting undo_retention retained in the undo tablespace data for so long, so to avoid snapshot too old error, but also through flashback and get a point in time previous data, but to emphasize a few points here: ...'),(265,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/ef/1873.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle how to view a patch has been played','oracle_how_to_view_a_patch_has_been_