 Ã‚Â </span> 1 NO <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">Ã‚Â  </span> INACTIVE <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â  </span> 785843 07-AUG-06</span></font></font></font> </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"BACKGROUND: #cccccc; MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt\"> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><font color=\"#000000\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt\"><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â  </span> 4 <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â  </span> 1 <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes\">Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Ã‚Â  </span></span></font></font></font> </p>','I. Ã‚Â   V $ LOG: STATUS status refers to the GROUP...'),(269,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/5b/1057.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Oracle database operations by some common','Oracle_database_operations_by_some_common','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> A: Database startup steps:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> ORACLE database instance and the database is divided into two parts, the database file, the instance is a memory area, add some background processes, memory area that is usually said that the data cache, shared pool and so is the background process, such as checkpoint, log writer, dbwriter and other data files and SQL SERVER\'s no different in concept, so that data files, memory, process to form a database. <br /> 1: First test parameter file init (sid). Ora, is the initialization parameter file, obtained from the parameter memory configuration parameter file, the database name and other information, for instance starts, so that memory is opened, the process has its own launch, this state is nomount. which Oracle database is started, first find the orapw &lt;sid&gt; the password file, if the file does not exist, then start looking, orapw the password file. <br /> 2: According to the information on the steps of the parameter file, control file from the parameter file for the address, add him to obtain the physical database files, but does not check the data file exists, this is called mount, <br /> 3: read the data file, open the database, perform some recovery checkpoint. The state is open.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Second: Change the instance name steps: <br /> 1: change the original instance of the parameter file init (sid). Ora, change the configuration parameters of a new instance of the named instance name <br /> *. Instance_name = \'gaogao1\' <br /> 2: change the original parameter file for the new instance with the new name of the parameter file: <br /> If mv initgaogao.ora initgaogao1.ora <br /> 2: Create a new instance of the new password file: <br /> orapwd file = orapw (sid) password = password entries = 5</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">III: on the database startup parameter files. <br /> 1: General, when the database instance in the open, oracle reads the parameter file is the process: first the database to find SPFILE (sid). Ora, if found, to look for INIT (sid). Ora, are looking for is not in the above will go to the init.ora. <br /> 2: generally create the database after the completion of the system will generate spfile (sid). Ora file. If you want to change the size of SGA. It would have to manually create a PFILE can adjust to the SGA. Because the spfile (sid). Ora is a binary value of the file. Can not use a text editor. <br /> 3: CREATE PFILE FROM SPFILE; in the dbs directory so you can automatically create a init (sid). Ora file. <br /> 4: If you want to start with the PFILE file, you can start the path to the specified file, or the spfile (sid). Ora to change the name on it.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Four: the user object from a table space gaojf into another table space gaojf1 steps:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1: REVOKE UNLIMITED TABLESPACE FROM &quot;GAOJF1&quot;; # system permissions in gaojf1 cancel unlimited tablespace</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">2: ALTER USER &quot;GAOJF1&quot; QUOTA 20 M ON CICRO1; resource limits to users gaojf1 20m <br /> Or ALTER USER &quot;GAOJF1&quot; QUOTA UNLIMITED ON CICRO1; to the user gaojf1 resource limit for unlimited use. (Not free)</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">3: then use the export statement: <br /> imp gaojf1/gaojf1 file = cicrotablestest.dmp fromuser = gaojf touser = gaojf1 ignore = y tablespaces = cicro1; <br /> Or <br /> imp gaojf1/gaojf1 file = cicrotablestest.dmp full = y, ignore = y; <br /> ok, let\'s see it! <br /> Five: the use of space on the table <br /> alter user hr quota 200m on test1; specified tablespace test1 hr user the use of limit of 200 megabytes. <br /> alter user hr quota 0 on example; hr in the table space specified using the example of the limits to 0, that is not specified limit (no). <br /> alter user hr quota unlimited on test1; designated space in the table test1 hr limit for unrestricted use (non-free, is the unlimited use). <br /> Only one mode (TABLES, FROMUSER, or FULL) can be specified # is the time of import, only from tables, fromuser, full specified in a pattern.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">IMP <a href=\"mailto:sales/sales@test1\">Sales / Sales @ Test1</a> FROMUSER = ZJJ touser = Sales rows = n ignore = n commit = y TABLESPACES = test File = D: \\ exp \\ zjj.dmp log = d: \\ exp \\ zjjimp01.log # into the format of the data <br /> imp hr / hr file = e: \\ hr.dmp log = e: \\ hrimp.log fromuser = hr touser = test1 <br /> alter table (tablename) move tablespace tablespace name of a table # to move to another table space.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> View the table of the table space after import <br /> select * from user_all_tables where table_name = \'table name\' <br /> View the table space usage <br /> select sum (bytes) / (1024 * 1024) as free_space, tablespace_name from dba_free_space group by tablespace_name; <br /> Six: Change the password for sys and the sysem Alter user sys identified by new password Alter user system identified by new password</font> </p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\">IXDBA.NET Technical Community</a></font></strong> <br /></font> <p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Seven: Change the database archiving mode: <br /> Through the v $ database, view database is in Archive Mode: <br /> SQL&gt; select log_mode from v $ database; <br /> Or by <br /> SQL&gt; archive log list; <br /> If not, Archive mode, you set the database is running in archive mode: <br /> A: The database with the pfile file modification methods. <br /> (1): SQL&gt; shutdown immediate <br /> SQL&gt; startup mount <br /> SQL&gt; alter database archivelog; <br /> SQL&gt; alter database open; <br /> If Automaticarchival shown as &quot;Enabled&quot;, the database archiving mode is automatically archived. Otherwise need to manually archive or modify the archive for the automatic archiving, such as: normal shutdown the database, in the parameter file init (sid). Ora add the following parameter SQL&gt; shutdown immediate <br /> Modify the init (sid). Ora: <br /> LOG_ARCHIVE_START = TRUE <br /> log_archive_dest = / opt/oracle/product/9.2.0/dbs/archgaogao (archived at the value of storage location can define) <br /> log_archive_format = &quot;T% TS% S. ARC&quot; (the file name of archived log file format) <br /> II: a database when used to modify the time of the binary spfile method, that by order operation. <br /> (1): SQL&gt; alter database archivelog; (set to archive mode) <br /> Set to automatically archive: (restart the database in force) <br /> (2): SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_start = true scope = spfile; <br /> Set the archive path: (restart the database in force) <br /> (3): SQL&gt; alter system set log_archive_dest = \'/ opt/oracle/product/9.2.0/dbs/archexitgogo\' scope = spfile; <br /> Restart the database: <br /> SQL&gt; startup force <br /> Then, restart the database, then Oracle Database will automatically archive the way work in Archive mode. Where the parameters are specified LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST archive log file path, suggestions and Oracle database files have different hard disk, on the one hand to reduce disk I / O competition, on the other hand can also avoid damage to the hard disk where the database file after the files are missing. Can also specify the archive path to the tape, and other physical storage devices, but may want to consider reading and writing speed, writing conditions and performance and other factors. <br /> If the database is running, you can not immediately re-starting, to set it as automatic archiving mode, do the following: <br /><br /> SVRMGRL&gt; ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG START; <br /><br /> To set the non-automatic archiving mode (cancel the automatic archiving), then: <br /><br /> SVRMGRL&gt; ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG STOP; <br /><br /> However, if after re-starting the database, modify the results of the statement on the failure, and automatic archiving parameter settings, or in accordance with the system file to set the value of LOG_ARCHIVE_START.</font> </font&gt; </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Manual archiving: ALTER SYSTEM ARCHIVE LOG ALL; <br /><br /> This point in time the archive redo logs <br /> SVRMGRL&gt; archive log all;</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Note: When the database is in ARCHIVE mode, we must ensure that the specified archive path can be written, otherwise the database will hang until all the archived information can be archived before they can use. <br /> Eight: How to view the data files through the control file, the file location on the value of controlfile does not look to know <br /> [Oracle @ localhost cicro] $ strings control01.ctl <br /> ] \\ [Z <br /> CICRO <br /> ! CICRO <br /> cicro <br /> cicro <br /> &quot;AoE <br /> &qu