soNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt 72','Part 1: Installing Linux ...'),(273,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/14/1185.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle basics (physical structure)','oracle_basics_physical_structure','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong>1, the physical structure (the control files, data files, redo log files, parameter files, archived files, password files) <br /><br /></strong> The data stored in a database physical file on disk, to be used, transferred to the memory. <br /><br /> Where the control files, data files, redo log files, trace files and alert log (trace files, alert files) is a database file; <br /><br /> Parameter file (parameter file) password file (password file) 1.1 data files non-database files: store data files. Data file typically represents the use of disk space according to their determined and a number of Oracle database volume. <br /><br /> For performance reasons, each type of data in the corresponding one or a series of documents in the files on different disks. <br /><br /> types: <br /> . Data dictionary. Data <br /> . Redo data. Index <br /> . Temporary data, etc. 1.2 control file: to maintain and verify database integrity contains the necessary information, for example, the control file is used to identify the data files and redo log files, a database requires at least one control file. <br /><br /> Control file contents. Database name. Table space information. All data file name and location. All redo log file name and location. The current log sequence number. Checkpoint information. Redo logs and archive on the current status of the process of using the control file control file to Oracle directed to other parts of the database file. Start an instance, Oracle reads the control parameter file from the file name and location. Install the database, Oracle opens the control file. Eventually open the database, Oracle reads the data from the control file and open the list of files where each file. <br /><br /> 1.3 redo log files: with the changes to the database record, so that in case of failure to enable data recovery. A database requires at least two redo log files. <br /><br /> 1.4 trace files and alert log (Trace Files and Alert Files) <br /><br /> In each instance running in the background process has a trace file (trace file) associated with it. Trace file records encountered in the process of background information on major events. <br /><br /> Warning Log (Alert Log) is a special trace file, there is a trace file for each database, synchronization and error messages recorded in the database. <br /><br /> 1.5 parameter files: including a large number of features Oracle database instance settings, such as the following settings: <br /><br /> . Database control file location. Oracle is used to cache data read from the disk the amount of memory. The default choice of the optimization process. <br /><br /> And the related database files, perform two important functions a&gt; for the database control files that 2&gt; archive log for the database that the target of 1.6 archive: the offline redo log files is a copy, these copies may be for failure from the media recovery is necessary. <br /><br /> 1.7 password file: authentication which users have permission to start and stop Oracle routines. <br /><br /> <strong>2, the logical structure (tablespaces, segments, district, block)</strong> <br /><br /> Table space: a database of the basic logical structure, a series of data files collection. <br /><br /> Section: the object space occupied in the database. <br /><br /> Area: one reserved for a large data storage space. <br /><br /> Block: ORACLE most basic unit of storage in a database when the specified. <br /><br /> <strong>3, the memory allocation (SGA and PGA)</strong> <br /><br /> SGA: is used to store database information in the memory area, the information sharing process for the database. It contains the Oracle server\'s data and control information, which resides in the Oracle server computer to the actual memory allocation, if not go down to the actual memory write virtual memory. <br /><br /> PGA: contains a single server process or a single background process data and control information, and contrary to several processes to share the SGA, PGA is used only by a process of regional, PGA is allocated in the creation process, when the termination of the process of recovery. <br /><br /> <strong>4, the background process</strong> &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; including data write process (Database Writer, DBWR), log writing process (Log Writer, LGWR), System Monitor (System Monitor, SMON), process control (Process Monitor, PMON) checkpoint process (Checkpoint Process, CKPT), archiving process, service process, the user process)</font></font>','empty\n'),(274,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/54/1222.html','http://www.ixdba.net','basic oracle: Oracle in the use of null','basic_oracle_Oracle_in_the_use_of_null','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Q: What is NULL? <br /> A: We do not know what specific data, that is unknown, can be NULL, <br /> We call it empty, ORACLE in the table with an empty zero-length values. <br /> ORACLE allows any type of data field is empty, except for the following two situations: <br /> 1, the primary key field (primary key), <br /> 2, the definition has been added to the field NOT NULL constraints <br /><br /> Description: <br /> 1, is equivalent to no value, is unknown. <br /> 2, NULL and 0, the empty string, spaces are different. <br /> 3, the null value to do addition, subtraction, multiplication, division and other arithmetic operations, the result is still empty. <br /> 4, NULL handling to use NVL function. <br /> 5, comparing the use of keywords &quot;is null&quot; and &quot;is not null&quot;. <br /> 6, the null value can not be indexed, so check the data when some matches may not be detected, <br /> count (*), the use of nvl (column name, 0), then check deal. <br /> 7, sorting the data were greater than the other (the index in descending order by default, small Ã¢Â†Â’ large), <br /> So NULL values are always at the bottom. <br /><br /> Usage: <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 from dual where null = null; <br /> No records found <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 from dual where null =\'\'; <br /> No records found <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 from dual where\'\'=\'\'; <br /> No records found <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 from dual where null is null; <br /> 1 <br /> --------- <br /> 1 <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 from dual where nvl (null, 0) = nvl (null, 0); <br /> 1 <br /> --------- <br /> 1 <br /> Of null values do addition, subtraction, multiplication, division and other arithmetic operations, the result is still empty. <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 + null from dual; <br /> SQL&gt; select 1-null from dual; <br /> SQL&gt; select 1 * null from dual; <br /> SQL&gt; select 1/null from dual; <br /> Query to a record. <br /> Note: This record is null SQL statement that <br /> Set some as a null value <br /> update table1 set out 1 = NULL where column 1 is not null; <br /> An existing product sales table sale, table structure is: <br /> month char (6) - month <br /> sellnumber (10,2) - the amount of monthly sales <br /> create table sale (month char (6), sell number); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200001 \', 1000); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200002 \', 1100); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200003 \', 1200); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200004 \', 1300); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200005 \', 1400); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200006 \', 1500); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200007 \', 1600); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200101 \', 1100); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200202 \', 1200); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200301 \', 1300); <br /> insert into sale values (\'200008 \', 1000); <br /> insert into sale (month) values (\'200009 \'); <br /> (Note: this record sell is empty) <br /> commit; <br /> 12 records total input <br /> SQL&gt; select * from sale where sell like \'%\'; <br /> MONTH SELL <br /> ------ --------- <br /> 2000011000 <br /> 2000021100 <br /> 2000031200 <br /> 2000041300 <br /> 2000051400 <br /> 2000061500 <br /> 2000071600 <br /> 2001011100 <br /> 2002021200 <br /> 2003011300 <br /> 2000081000 <br /><br /> Query to 11 records. <br /><br /> Results show: <br /> Results illustrate the value of SQL statement to query the column NULL fields not required at this time the situation on the field is NULL other treatment. <br /> SQL&gt; select * from sale where sell like \'%\' or sell is null;</font>','empty\n'),(275,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/75/1236.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Collection of commonly used basic syntax of Oracle operations','Collection_of_commonly_used_basic_syntax_of_Oracle_operations','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<html><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>1, Table</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create table test (names varchar2 (12), <br /> dates date, <br /> num int, <br /> dou double);</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>2 views</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace view vi_test as <br /> select * from test;</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>3 synonyms</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace synonym aa <br /> for dbusrcard001.aa;</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>4, stored procedures</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace produce dd (v_id in employee.empoy_id% type) <br /> as <br /> begin <br /><br /> end <br /> dd;</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>5, the function</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace function ee (v_id in employee% rowtype) return varchar (15) <br /> is <br /> var_test varchar2 (15); <br /> begin <br /> return var_test; <br /> exception when others then <br /><br /> end</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>6, the definition of the three trigger</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace trigger ff <br /> alter delete <br /> on test <br /> for each row <br /> declare <br /> begin <br /> delete from test; <br /> if sql% rowcount &lt;0 or sql% rowcount is null then <br /> rais_replaction_err (-20004, &quot;error&quot;) <br /> end if <br /> end</font> </pre><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace trigger gg <br /> alter insert <br /> on test <br /> for each row <br /> declare <br /> begin <br /> if: old.names =: new.names then <br /> raise_replaction_err (-2003, &quot;coding repeat&quot;); <br /> end if <br /> end</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create or replace trigger hh <br /> for update <br /> on test <br /> for each row <br /> declare <br /> begin <br /> if updating then <br /> if: old.names &lt;&gt;: new.names then <br /> reaise_replaction_err (-2002, &quot;keyword can not be modified&quot;) <br /> end if <br /> end if <br /> end</font> </p></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>7, define the cursor</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">declare <br /> <font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\"><strong>IXDBA.NET Technical Community</strong></a></font> <br /> cursor aa is <br /> select names, num from test; <br /> begin <br /> for bb in aa <br /> loop <br /> if bb.names = &quot;ORACLE&quot; then <br /><br /> end if <br /> end loop; <br /><br /> end</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>8, speed optimization, the previous statement is not a statement after a few times faster</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">select names, dates <br /> from test, b <br /> where test.names = b.names (+) and <br /> b.names is null and <br /> b.dates&gt; date (\'2003-01-01 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \') <br /><br /> select names, dates <br /> from test <br /> where names not in (select names <br /> from b <br /> where dates&gt; to_date (\'2003-01-01 \',\' yyyy-mm-dd \'))</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>9, find duplicate records</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">select names, num <br /> from test <br /> where rowid! = (select max (rowid) <br /> from test b <br /> where b.names = test.names and <br </html></font>/&gt; B.num = test.num) </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>10, the lookup table TEST in the time before the latest 10 records</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">select * from (select * from test order by dates desc) where rownum &lt;11</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>11, serial number generation</strong></font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">create sequence row_id <br /> minvalue 1 <br /> maxvalue 9999999999999999999999 <br /> start with 1 <br /> increment by 1</font> </pre><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">insert into test values (row_id.nextval ,....)</font> </p></td></tr></tbody></table></p>','1,...'),(276,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/a1/1237.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle database query is issued front','oracle_database_query_is_issued_front','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <strong><font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\">Q: How can I find out front is given sql statement?</font></font></strong> </p><p> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong>A: The</strong> specific steps are as follows:</font></font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Software Environment:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1, Windows 2000 + ORACLE 8.1.6 <br /> 2, ORACLE installation path: C: \\ ORANT</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Implementation:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Can use the following statement:</font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">select user_name, sql_text <br /> from v $ open_cursor <br /> where sid in (select sid from <br /> (Select sid, serial <br /> from v $ session <br /> where status =\'\'\'\' ACTIVE\'\'\'\'))</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Subquery:</font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">select sid, serial from v $ session <br /> where status =\'\'\'\' ACTIVE\'\'\'\'</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Detect inactive session is the sid.</font> </p><p><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\"><pre></pre><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">SQL&gt; desc v $ open_cursor <br /> Type the name space <br /> ----------------------------- ------- <br /> SADDR RAW (4) <br /> SID NUMBER <br /> USER_NAME VARCHAR2 (30) <br /> ADDRESS RAW (4) <br /> HASH_VALUE NUMBER <br /> SQL_TEXT VARCHAR2 (60)</font> </p></td></tr></tbody></table></p>','Q: How can I find out front is given sql...'),(277,'BLOG','BLOG','