ying_Bonding_Configuration\"><font color=\"#800080\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><span class=\"mw-headline\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Querying Bonding Configuration</span></span></font></font></a> </a&gt; <ul><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <font color=\"#800080\"><a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Bonding_Configuration\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bonding Configuration</span></a></font> </li><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Network_configuration\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Network configuration</span></font></a> </li></ul></li><li class=\"toclevel-1\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Switch_Configuration\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Switch Configuration</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-1\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#802.1q_VLAN_Support\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">802.1q VLAN Support</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-1\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Link_Monitoring\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Link Monitoring</span></font></a> <ul><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#ARP_Monitor_Operation\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">ARP Monitor Operation</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Configuring_Multiple_ARP_Targets\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Configuring Multiple ARP Targets</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#MII_Monitor_Operation\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7.3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">MII Monitor Operation</span></font></a> </li></ul></li><li class=\"toclevel-1\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Potential_Sources_of_Trouble\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">8</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Potential Sources of Trouble</span></font></a> <ul><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Adventures_in_Routing\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">8.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Adventures in Routing</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Ethernet_Device_Renaming\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">8.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Ethernet Device Renaming</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Painfully_Slow_Or_No_Failed_Link_Detection_By_Miimon\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\"><span class=\"toctext\">8.3</span> Painfully</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Slow Or No Failed Link Detection By Miimon</span></font></a> </li></ul></li><li class=\"toclevel-1\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#SNMP_agents\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">9</span> <span class=\"toctext\">SNMP agents</span></font></a> <ul><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Promiscuous_mode\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">9.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Promiscuous mode</span></font></a> </li></ul></li><li class=\"toclevel-1\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#Configuring_Bonding_for_High_Availability\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">10</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Configuring Bonding for High Availability</span></font></a> <ul><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#High_Availability_in_a_Single_Switch_Topology\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">10.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">High Availability in a Single Switch Topology</span></font></a> </li><li class=\"toclevel-2\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#High_Availability_in_a_Multiple_Switch_Topology\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">10.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">High Availability in a Multiple Switch Topology</span></font></a> <ul><li class=\"toclevel-3\"> <a href=\"http://www.linuxfoundation.org/en/Net:Bonding#HA_Bonding_Mode_Selection_for_Multiple_Switch_Topology\"><font color=\"#800080\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">10.2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">HA Bonding Mode Selection for Multiple Switch Topology</span></font></a> </li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table></p>','The Linux bonding Driver provides a method for aggregating multiple Logical Network Interfaces into a single bonded interface. The behavior of the bonded Interfaces depends upon the mode; generally speaking, modes provide either STANDBY or load Balancing Services Hot. Additionally, Link Integrity...'),(314,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/e9/2007.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Dual NIC teaming under linux as5 technical implementation details','Dual_NIC_teaming_under_linux_as5_technical_implementation_details','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">The so-called bonding, is bound to multiple network cards to provide services outside the same IP address, can achieve high availability or load balancing. Of course, two network cards directly to the same IP address setting is not possible. Through bonding, to provide connectivity outside the virtual piece of card, the physical card is modified to the same MAC address. Kernels 2.4.12 and later versions provide a bonding module, the previous version can be achieved through the patch.</font> </p><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1: First see if linux supports bonding, RHEL4 has been supported by default. (Most distributions support)</font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"># Modinfo bonding</font> </div><div></div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">filename: / lib/modules/2.6.18-8.el5/kernel/drivers/net/bonding/bonding.ko <br /> author: Thomas Davis, tadavis@lbl.gov and many others <br /> description: Ethernet Channel Bonding Driver, v3.0.3 <br /> version: 3.0.3 <br /> license: GPL <br /> srcversion: 2547D22885C2FDF28EF7D98 <br /></font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If you have similar information on the above output, that has supported.</font> </div><div></div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If not, that kernel does not support bonding, need to recompile the kernel</font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Steps to compile the kernel here is not to write, and in the make menuconfig inside</font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Bonding driver support such a find dialog box, select it.</font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If the module is compiled, but also need to mount the module. Mount bonding method of the module;</font> <div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ localhost #] modprobe bonding</font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If / sbin / ifenslave not, we also need to compile it out alone <br /> [Root @ lin: / home / beinan #] cd / usr/src/linux-2.6.20/Documentation/networking <br /> [Root @ lin: / home / networking #] gcc-Wall-Wstrict-prototypes-O -I/usr/src/linux-2.6.20/include ifenslave.c-o ifenslave</font> </div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ lin: / home / networking #] cp ifenslave / sbin / ifenslave</font> </div></div></div><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">2. Make sure you are using the card, check / etc / sysconfig / network-scripts directory in the file ifcfg-start, should be eth0, eth1 ...</font> </p><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">3. Bond0 configure virtual network card</font> </p><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">NIC Initiation Protocol, you can use DHCP, you can configure static IP, where I tested the static, dhcp, none found no difference, the best edit the configuration file through vi</font> </p><center><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ server1 ~] # cd / etc / sysconfig / network-scripts\r\n[Root @ server1 network-scripts] # cat ifcfg-bond0\r\nDEVICE = bond0\r\nBOOTPROTO = none\r\nONBOOT = yes\r\nNETWORK = 192.168.0.0\r\nNETMASK = 255.255.255.0\r\nIPADDR = 192.168.0.10\r\nUSERCTL = no\r\nGATEWAY = 192.168.0.254\r\nTYPE = Ethernet</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></center><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">4. Modify eth0, eth1 configuration file</font> </p><center><table align=\"center\" border=\"1\" bordercolordark=\"#ffffff\" bordercolorlight=\"#000000\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"400\"><tbody><tr><td bgcolor=\"#e6e6e6\" class=\"code\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 9pt\"><pre> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">[Root @ server1 network-scripts] # ifcfg-eth0\r\nDEVICE = eth0\r\nBOOTPROTO = none\r\nONBOOT = yes\r\nMASTER = bond0\r\nSLAVE = yes\r\nUSERCTL = yes\r\n[Root @ server1 network-scripts] # ifcfg-eth1\r\nDEVICE = eth1\r\nBOOTPROTO = none\r\nONBOOT = yes\r\nMASTER = bond0\r\nSLAVE = yes\r\nUSERCTL = yes</font> </pre></td></tr></tbody></table></center><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">5. Bond0 device will add the newly added in modprobe.conf for kernel identification. Add to set parameters, miimon value indicates the time two network cards to monitor each other to ms units. mode is working mode can be set to high availability or load balancing, high availability 0 (default), 1 for load balancing, while there is a XOR mode.</font> </p><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">alias bond0 bonding</font> </p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://bbs.ixdba.net\">IXDBA.NET Community Forums</a></font></strong> <br /></font> <p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">options bond0 miimon = 100 mode = 1</font> </p><p style=\"TEXT-INDENT: 2em\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Description: miimon is used for link monitoring. For example: miimon = 100, then the system once every 100ms link connection status monitoring, if there is a line unreasonable to turn to another line; mode of the value of that mode, his total 0,1,2,3 four modes used Two for the 0,1. <br /> mode = 0 that load balancing (round-robin) mode for the load balancing, two network cards are working. <br /> mode = 1, said fault-tolerance (active-backup) to provide redundancy, work is the main preparation work, that is by default only one network card working, the other for backup. <br /> bonding can only provide the link monitoring, that is, the link from the host is connected to the switch. If you just switch off the external link down, but the switch itself does not malfunction, then the bonding would think that there is no problem and continue to use the link.</font> </p><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Should be noted that if you want to make load balancing, just to set this options bond0 miimon = 100 mode = 0 is not enough, also need to set the switch port.</font> </div><div></div><div> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In principle an analysis (bond under running mode 0): <br /> mode 0 bond is bound under the network card IP have been modified to the same mac address, if these cards are connected to the same switch, then switch the mac address arp table have the corresponding port number, then the switch sent to the mac address of received packet should be forwarded to which port it? Under normal circumstances mac address is globally unique, a mac address to make sure the switch port corresponds to many confused. <br /> Therefore, under the bond if mode0 connected to the switch, the switch port should take these polymerization (cisco called ethernetchannel, foundry called portgroup), as did the switch after polymerization, the polymerization was also under several ports bundled into a mac address.</font> </div>','The so-called bonding, is bound to multiple network cards to provide services outside the same IP address, can achieve high availability or load balancing. Of course, two network cards directly to the same IP address setting is not possible. Through bonding, to provide connectivity outside the...'),(315,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/0d/2006.html','http://www.ixdba.net','NIC teaming under Linux as a dual-NIC load balancing and fail-safe','NIC_teaming_under_Linux_as_a_dualNIC_load_balancing_and_failsafe','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Linux is described in this dual NIC teaming is to use two network cards to achieve to become a virtual network adapter, this device appears to be aggregated together in a separate Ethernet interface device, popular speak is the two cards have the same IP address and parallel links as a logical link aggregate work. In fact, this</font> <script language=\"javascript\" src=\"/CMS/JS/newsad.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Sun and Cisco technology has long existed, known as Trunking and Etherchannel technology in the 2.4.x Linux kernel that this technology is also used, known as bonding. The earliest application of bonding technology in the cluster - beowulf, in order to improve the data transmission between the cluster nodes designed. Here we discuss the principle of bonding and what is needed from the NIC bonding hybrid (promisc) mode start. We know that in normal circumstances, the purpose of receiving only the hardware address of network card (MAC Address) is a self-Mac\'s Ethernet frame, for the other data frames are filtered to reduce the burden on the driver. But the card also supports another mode called mixed promisc, can receive all frames on the network, such as tcpdump, is running in this mode. bonding is also running in this mode, the driver and modify the mac address of the Mac address of the two into the same card, can receive a specific mac data frame. Then the corresponding data frames transmitted to the bond-driven procedures. <br /><br /> Theory that a long time, in fact, very simple configuration, a total of four steps: <br /><br /> Experimental operating system is Redhat Linux Enterprise 3.0 <br /> Prerequisite for binding: the same chipset model, and network card should have its own independent BIOS chip.</font> </p><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Dual NIC bonding topology (see figure below)</font> </p><p><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"/hbcms/upload/image/big/e4/e418c8c67789442f4a88c5d57820a841.gif\" /><br /></p><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></p><p><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1. Edit the virtual network interface configuration file, specify the LAN IP <br /> vi / etc / sysconfig / network-scripts / ifcfg-bond0 <br /> [Root @ rhas-13 root] # cp / etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-eth0 ifcfg-bond0 <br /> 2 # vi ifcfg-bond0 <br /> The first line will change DEVICE = bond0 <br /> # Cat ifcfg-bond0 <br /> DEVICE = bond0 <br /> BOOTPROTO = static <br /> IPADDR = 172.31.0.13 <br /> NETMASK = 255.255.252.0 <br /> BROADCAST = 172.31.3.254 <br /> ONBOOT = yes <br /> TYPE = Ethernet <br /> To mind here, do not specify a single network card IP address, subnet mask or network card ID. This information will be assigned to the virtual adapter (bonding) can be. <br /> [Root @ rhas-13 network-scripts] # cat ifcfg-eth0 <br /> DEVICE = eth0 <br /> ONBOOT = yes <br /> BOOTPROTO = dhcp <br /> [Root @ rhas-13 network-scripts] # cat ifcfg-eth1 <br /> DEVICE = eth0 <br /> ONBOOT = yes <br /> BOOTPROTO = dhcp</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">3 # vi / etc / modules.conf <br /> Edit / etc / modules.conf file and add the following line to enable the system load the bonding module at boot time, external virtual network interface device for the bond0 <br /><br /> Add the following two lines <br /> alias bond0 bonding <br /> options bond0 miimon = 100 mode = 1 <br /> Description: miimon is used for link monitoring. For example: miimon = 100, then the system once every 100ms link connection status monitoring, if there is a line unreasonable to turn to another line; mode of the value of that mode, his total 0,1,2,3 four modes used Two for the 0,1. <br /> mode = 0 that load balancing (round-robin) mode for the load balancing, two network cards are working. <br /> mode = 1, said fault-tolerance (active-backup) to provide redundancy, work is the main preparation work, that is by default only one network card working, the other for backup. <br /> bonding can only provide the link monitoring, that is, the link from the host is connected to the switch. If you just switch off the external link down, but the switch itself does not malfunction, then the bonding would think that there is no problem and continue to use the link <br /> 4 # vi / etc / rc.d / rc.local <br /> Add two lines <br /> ifenslave bond0 eth0 eth1 <br /> route add-net 172.31.3.254 netmask 255.255.255.0 bond0</font> </p>','Linux is described in this dual NIC teaming is to use two network cards to achieve to become a virtual network adapter, this device appears to be aggregated together in a separate Ethernet interface device, popular speak is the two cards have the same IP address and parallel links as a logical link...'),(316,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/3a/1961.html','http://www.ixdba.net','nginx load balancing and php simple tutorial to explain','nginx_load_balancing_and_php_simple_tutorial_to_explain','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> Download <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">wget</font> http://sysoev.ru/nginx/nginx-0.5.35.tar.gz <br /> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Decompression after the installation to / usr / local / nginx <br /> . / Configure - with-http_ssl_module - with-http_realip_module - with-http_addition_module - with-http_sub_module - with-http_dav_module - with-http_flv_module - with-http_stub_status_module - prefix = / usr / local / nginx <br /> make <br /> make install <br /><br /> Create users, create web root directory <br /> useradd-d / dev / null-s / sbin / nologin www <br /> cd / <br /> mkdir web <br /> cd web <br /> mkdir htdocs <br /> cd / <br /> chown-R www: www web <br /> cd / usr / local / nginx <br /> mkdir var <br /> cd .. <br /> chown-R www: www nginx <br /> cd nginx <br /><br /> Configuration nginx.conf <br /> vi / usr / local / nginx / conf / nginx.conf <br /> Examples for the content of <br /> user www www; <br /> worker_processes 2; <br /> error_log / usr / local / nginx / logs / error.log; <br /> pid / usr / local / nginx / var / nginx.pid; <br /> worker_rlimit_nofile 51200; <br /> events <br /> { <br /> use epoll; <br /> worker_connections 51200; <br /> } <br /> http <br /> { <br /> include conf / mime.types; <br /> default_type application / octet-stream; <br /> log_format main \'$ remote_addr $ remote_user - [$ time_local] &quot;$ request&quot;\' <br /> \'$ Status $ body_bytes_sent &quot;$ http_referer&quot;\' <br /> \'&quot;$ Http_user_agent&quot;\'; <br /> access_log / usr / local / nginx / logs / access.log main; <br /><br /> keepalive_timeout 30; <br /><br /> tcp_nopush on; <br /> tcp_nodelay off; <br /><br /> upstream test { <br /> server 127.0.0.1:81 fail_timeout = 60; <br /> server 127.0.0.1:82 fail_timeout = 60; <br /> } <br /><br /> limit_zone httplimit $ binary_remote_addr 10m; <br /> server <br /> { <br /> listen 80; <br /> client_max_body_size 50M; <br /> server_name www.2tutu.com 192.168.1.33; <br /> index index.php index.htm index.html; <br /> root / web / htdocs; <br /> limit_conn httplimit 8;</font> </p>',' Download wget http://sysoev.ru/nginx/nginx-0.5.35.tar.gz  Decompression after the installation to / usr / local / nginx  . / Configure - with-http_ssl_module - with-http_realip_module - with-http_addition_module - with-http_sub_module - with-http_dav_module - with-http_flv_module -...'),(317,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/42/1913.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Red Hat cluster (Cluster) package introduced','Red_Hat_cluster_Cluster_package_introduced','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<div id=\"Content\" onselectstart=\"return false;\" style=\"OVERFLOW: hidden; WORD-BREAK: break-all; WORD-WRAP: break-word\"><div> <font color=\"#000000\" size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\">Red Hat Cluster Suite is able to provide a high performance, high reliability, load balancing, high availability clusters and relatively cheap tool set.</font></font> <p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">A cluster usually has two or more computers (called &quot;nodes&quot; or &quot;members&quot;) jointly perform a task. There are four common clusters:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Storage Cluster</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* High Availability Cluster</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Load balancing</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* High Performance Cluster</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Storage Cluster for service in a cluster to provide a consistent file system image, allowing the service to read and write while a single shared file system. Through the data storage cluster file system into a shared application eliminates the trouble of copying data between, and provide a single point of backup and recovery. Red Hat Cluster Suite provides a through Red Hat GFS storage cluster.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">High availability by eliminating single point of failure cluster and node failover (when a cluster node fails after the service to other nodes) to provide high availability. Node failover functionality is transparent to the client when the client node failure and will not see the transfer of services between nodes. Red Hat Cluster Suite components through high-availability service management to provide a high availability cluster.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Load balancing cluster will service request dispatched to multiple nodes in the cluster. Is a low-cost load balancing, high availability clusters, because you can load flexibility to add and remove nodes. In the load balancing cluster when a node fails, the scheduler will find that this failure and to stop sending requests to this node. Node failure is transparent to the client. Red Hat Cluster Suite through LVS (Linux Virtual Server) to provide load balancing cluster.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">High-performance cluster nodes to perform parallel computing. High-performance parallel computing cluster allows applications to improve application performance.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">RHCS are the following components:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Cluster architecture - to provide a basic function to work together as a cluster node: configuration file management, membership management, lock management, and grid equipment.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* High-availability Service Management - provides node failover service, when a node fails after the service to another node.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Cluster Management tools - through the configuration and management tools to configure and manage Red Hat cluster.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Linux Virtual Server (LVS) - LVS to provide a load balancing based on IP, through the LVS client requests can be evenly distributed to cluster nodes.</font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">You can add the following Red Hat Cluster components:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Red Hat GFS (Global File System) - GFS for the Red Hat Cluster Suite provides a cluster file system, CFS allows multiple nodes to share at the block level storage.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Cluster Logical Volume Manager (CLVM) - to provide logical volume management of cluster storage.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Global Network Block Device (GNBD) - GFS a complementary component is stored in the block level for export to Ethernet.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static5.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441641944ea04\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Red Hat Cluster Suite Introduction</font> </p><p> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Red Hat Cluster describes</font></strong> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1, cluster management</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CMAN (cluster manager) in the Red Hat Cluster Suite to perform cluster management tasks. CMAN is a distributed cluster manager that runs on each cluster node.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net\"><strong>www.ixdba.net</strong></a></font> </p><br /><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CMAN cluster nodes by monitoring the number of nodes to provide a statutory (quorum), when half of the cluster nodes are redundant in an active state that there is a statutory number of nodes, when there are half or less than half of the nodes in the active state is not with a statutory number of nodes, the cluster becomes unavailable at this time.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CMAN node by monitoring the members of the node to understand the relationship, when the cluster membership change, CMAN notice the underlying structure of an adjustment accordingly.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static5.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441641959e584\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CMAN / DLM Overview</font> </p><p> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">2, the lock manager</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Lock management is a common infrastructure, on the other cluster structure to provide a mechanism for shared cluster resources. In the Red Hat cluster DLM is a distributed lock manager, it runs on all cluster nodes. GFS and CLVM through the lock manager to use the lock. GFS uses a lock through lock manager mechanism to synchronize access to the file system metadata. CLVM through the lock manager to synchronize updates to LVM volumes and volumes of data groups.</font> </p><p><br /> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">3, the gate device (Fencing)</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Through the gate device can be disconnected from a shared storage cluster nodes. Cut off from the shared memory gate device I / O to ensure data integrity. When CMAN identify a node fails, it notices that the cluster structure of the failed node, fenced process will isolate the failed node to ensure that failure does not undermine the shared data nodes. Fenced running on each node.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Red Hat Cluster Suite to provide centralized isolation following ways:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Power grid devices</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Fibre Channel-gate devices</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* GNBD gate</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Other gate devices</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Gate device instance</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">When the A gate process found on the D node failure, it is through the gate agent informed the power controller D node isolation.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static6.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416419563865\" /></font> </p><p align<html> = &quot;Center&quot;&gt; <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">instance of the power grid equipment</font> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">When the A gate process found on the D node failure, it is informed by the gate agent D Fibre Channel switch device node isolation.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static7.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441641959fcc6\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Fibre Channel switch gate device instance</font> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">4, the cluster configuration system</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Cluster Configuration System (CCS) manages the cluster configuration and cluster structure provides for other configuration information. CCS runs in each node and to ensure that each node in the cluster configuration file is the latest. For example, if an administrator to update the configuration file node A, CCS is responsible for dissemination of updates to other nodes.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static10.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441641961f329\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CCS Overview</font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Other cluster components (such as CMAN) access through the CCS configuration information from the configuration file.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static13.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441641968718c\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Access to configuration information</font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Cluster configuration file (/ etc / cluster / cluster.conf) is an XML file, used to describe the following cluster features:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Cluster Name - lists the cluster name, cluster configuration file version, and a period of segregation, isolation, the corresponding time when a new node joins or isolation from the cluster.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Clusters - List each node in the cluster, specify the node name, node ID, the number of legal votes, and the gate pattern.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Gate equipment - definition of grid equipment.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Management of resources - the definition of the resources required to create cluster services. Management of resources, including failover domains, resources (such as IP) and services.</font> </p><p><br /> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">5, high-availability service management</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">High-availability service management provides a way to create high-availability cluster services. rgmanager running on each cluster node. When a node fails, high-availability cluster service can fail from one node to other nodes, and this transfer is transparent to the client.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">You can configure the cluster configuration file, a high-availability cluster service. Cluster service includes cluster resources (such as a IP address, an application initialization script, Red Hat GFS shared file system, etc.).</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">You can add a cluster service and the combination of a failed transfer of the domain. A failover domain is a specific service to run a subset of cluster nodes. In a failover domain can be specified for each node a priority level to determine when a failure occurs in the service node transfer order. If you do not specify a priority, the cluster service can failover between nodes of any transfer of the domain. You can also limit the transfer of a service failure only in the inter-domain transfer.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Here is an example of a failed transfer of the domain composition of the nodes A and B, and configure a limit, when node A fails, the service can only be transferred to the Node B X on. Failover domain 2 from the node B, C and D components, and configure a limit, C the priority is set to 1, B the priority is set to 2, D is set to 3 priority, when the C node fails, the service Y trying to transfer to B, if unsuccessful, then transferred to D. 3 is configured to transfer the domain failure without priority, unlimited, where the node if the service fails it will attempt to Z transferred to other nodes, the nodes are not valid when the domain when the service transferred to other nodes in the cluster.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static9.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416419662578\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Transfer the domain failure</font> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">The following is an example of a high-availability cluster, one is called &quot;content-webserver&quot;.\'s Service runs on node B, there is a failover domain, including nodes A, B and D. Another failure of a priority transfer domain configuration, D higher priority than A, and set limits. This service contains the following cluster resources:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* IP address resources - IP address of 10.10.10.201.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Application Resources &quot;httpd-content&quot; - a Web service program initialization script / etc / init.d / httpd.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* File system resources - GFS name is: &quot;gfs-content-webserver&quot;.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static4.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416419736c13\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Web Server Cluster Service Example</font> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Client access to web services via 10.10.10.201, httpd-content application data into gfs-content-webserver file system.</font> </p><p><br /> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">6, Red Hat GFS</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GFS for the Red Hat Cluster Suite provides a cluster file system that allows multiple nodes to share in the block-level storage. GFS uses a distributed metadata and multiple Subscriptions (multiple journals), GFS is an ideal cluster file system. To ensure file system integrity, GFS uses a lock manager to manage the I / O. When a node, modify the data in the GFS, the changes can immediately use this file in other system nodes visible.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Nodes running Red Hat GFS Red Hat Cluster Suite can be configured through the management tool to manage. For volume management through CLVM. Between the nodes in the cluster GFS provides data sharing.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static7.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441643195f5b6\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GFS with a SAN</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static1.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441643197a0a0\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"><html> face = &quot;Verdana&quot; size = &quot;2&quot;&gt; GFS and GNBD with a SAN </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static13.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416431ad9a2c\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GFS and GNBD with Directly Connected Storage</font> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">7, Cluster Logical Volume Manager</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CLVM in a single node to provide the same performance with LVM2, but it can be used by all cluster nodes to create the volume available. Logical volume created by CLVM can be used for all the cluster nodes.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">clvmd provide a standard tool for LVM2 cluster expanded to allow the use LVM2 tools to manage shared storage. clvmd running on each cluster node, distributed in the cluster can be updated metadata to other nodes to see a consistent logical view.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static9.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416431a8c378\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">CLVM Overview</font> </p><p><br /> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">8, Global Network Block Device (GNBD)</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Global Network Block Device (GNBD) provided by TCP / IP access to Red Hat GFS method. GNBD consists of two main parts: a GNBD client, a GNBD server. GNBD server is used to export local storage. GNBD client runs on the node using GFS, import export from GNBD server disk devices. Multiple clients can simultaneously access a disk device GNBD server exported.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static16.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416431a6f19f\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">GNBD Overview</font> </p><p><br /> <strong><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">9, Linux Virtual Server</font></strong> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Linux Virtual Server (LVS) is a complete IP-based load balancing cluster software. LVS runs on a pair of similarly configured computers: one as the active LVS Router, one as a backup LVS Router. Activities LVS Router service has two roles:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Balancing the load to the real server.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Check the actual services provided by the server is normal.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Backup LVS Router used to monitor the activities of LVS Router, to prepare for the activities of LVS Router fails, taken over by the backup LVS Router.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static6.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416431b43b55\" /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">LVS Cluster</font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Pulse process runs in the active LVS Router and backup LVS Router on. On the backup LVS Router, pulse sends a heartbeat (heartbeat) to the active LVS Router\'s public network interface to check the activities of LVS Router is normal. On the active LVS Router, pulse start lvs process and respond to the backup LVS Router from the heart.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">lvs process calls the ipvsadm tool to configure and maintain the IPVS routing table, and for each virtual server in the real service starts a nanny process. Each nanny process to check the real state of virtual service on the server, and failure to inform the lvs process. If a fault is found, lvs process notice ipcsadm IPVS routing table in this server to delete.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If the backup LVS Router does not receive active LVS Router from the response, it calls the virtual IP address send_arp redistribution to the backup LVS Router\'s public network interface. And in the public network interface and LAN interface to send a command to turn off the respective activities of LVS Router on lvs process. At the same time to start the process of scheduling their own lvs client requests.</font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Here is a two-tier structure of the LVS framework:</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static12.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416431b276db\" /></font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Here is a three-tier structure of the LVS framework:</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static16.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e214416431c53abf\" /></font> </p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Ã‚Â </font></p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Two-tier structure of the LVS framework for data changes on the Real Server is not very frequent, and if data changes on the Real Server very frequent use of three-tier structure should be considered LVS architecture, the data into a shared file system (GFS) for reference by all of the Real Server while reading and writing.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">You can use the VS / NAT, and VS / DR to achieve IP load balancing:</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Use the VS / NAT methods: customers through the Virtual IP Address (the IP address of the virtual services) access to network services, the request message to reach the scheduler, the scheduler connection scheduling algorithm based on the real server from a group selected a server, will be reported text rewrite the destination address Virtual IP Address The address of the selected server, rewrite the destination port of packets corresponding to the selected server, port, and finally the modified packets sent to the selected server. Meanwhile, the scheduler records in connection Hash table this connection, when the connection to the next packet arrives, from the connection of the original Hash tables can be selected in the server address and port, the same rewriting operation, and packets passed to the original selected server. When the server response from real packets through the scheduler, the scheduler the packet source address and source port to the appropriate Virtual IP Address and port, then the message to the user. When using the VS / NAT method, if a large number of response data through the scheduler, the scheduler will become the bottleneck of the whole cluster.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static10.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441643ca4b019\" /></font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">* Use the VS / DR Methods: scheduler and server group must have a network card in the physical break through, regardless of the LAN connected, such as through switches or high-speed HUB connected. VIP address for the dispatcher and the server group shared, the scheduler is configured VIP address the visibility of, for receiving the virtual service request packets; all the VIP address of the server configuration in their Non-ARP network devices, it is not visible outside, but the destination address for processing requests for the VIP network. In the VS / DR, the scheduler of each server based on load, dynamically select a server, without modifying the IP packet is not encapsulated, but the data frame\'s MAC address to MAC address of the server selected, then The revised data frame in the LAN with the server group to send. MAC address because the data frame is selected server, the server must be able to receive the data frame, from which you can obtain the IP packet. When the server found that VIP packet destination address is on the local network device, server processing this message, then the response packet routing table directly back to the customer.</font> </p><p align=\"center\">r = &quot;# 000000&quot; face = &quot;Verdana&quot; size = &quot;2&quot;&gt; <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static5.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441643cc2c734\" /></p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>10, cluster management tools</strong></font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Red Hat Cluster Suite provides a variety of cluster configuration and management tools, such as the Conga, Cluster Administration GUI and command line-based management tools.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Conga is a Web-based management tool, it provides a centralized management of Red Hat cluster and storage management platform. It is mainly composed of two parts luci and ricci, ricci which run in each cluster node, luci installed on a computer used to manage the cluster. Luci ricci and through communication nodes in the cluster.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">system-config-cluster is a cluster node for configuring and managing a graphical management tool. It has two cluster configuration and cluster management tab, used to complete the appropriate configuration and management.</font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static16.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441643cd1c18f\" /></font> </p><p><br /> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">ccs_tool, cman_tool, fence_tool, clustat, clusvcadm are several command-line tool, details, please read the corresponding man page.</font> </p><p> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Piranha is a web-based page for the LVS cluster configuration and management of graphical tools. <br /></font> </p><p align=\"center\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://static7.photo.sina.com.cn/bmiddle/4e424e21441643ccde266\" /></font> <script id=\"PVCOUNTER_FORIE\" src=\"http://counter.sina.com.cn/pvcounter?pid=1&key=4e424e2101007qpm&url=http%3A%2F%2Fblog.sina.com.cn%2Fs%2Fblog_4e424e2101007qpm.html\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><script src=\"http://news.sina.com.cn/pvcounter/pvcounter.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><script src=\"http://sina.wrating.com/a1.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script></p></div></div><div style=\"DISPLAY: none\"> <font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"1\" id=\"wrTagImage\" src=\"http://sina.wrating.com/a.gif?a=11a774bc300&t=&i=-18ea10295.11a4e87d691.0.712a7803c045f&b=http%3A//blog.sina.com.cn/s/reader_4e424e2101007qpm.html&c=860010-0328010000&s=1280x800x32&l=zh-cn&z=8&j=1&f=9.0&r=http%3A//www.google.cn/search%3Fhl%3Dzh-CN%26q%3DRed+Hat%25E9%259B%2586%25E7%25BE%25A4%2528Cluster%2529%25E5%25A5%2597%25E4%25BB%25B6%26btnG%3DGoogle+%25E6%2590%259C%25E7%25B4%25A2%26meta%3D%26aq%3Df&js=&ck=1\" width=\"1\" /></font> </div><script type=\"text/javascript\">\r\ntry{\r\nvar vjAcc=\"860010-0328010000\"; \r\nvar wrUrl=\"http://sina.wrating.com/\";\r\nvjTrack(\"\");\r\n}catch(e){};\r\n</script><noscript></noscript>','A cluster usually has two or more computers (called \"nodes\" or \"members\") jointly perform a task. There are four common...'),(318,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/9b/1911.html','http://www.ixdba.net','redhat linux installation diary under the GFS and RHCS','redhat_linux_installation_diary_under_the_GFS_and_RHCS','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<div class=\"t_msgfont\" id=\"message5913457\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><br /> Hardware: Dual AMD 275HE dual-core CPU/4G Memory / 73G scsi <br /> Operating System: RedHat AS 4 update 2 <br /> Kernel version :2.6.9-22. ELsmp <br /><br /> 1. To the appropriate site to download redhat Cluster Suite / GFS software. In the absence of registration number, you can not up2date upgrade, so it would be more trouble. <br /> Download the appropriate RHCS to ftp://ftp.redhat.com/pub/redhat/linux/updates/enterprise/4AS/en/ and RHGFS the src.rpm file in a directory, often several versions of the same software exist. Following installation of the software used in the notes is RHAS4 U2 prevail. <br /> 1.1 install cman-kernel-2.6.9-39.5.src.rpm <br /> rpm-iv cman-kernel-2.6.9-39.5.src.rpm <br /> cd / usr / src / redhat / SPECS <br /> rpmbuild-ba - nodeps cman-kernel.spec # add - nodeps because of tips, kernel-hugemem-devel = 2.6.9-22.EL is needed, try to resolve unsuccessful, give up. Hope not a problem. <br /> cd / usr/src/redhat/RPMS/x86_64 / <br /> rpm-ivh cman-ker * <br /><br /> 1.2 Installation magma-1.0.1-4.src.rpm <br /> rpm-iv magma-1.0.1-4.src.rpm <br /> cd / usr / src / redhat / SPECS <br /> rpmbuild-ba magma.spec <br /> cd / usr/src/redhat/RPMS/x86_64 / <br /> rpm-ivh magma * <br /><br /> 1.3 Installation dlm-kernel-2.6.9-37.7.src.rpm <br /> rpm-iv dlm-kernel-2.6.9-37.7.src.rpm <br /> cd / usr / src / redhat / SPECS <br /> rpmbuild-ba - nodeps dlm-kernel.spec <br /> cd / usr/src/redhat/RPMS/x86_64 / <br /> rpm-ivh dlm-kern * <br /><br /> 1.4 Installation dlm-1.0.0-5.src.rpm <br /> rpm-iv dlm-1.0.0-5.src.rpm <br /> cd / usr / src / redhat / SPECS <br /> rpmbuild-ba dlm.spec <br /> cd / usr/src/redhat/RPMS/x86_64 / <br /> rpm-ivh - nodeps dlm-1.0.0-5.x86_64.rpm <br /> rpm-ivh dlm-debuginfo-1.0.0-5.x86_64.rpm <br /> rpm-ivh dlm-devel-1.0.0-5.x86_64.rpm <br /><br /> 1.5 install ccs-1.0.2-0.src.rpm <br /> rpm-iv ccs-1.0.2-0.src.rpm <br /> cd / usr / src / redhat / SPECS</font> </div><br /><br /><center> <b><font color=\"red\">Read more:</font> <font color=\"red\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">1</font></b> <a href=\"/article/9b/1911$2.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">2</a> * <a href=\"/article/9b/1911$3.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">3</a> * <a href=\"/article/9b/1911$4.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">4</a> * <a href=\"/article/9b/1911$5.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">5</a> * <a href=\"/article/9b/1911$6.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">6</a> * <a href=\"/article/9b/1911$2.html\" Ã£ÂƒÂ»=\"Ã£ÂƒÂ»\">Next&gt;&gt;</a> </center><br />','empty\n'),(319,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/23/1874.html','http://www.ixdba.net','oracle rac basic daily maintenance of order','oracle_rac_basic_daily_maintenance_of_order','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">The status of all instances and services</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"></span></strong> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">$ Srvctl status database-d orcl <br /> Instance orcl1 is running on node linux1 <br /> Instance orcl2 is running on node linux2 <br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /></span> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">The state of a single instance</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"></span></strong> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">$ Srvctl status instance-d orcl-i orcl2 <br /> Instance orcl2 is running on node linux2 <br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /></span> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">In the database the state of the global naming service</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"></span></strong> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">$ Srvctl status service-d orcl-s orcltest <br /> Service orcltest is running on instance (s) orcl2, orcl1 <br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /></span> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">Node, node-specific state of the application</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"></span></strong> </p> <strong><font color=\"#ecf4f5\" face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><a href=\"http://bbs.ixdba.net\">IXDBA.NET Community Forums</a></font></strong> <br /><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">$</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: blue; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\">Srvctl status nodeapps-n linux1</strong></span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"><br /> VIP is running on node: linux1 <br /> GSD is running on node: linux1 <br /> Listener is running on node: linux1 <br /> ONS dae</span><html> mon is running on node: linux1 <br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /></p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">The status of</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">ASM</span> <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">instance</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\"></span></strong> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">$ Srvctl status asm-n linux1 <br /> ASM instance + ASM1 is running on node linux1. <br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\" /></span> </p><p align=\"left\" class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 16.75pt; TEXT-ALIGN: left; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto\"> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-bidi-font-family: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana; mso-font-kerning: 0pt\">List all configured databases</span> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: red; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana; mso-bidi-font-fa