g to Google, and its annual cash flow can be increased by 25% or more.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">The source said Yahoo will check with Google as an important means of Microsoft\'s acquisition. Of course, Yahoo also hopes to introduce a company with Microsoft\'s bid, thereby increasing the difficulty of Microsoft\'s acquisition. It is said that Yahoo has been in recent weeks to negotiate with Google, hoping to outsource Web search advertising in Europe to the latter. While Microsoft has submitted a bid, but Yahoo and Google will continue the negotiations.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Clearly, Google is also interested in taking over Yahoo\'s search advertising business. According to sources, Google CEO Eric Schmidt (Eric Schmidt) on Friday call Yahoo CEO Jerry Yang specifically, I hope to provide assistance for Yahoo against Microsoft\'s &quot;hostile&quot; takeover. Google directly is almost no possibility of acquisition of Yahoo because the two companies accounted for Web search and advertising market share in the vast majority of such transactions can not antitrust regulatory approval. But antitrust experts say, even if Google and Yahoo in search advertising options business cooperation will be met with opposition from regulators.</font> </p><p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Anti-monopoly is double-edged sword</font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">According to market research firm eMarketer released the latest data, Google in 2007 accounted for 71% of U.S. search advertising revenue, Yahoo, followed by the proportion accounted for 8.9%. In the entire U.S. online advertising market, Google accounted for 28% of the share, Yahoo is still followed, accounting for 15.4% of the market. According to data released by Nielsen NetRatings, Google last December in the U.S. Web search market share accounted for 56.3%, while Yahoo accounted for 17.7%, Microsoft accounted for 13.8%.</font> </p><p> <font f