\"t_msgfont\"><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></div><div class=\"t_msgfont\"><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></div><div class=\"t_msgfont\"><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></div><div class=\"t_msgfont\"><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></div><div class=\"t_msgfont\"><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></div><div class=\"t_msgfont\"><div class=\"t_msgfont\" id=\"postmessage_384123\"> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In the windows environment, the basic need iSCSI cards, and now most of the servers have a TOE function. But in Linux environment, recommend the use of iSCSI cards, because Linux will be more under the Initiator-consuming CPU resources, it is heavier in the case of IO use iSCSI HBA card.</font> </div></div></div></div></div></div>','empty\n'),(376,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/d5/1206.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Storage Q &amp; A: How to create a hot backup AIX 5.1 (hot spare) disk?','Storage_Q_amp_A_How_to_create_a_hot_backup_AIX_51_hot_spare_disk','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <strong><font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"></font></strong> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In the AIX 5.1 operating system can create a hot spare disk level.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">If required, in a volume group (VG) to create hot spare disk, you must meet the following conditions:</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1. Logical volume (LV) in this group must be mirrored volume (mirror).</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">2. As a hot spare disk can not have any logical volume or file system.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">3. Hot spare disk capacity should be greater than or equal to this volume group, the maximum disk capacity.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">When the meet the above conditions, use the following steps (assuming volume group here called testvg, the disk is hdisk6):</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">1. # Exptendvg testvg hdisk6</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Volume group will be joined hdisk6 testvg.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">2. # Chpv-hy hdisk6</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Will be marked as hot spare disk hdisk6.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">3. # Chvg-hy-sy testvg</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Will be marked for the use of hot spare testvg disk volume group, and when failure occurs automatically when the disk replace the disk and synchronize.</font> </p>','empty\n'),(377,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/70/1205.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Storage Q &amp; A: Redhat disk array mapping not recognized','Storage_Q_amp_A_Redhat_disk_array_mapping_not_recognized','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\"><strong>Q: I have a channel on the disk array mapping of the two partitions, the result of the system in Redhat 9, through the fdisk / dev / sda can edit, but fdisk / dev / sdb the second is no, why?</strong></font> </p><p> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong>Answer:</strong> 1) uname-a to get your linux kernel version, such as :2.4.18-3 <br /> 2) Make a Linux recovery disk before doing any updates are a good idea, you can use this command to create recovery disk: <br /> / Sbin / mkbootdisk &lt;your kernel version here&gt; \' <br /> For example, / sbin / mkbootdisk 2.4.18-3 <br /> 3) In the / etc / modules.conf in the last line add options scsi_mod max_scsi_luns = 255 <br /> 4) To make this change take effect, you must re-create your initrid boot image. First, put your saved as another name for the original, <br /> \'Cp / boot/initrd- &lt;kernel version&gt;. Img / boot/initrd- &lt;kernel version&gt;. Old\'. <br /> 5) Now, create a new initrd image, you can enter: <br /> \'Mkinitrd-f / boot/initrd- &lt;kernel version&gt;. Img &lt;kernel version&gt;\'. <br /> Example: mkinitrd-f / boot/initrd-2.4.21-15.EL.img 2.4.21-15.EL <br /> 6) If you GRUB as your boot loader, you only have to restart it. You can then load the SCSI card driver to see multiple LUN was. <br /> 7) If you use LILO, you want to run lilo and reboot the system. <br /> 8) If the system can not start properly, use the recovery disk and then re-loaded from the original initrd image initrd-&lt;kernel version&gt;. Old. Then if you use GRUB, reboot your system; If you use LILO, run lilo and then reboot.</font></font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">9) command: echo &quot;scsi add-single-device 0 0 0 1&quot;&gt; / proc / scsi / scsi <br /></font> </p>','Q: I have a channel on the disk array mapping of the two partitions, the result of the system in Redhat 9, through the fdisk / dev / sda can edit, but fdisk / dev / sdb the second is no,...'),(378,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/1f/1204.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Multi-controller storage array configuration mode between','Multicontroller_storage_array_configuration_mode_between','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong></strong></font></font> </p><p> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong>Q:</strong> Active / Active and Active / Passive array What is the difference between? Which technology is better?</font></font> </p><p> <font size=\"2\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><strong>A:</strong> The controller has two or more storage array (SCSI, FC, iSCSI and NAS) can be configured as Active / Active mode or Active / Passive mode.</font></font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Active / Passive means that a controller for the active handling I / O requests, and the other is idle, to prepare for the failure of the primary controller is offline or take over its work. The Active / Active configuration will enable two controller nodes to handle I / O requests and to provide redundancy for each other\'s performance.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">Normally, Active / Active storage system includes a battery-backed mirrored cache, the contents of the cache controller is a complete image to another controller, and be able to guarantee its availability. For example, if the Active / Active controllers share the 4GB cache (per controller, 2GB), then the cache can be used to mirror the number of its 50%, that is 2GB.</font> </p><p> <font face=\"Verdana\" size=\"2\">In general, the main controller through to access a specific LUN, so as to maintain cache consistency. Some controllers also allows a controller to respond to any server for the LUN\'s I / O requests. However, the actual I / O is usually specified by a controller to complete. About which way better if you can provide a free controller, the Active / Passive mode configuration will fail to provide a performance advantage can be expected. Many NAS vendors use this model, which is usually referred to as NAS cluster. Active / Active configuration enable the two controllers are active mode, in order to achieve performance under normal operation. However, in failover cases, this pattern will produce the consequences of performance degradation.</font> </p>','empty\n'),(379,'BLOG','BLOG','en','/article/80/287.html','http://www.ixdba.net','VMworld 2007 virtualization ecosystem held','VMworld_2007_virtualization_ecosystem_held','2010-11-12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<html><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt\"> <span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana\"><span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">September</span> 11 to <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">13, sponsored by the</span> VMware VMworld 2007 <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Ã¥Â®Â‹Ã¤Â½Â“; mso-ascii-font-family: Verdana; mso-hansi-font-family: Verdana\">in San Francisco\'s</span> Moscone <span style=\"FONT-SIZE: 